urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.1#CHAPTER I. PREJUDICES OF PHILOSOPHERS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.2#1. The Will to Truth, which is to tempt us to many a hazardous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.3#enterprise, the famous Truthfulness of which all philosophers have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.4#hitherto spoken with respect, what questions has this Will to Truth not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.5#laid before us! What strange, perplexing, questionable questions! It is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.6#already a long story; yet it seems as if it were hardly commenced. Is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.7#it any wonder if we at last grow distrustful, lose patience, and turn
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.8#impatiently away? That this Sphinx teaches us at last to ask questions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.9#ourselves? WHO is it really that puts questions to us here? WHAT really
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.10#is this "Will to Truth" in us? In fact we made a long halt at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.11#question as to the origin of this Will--until at last we came to an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.12#absolute standstill before a yet more fundamental question. We inquired
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.13#about the VALUE of this Will. Granted that we want the truth: WHY NOT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.14#RATHER untruth? And uncertainty? Even ignorance? The problem of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.15#value of truth presented itself before us--or was it we who presented
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.16#ourselves before the problem? Which of us is the Oedipus here? Which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.17#the Sphinx? It would seem to be a rendezvous of questions and notes of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.18#interrogation. And could it be believed that it at last seems to us as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.19#if the problem had never been propounded before, as if we were the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.20#to discern it, get a sight of it, and RISK RAISING it? For there is risk
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.21#in raising it, perhaps there is no greater risk.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.22#2. "HOW COULD anything originate out of its opposite? For example, truth
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.23#out of error? or the Will to Truth out of the will to deception? or the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.24#generous deed out of selfishness? or the pure sun-bright vision of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.25#wise man out of covetousness? Such genesis is impossible; whoever dreams
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.26#of it is a fool, nay, worse than a fool; things of the highest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.27#value must have a different origin, an origin of THEIR own--in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.28#transitory, seductive, illusory, paltry world, in this turmoil of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.29#delusion and cupidity, they cannot have their source. But rather in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.30#the lap of Being, in the intransitory, in the concealed God, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.31#'Thing-in-itself--THERE must be their source, and nowhere else!"--This
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.32#mode of reasoning discloses the typical prejudice by which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.33#metaphysicians of all times can be recognized, this mode of valuation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.34#is at the back of all their logical procedure; through this "belief" of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.35#theirs, they exert themselves for their "knowledge," for something that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.36#is in the end solemnly christened "the Truth." The fundamental belief of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.37#metaphysicians is THE BELIEF IN ANTITHESES OF VALUES. It never occurred
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.38#even to the wariest of them to doubt here on the very threshold (where
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.39#doubt, however, was most necessary); though they had made a solemn
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.40#vow, "DE OMNIBUS DUBITANDUM." For it may be doubted, firstly, whether
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.41#antitheses exist at all; and secondly, whether the popular valuations
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.42#and antitheses of value upon which metaphysicians have set their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.43#seal, are not perhaps merely superficial estimates, merely provisional
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.44#perspectives, besides being probably made from some corner, perhaps from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.45#below--"frog perspectives," as it were, to borrow an expression current
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.46#among painters. In spite of all the value which may belong to the true,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.47#the positive, and the unselfish, it might be possible that a higher
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.48#and more fundamental value for life generally should be assigned to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.49#pretence, to the will to delusion, to selfishness, and cupidity. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.50#might even be possible that WHAT constitutes the value of those good and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.51#respected things, consists precisely in their being insidiously
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.52#related, knotted, and crocheted to these evil and apparently opposed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.53#things--perhaps even in being essentially identical with them. Perhaps!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.54#But who wishes to concern himself with such dangerous "Perhapses"!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.55#For that investigation one must await the advent of a new order of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.56#philosophers, such as will have other tastes and inclinations, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.57#reverse of those hitherto prevalent--philosophers of the dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.58#"Perhaps" in every sense of the term. And to speak in all seriousness, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.59#see such new philosophers beginning to appear.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.60#3. Having kept a sharp eye on philosophers, and having read between
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.61#their lines long enough, I now say to myself that the greater part of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.62#conscious thinking must be counted among the instinctive functions, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.63#it is so even in the case of philosophical thinking; one has here to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.64#learn anew, as one learned anew about heredity and "innateness." As
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.65#little as the act of birth comes into consideration in the whole process
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.66#and procedure of heredity, just as little is "being-conscious" OPPOSED
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.67#to the instinctive in any decisive sense; the greater part of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.68#conscious thinking of a philosopher is secretly influenced by his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.69#instincts, and forced into definite channels. And behind all logic and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.70#its seeming sovereignty of movement, there are valuations, or to speak
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.71#more plainly, physiological demands, for the maintenance of a definite
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.72#mode of life For example, that the certain is worth more than the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.73#uncertain, that illusion is less valuable than "truth" such valuations,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.74#in spite of their regulative importance for US, might notwithstanding be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.75#only superficial valuations, special kinds of _niaiserie_, such as may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.76#be necessary for the maintenance of beings such as ourselves. Supposing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.77#in effect, that man is not just the "measure of things."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.78#4. The falseness of an opinion is not for us any objection to it: it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.79#here, perhaps, that our new language sounds most strangely. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.80#question is, how far an opinion is life-furthering, life-preserving,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.81#species-preserving, perhaps species-rearing, and we are fundamentally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.82#inclined to maintain that the falsest opinions (to which the synthetic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.83#judgments a priori belong), are the most indispensable to us, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.84#without a recognition of logical fictions, without a comparison of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.85#reality with the purely IMAGINED world of the absolute and immutable,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.86#without a constant counterfeiting of the world by means of numbers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.87#man could not live--that the renunciation of false opinions would be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.88#a renunciation of life, a negation of life. TO RECOGNISE UNTRUTH AS A
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.89#CONDITION OF LIFE; that is certainly to impugn the traditional ideas of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.90#value in a dangerous manner, and a philosophy which ventures to do so,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.91#has thereby alone placed itself beyond good and evil.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.92#5. That which causes philosophers to be regarded half-distrustfully
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.93#and half-mockingly, is not the oft-repeated discovery how innocent they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.94#are--how often and easily they make mistakes and lose their way, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.95#short, how childish and childlike they are,--but that there is not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.96#enough honest dealing with them, whereas they all raise a loud and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.97#virtuous outcry when the problem of truthfulness is even hinted at in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.98#the remotest manner. They all pose as though their real opinions had
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.99#been discovered and attained through the self-evolving of a cold, pure,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.100#divinely indifferent dialectic (in contrast to all sorts of mystics,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.101#who, fairer and foolisher, talk of "inspiration"), whereas, in fact, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.102#prejudiced proposition, idea, or "suggestion," which is generally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.103#their heart's desire abstracted and refined, is defended by them with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.104#arguments sought out after the event. They are all advocates who do not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.105#wish to be regarded as such, generally astute defenders, also, of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.106#prejudices, which they dub "truths,"--and VERY far from having the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.107#conscience which bravely admits this to itself, very far from having
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.108#the good taste of the courage which goes so far as to let this be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.109#understood, perhaps to warn friend or foe, or in cheerful confidence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.110#and self-ridicule. The spectacle of the Tartuffery of old Kant, equally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.111#stiff and decent, with which he entices us into the dialectic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.112#by-ways that lead (more correctly mislead) to his "categorical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.113#imperative"--makes us fastidious ones smile, we who find no small
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.114#amusement in spying out the subtle tricks of old moralists and ethical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.115#preachers. Or, still more so, the hocus-pocus in mathematical form, by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.116#means of which Spinoza has, as it were, clad his philosophy in mail and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.117#mask--in fact, the "love of HIS wisdom," to translate the term fairly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.118#and squarely--in order thereby to strike terror at once into the heart
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.119#of the assailant who should dare to cast a glance on that invincible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.120#maiden, that Pallas Athene:--how much of personal timidity and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.121#vulnerability does this masquerade of a sickly recluse betray!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.122#6. It has gradually become clear to me what every great philosophy up
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.123#till now has consisted of--namely, the confession of its originator, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.124#a species of involuntary and unconscious auto-biography; and moreover
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.125#that the moral (or immoral) purpose in every philosophy has constituted
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.126#the true vital germ out of which the entire plant has always grown.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.127#Indeed, to understand how the abstrusest metaphysical assertions of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.128#philosopher have been arrived at, it is always well (and wise) to first
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.129#ask oneself: "What morality do they (or does he) aim at?" Accordingly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.130#I do not believe that an "impulse to knowledge" is the father of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.131#philosophy; but that another impulse, here as elsewhere, has only made
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.132#use of knowledge (and mistaken knowledge!) as an instrument. But whoever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.133#considers the fundamental impulses of man with a view to determining
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.134#how far they may have here acted as INSPIRING GENII (or as demons and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.135#cobolds), will find that they have all practiced philosophy at one time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.136#or another, and that each one of them would have been only too glad to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.137#look upon itself as the ultimate end of existence and the legitimate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.138#LORD over all the other impulses. For every impulse is imperious, and as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.139#SUCH, attempts to philosophize. To be sure, in the case of scholars, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.140#the case of really scientific men, it may be otherwise--"better," if
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.141#you will; there there may really be such a thing as an "impulse to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.142#knowledge," some kind of small, independent clock-work, which, when well
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.143#wound up, works away industriously to that end, WITHOUT the rest of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.144#the scholarly impulses taking any material part therein. The actual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.145#"interests" of the scholar, therefore, are generally in quite another
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.146#direction--in the family, perhaps, or in money-making, or in politics;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.147#it is, in fact, almost indifferent at what point of research his little
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.148#machine is placed, and whether the hopeful young worker becomes a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.149#good philologist, a mushroom specialist, or a chemist; he is not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.150#CHARACTERISED by becoming this or that. In the philosopher, on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.151#contrary, there is absolutely nothing impersonal; and above all,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.152#his morality furnishes a decided and decisive testimony as to WHO HE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.153#IS,--that is to say, in what order the deepest impulses of his nature
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.154#stand to each other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.155#7. How malicious philosophers can be! I know of nothing more stinging
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.156#than the joke Epicurus took the liberty of making on Plato and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.157#Platonists; he called them Dionysiokolakes. In its original sense,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.158#and on the face of it, the word signifies "Flatterers of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.159#Dionysius"--consequently, tyrants' accessories and lick-spittles;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.160#besides this, however, it is as much as to say, "They are all ACTORS,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.161#there is nothing genuine about them" (for Dionysiokolax was a popular
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.162#name for an actor). And the latter is really the malignant reproach that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.163#Epicurus cast upon Plato: he was annoyed by the grandiose manner, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.164#mise en scene style of which Plato and his scholars were masters--of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.165#which Epicurus was not a master! He, the old school-teacher of Samos,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.166#who sat concealed in his little garden at Athens, and wrote three
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.167#hundred books, perhaps out of rage and ambitious envy of Plato, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.168#knows! Greece took a hundred years to find out who the garden-god
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.169#Epicurus really was. Did she ever find out?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.170#8. There is a point in every philosophy at which the "conviction" of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.171#the philosopher appears on the scene; or, to put it in the words of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.172#ancient mystery:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.173#Adventavit asinus, Pulcher et fortissimus.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.174#9. You desire to LIVE "according to Nature"? Oh, you noble Stoics, what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.175#fraud of words! Imagine to yourselves a being like Nature, boundlessly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.176#extravagant, boundlessly indifferent, without purpose or consideration,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.177#without pity or justice, at once fruitful and barren and uncertain:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.178#imagine to yourselves INDIFFERENCE as a power--how COULD you live
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.179#in accordance with such indifference? To live--is not that just
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.180#endeavouring to be otherwise than this Nature? Is not living valuing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.181#preferring, being unjust, being limited, endeavouring to be different?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.182#And granted that your imperative, "living according to Nature," means
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.183#actually the same as "living according to life"--how could you do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.184#DIFFERENTLY? Why should you make a principle out of what you yourselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.185#are, and must be? In reality, however, it is quite otherwise with you:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.186#while you pretend to read with rapture the canon of your law in Nature,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.187#you want something quite the contrary, you extraordinary stage-players
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.188#and self-deluders! In your pride you wish to dictate your morals and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.189#ideals to Nature, to Nature herself, and to incorporate them therein;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.190#you insist that it shall be Nature "according to the Stoa," and would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.191#like everything to be made after your own image, as a vast, eternal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.192#glorification and generalism of Stoicism! With all your love for truth,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.193#you have forced yourselves so long, so persistently, and with such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.194#hypnotic rigidity to see Nature FALSELY, that is to say, Stoically,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.195#that you are no longer able to see it otherwise--and to crown all, some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.196#unfathomable superciliousness gives you the Bedlamite hope that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.197#BECAUSE you are able to tyrannize over yourselves--Stoicism is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.198#self-tyranny--Nature will also allow herself to be tyrannized over: is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.199#not the Stoic a PART of Nature?... But this is an old and everlasting
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.200#story: what happened in old times with the Stoics still happens today,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.201#as soon as ever a philosophy begins to believe in itself. It always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.202#creates the world in its own image; it cannot do otherwise; philosophy
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.203#is this tyrannical impulse itself, the most spiritual Will to Power, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.204#will to "creation of the world," the will to the causa prima.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.205#10. The eagerness and subtlety, I should even say craftiness, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.206#which the problem of "the real and the apparent world" is dealt with at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.207#present throughout Europe, furnishes food for thought and attention; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.208#he who hears only a "Will to Truth" in the background, and nothing else,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.209#cannot certainly boast of the sharpest ears. In rare and isolated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.210#cases, it may really have happened that such a Will to Truth--a certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.211#extravagant and adventurous pluck, a metaphysician's ambition of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.212#forlorn hope--has participated therein: that which in the end always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.213#prefers a handful of "certainty" to a whole cartload of beautiful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.214#possibilities; there may even be puritanical fanatics of conscience,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.215#who prefer to put their last trust in a sure nothing, rather than in an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.216#uncertain something. But that is Nihilism, and the sign of a despairing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.217#mortally wearied soul, notwithstanding the courageous bearing such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.218#virtue may display. It seems, however, to be otherwise with stronger
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.219#and livelier thinkers who are still eager for life. In that they side
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.220#AGAINST appearance, and speak superciliously of "perspective," in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.221#that they rank the credibility of their own bodies about as low as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.222#credibility of the ocular evidence that "the earth stands still," and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.223#thus, apparently, allowing with complacency their securest possession
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.224#to escape (for what does one at present believe in more firmly than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.225#in one's body?),--who knows if they are not really trying to win back
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.226#something which was formerly an even securer possession, something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.227#of the old domain of the faith of former times, perhaps the "immortal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.228#soul," perhaps "the old God," in short, ideas by which they could live
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.229#better, that is to say, more vigorously and more joyously, than by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.230#"modern ideas"? There is DISTRUST of these modern ideas in this mode
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.231#of looking at things, a disbelief in all that has been constructed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.232#yesterday and today; there is perhaps some slight admixture of satiety
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.233#and scorn, which can no longer endure the BRIC-A-BRAC of ideas of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.234#most varied origin, such as so-called Positivism at present throws on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.235#the market; a disgust of the more refined taste at the village-fair
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.236#motleyness and patchiness of all these reality-philosophasters, in whom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.237#there is nothing either new or true, except this motleyness. Therein it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.238#seems to me that we should agree with those skeptical anti-realists and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.239#knowledge-microscopists of the present day; their instinct, which repels
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.240#them from MODERN reality, is unrefuted... what do their retrograde
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.241#by-paths concern us! The main thing about them is NOT that they wish
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.242#to go "back," but that they wish to get AWAY therefrom. A little MORE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.243#strength, swing, courage, and artistic power, and they would be OFF--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.244#not back!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.245#11. It seems to me that there is everywhere an attempt at present to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.246#divert attention from the actual influence which Kant exercised on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.247#German philosophy, and especially to ignore prudently the value which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.248#he set upon himself. Kant was first and foremost proud of his Table of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.249#Categories; with it in his hand he said: "This is the most difficult
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.250#thing that could ever be undertaken on behalf of metaphysics." Let us
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.251#only understand this "could be"! He was proud of having DISCOVERED a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.252#new faculty in man, the faculty of synthetic judgment a priori. Granting
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.253#that he deceived himself in this matter; the development and rapid
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.254#flourishing of German philosophy depended nevertheless on his pride, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.255#on the eager rivalry of the younger generation to discover if possible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.256#something--at all events "new faculties"--of which to be still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.257#prouder!--But let us reflect for a moment--it is high time to do so.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.258#"How are synthetic judgments a priori POSSIBLE?" Kant asks himself--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.259#what is really his answer? "BY MEANS OF A MEANS (faculty)"--but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.260#unfortunately not in five words, but so circumstantially, imposingly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.261#and with such display of German profundity and verbal flourishes, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.262#one altogether loses sight of the comical niaiserie allemande involved
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.263#in such an answer. People were beside themselves with delight over this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.264#new faculty, and the jubilation reached its climax when Kant further
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.265#discovered a moral faculty in man--for at that time Germans were still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.266#moral, not yet dabbling in the "Politics of hard fact." Then came
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.267#the honeymoon of German philosophy. All the young theologians of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.268#Tubingen institution went immediately into the groves--all seeking for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.269#"faculties." And what did they not find--in that innocent, rich, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.270#still youthful period of the German spirit, to which Romanticism, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.271#malicious fairy, piped and sang, when one could not yet distinguish
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.272#between "finding" and "inventing"! Above all a faculty for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.273#"transcendental"; Schelling christened it, intellectual intuition,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.274#and thereby gratified the most earnest longings of the naturally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.275#pious-inclined Germans. One can do no greater wrong to the whole of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.276#this exuberant and eccentric movement (which was really youthfulness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.277#notwithstanding that it disguised itself so boldly, in hoary and senile
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.278#conceptions), than to take it seriously, or even treat it with moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.279#indignation. Enough, however--the world grew older, and the dream
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.280#vanished. A time came when people rubbed their foreheads, and they still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.281#rub them today. People had been dreaming, and first and foremost--old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.282#Kant. "By means of a means (faculty)"--he had said, or at least meant to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.283#say. But, is that--an answer? An explanation? Or is it not rather merely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.284#a repetition of the question? How does opium induce sleep? "By means of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.285#a means (faculty)," namely the virtus dormitiva, replies the doctor in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.286#Moliere,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.287#    Quia est in eo virtus dormitiva,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.288#    Cujus est natura sensus assoupire.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.289#But such replies belong to the realm of comedy, and it is high time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.290#to replace the Kantian question, "How are synthetic judgments a PRIORI
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.291#possible?" by another question, "Why is belief in such judgments
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.292#necessary?"--in effect, it is high time that we should understand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.293#that such judgments must be believed to be true, for the sake of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.294#preservation of creatures like ourselves; though they still might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.295#naturally be false judgments! Or, more plainly spoken, and roughly and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.296#readily--synthetic judgments a priori should not "be possible" at all;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.297#we have no right to them; in our mouths they are nothing but false
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.298#judgments. Only, of course, the belief in their truth is necessary, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.299#plausible belief and ocular evidence belonging to the perspective view
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.300#of life. And finally, to call to mind the enormous influence which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.301#"German philosophy"--I hope you understand its right to inverted commas
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.302#(goosefeet)?--has exercised throughout the whole of Europe, there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.303#no doubt that a certain VIRTUS DORMITIVA had a share in it; thanks to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.304#German philosophy, it was a delight to the noble idlers, the virtuous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.305#the mystics, the artiste, the three-fourths Christians, and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.306#political obscurantists of all nations, to find an antidote to the still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.307#overwhelming sensualism which overflowed from the last century into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.308#this, in short--"sensus assoupire."...
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.309#12. As regards materialistic atomism, it is one of the best-refuted
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.310#theories that have been advanced, and in Europe there is now perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.311#no one in the learned world so unscholarly as to attach serious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.312#signification to it, except for convenient everyday use (as an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.313#abbreviation of the means of expression)--thanks chiefly to the Pole
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.314#Boscovich: he and the Pole Copernicus have hitherto been the greatest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.315#and most successful opponents of ocular evidence. For while Copernicus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.316#has persuaded us to believe, contrary to all the senses, that the earth
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.317#does NOT stand fast, Boscovich has taught us to abjure the belief in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.318#last thing that "stood fast" of the earth--the belief in "substance," in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.319#"matter," in the earth-residuum, and particle-atom: it is the greatest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.320#triumph over the senses that has hitherto been gained on earth. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.321#must, however, go still further, and also declare war, relentless war
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.322#to the knife, against the "atomistic requirements" which still lead a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.323#dangerous after-life in places where no one suspects them, like the more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.324#celebrated "metaphysical requirements": one must also above all give
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.325#the finishing stroke to that other and more portentous atomism which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.326#Christianity has taught best and longest, the SOUL-ATOMISM. Let it be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.327#permitted to designate by this expression the belief which regards the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.328#soul as something indestructible, eternal, indivisible, as a monad,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.329#as an atomon: this belief ought to be expelled from science! Between
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.330#ourselves, it is not at all necessary to get rid of "the soul" thereby,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.331#and thus renounce one of the oldest and most venerated hypotheses--as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.332#happens frequently to the clumsiness of naturalists, who can hardly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.333#touch on the soul without immediately losing it. But the way is open
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.334#for new acceptations and refinements of the soul-hypothesis; and such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.335#conceptions as "mortal soul," and "soul of subjective multiplicity,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.336#and "soul as social structure of the instincts and passions," want
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.337#henceforth to have legitimate rights in science. In that the NEW
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.338#psychologist is about to put an end to the superstitions which have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.339#hitherto flourished with almost tropical luxuriance around the idea of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.340#the soul, he is really, as it were, thrusting himself into a new desert
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.341#and a new distrust--it is possible that the older psychologists had a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.342#merrier and more comfortable time of it; eventually, however, he finds
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.343#that precisely thereby he is also condemned to INVENT--and, who knows?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.344#perhaps to DISCOVER the new.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.345#13. Psychologists should bethink themselves before putting down the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.346#instinct of self-preservation as the cardinal instinct of an organic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.347#being. A living thing seeks above all to DISCHARGE its strength--life
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.348#itself is WILL TO POWER; self-preservation is only one of the indirect
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.349#and most frequent RESULTS thereof. In short, here, as everywhere else,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.350#let us beware of SUPERFLUOUS teleological principles!--one of which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.351#is the instinct of self-preservation (we owe it to Spinoza's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.352#inconsistency). It is thus, in effect, that method ordains, which must
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.353#be essentially economy of principles.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.354#14. It is perhaps just dawning on five or six minds that natural
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.355#philosophy is only a world-exposition and world-arrangement (according
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.356#to us, if I may say so!) and NOT a world-explanation; but in so far as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.357#it is based on belief in the senses, it is regarded as more, and for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.358#long time to come must be regarded as more--namely, as an explanation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.359#It has eyes and fingers of its own, it has ocular evidence and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.360#palpableness of its own: this operates fascinatingly, persuasively, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.361#CONVINCINGLY upon an age with fundamentally plebeian tastes--in fact, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.362#follows instinctively the canon of truth of eternal popular sensualism.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.363#What is clear, what is "explained"? Only that which can be seen and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.364#felt--one must pursue every problem thus far. Obversely, however, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.365#charm of the Platonic mode of thought, which was an ARISTOCRATIC mode,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.366#consisted precisely in RESISTANCE to obvious sense-evidence--perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.367#among men who enjoyed even stronger and more fastidious senses than our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.368#contemporaries, but who knew how to find a higher triumph in remaining
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.369#masters of them: and this by means of pale, cold, grey conceptional
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.370#networks which they threw over the motley whirl of the senses--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.371#mob of the senses, as Plato said. In this overcoming of the world, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.372#interpreting of the world in the manner of Plato, there was an ENJOYMENT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.373#different from that which the physicists of today offer us--and likewise
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.374#the Darwinists and anti-teleologists among the physiological workers,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.375#with their principle of the "smallest possible effort," and the greatest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.376#possible blunder. "Where there is nothing more to see or to grasp, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.377#is also nothing more for men to do"--that is certainly an imperative
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.378#different from the Platonic one, but it may notwithstanding be the right
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.379#imperative for a hardy, laborious race of machinists and bridge-builders
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.380#of the future, who have nothing but ROUGH work to perform.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.381#15. To study physiology with a clear conscience, one must insist on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.382#the fact that the sense-organs are not phenomena in the sense of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.383#idealistic philosophy; as such they certainly could not be causes!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.384#Sensualism, therefore, at least as regulative hypothesis, if not as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.385#heuristic principle. What? And others say even that the external world
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.386#is the work of our organs? But then our body, as a part of this external
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.387#world, would be the work of our organs! But then our organs themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.388#would be the work of our organs! It seems to me that this is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.389#complete REDUCTIO AD ABSURDUM, if the conception CAUSA SUI is something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.390#fundamentally absurd. Consequently, the external world is NOT the work
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.391#of our organs--?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.392#16. There are still harmless self-observers who believe that there are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.393#"immediate certainties"; for instance, "I think," or as the superstition
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.394#of Schopenhauer puts it, "I will"; as though cognition here got hold
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.395#of its object purely and simply as "the thing in itself," without any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.396#falsification taking place either on the part of the subject or the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.397#object. I would repeat it, however, a hundred times, that "immediate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.398#certainty," as well as "absolute knowledge" and the "thing in itself,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.399#involve a CONTRADICTIO IN ADJECTO; we really ought to free ourselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.400#from the misleading significance of words! The people on their part may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.401#think that cognition is knowing all about things, but the philosopher
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.402#must say to himself: "When I analyze the process that is expressed in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.403#the sentence, 'I think,' I find a whole series of daring assertions, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.404#argumentative proof of which would be difficult, perhaps impossible:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.405#for instance, that it is _I_ who think, that there must necessarily be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.406#something that thinks, that thinking is an activity and operation on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.407#part of a being who is thought of as a cause, that there is an 'ego,'
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.408#and finally, that it is already determined what is to be designated by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.409#thinking--that I KNOW what thinking is. For if I had not already decided
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.410#within myself what it is, by what standard could I determine whether
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.411#that which is just happening is not perhaps 'willing' or 'feeling'? In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.412#short, the assertion 'I think,' assumes that I COMPARE my state at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.413#present moment with other states of myself which I know, in order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.414#determine what it is; on account of this retrospective connection with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.415#further 'knowledge,' it has, at any rate, no immediate certainty for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.416#me."--In place of the "immediate certainty" in which the people may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.417#believe in the special case, the philosopher thus finds a series of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.418#metaphysical questions presented to him, veritable conscience questions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.419#of the intellect, to wit: "Whence did I get the notion of 'thinking'?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.420#Why do I believe in cause and effect? What gives me the right to speak
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.421#of an 'ego,' and even of an 'ego' as cause, and finally of an 'ego'
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.422#as cause of thought?" He who ventures to answer these metaphysical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.423#questions at once by an appeal to a sort of INTUITIVE perception, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.424#the person who says, "I think, and know that this, at least, is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.425#true, actual, and certain"--will encounter a smile and two notes of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.426#interrogation in a philosopher nowadays. "Sir," the philosopher will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.427#perhaps give him to understand, "it is improbable that you are not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.428#mistaken, but why should it be the truth?"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.429#17. With regard to the superstitions of logicians, I shall never tire
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.430#of emphasizing a small, terse fact, which is unwillingly recognized by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.431#these credulous minds--namely, that a thought comes when "it" wishes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.432#and not when "I" wish; so that it is a PERVERSION of the facts of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.433#case to say that the subject "I" is the condition of the predicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.434#"think." ONE thinks; but that this "one" is precisely the famous old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.435#"ego," is, to put it mildly, only a supposition, an assertion, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.436#assuredly not an "immediate certainty." After all, one has even gone too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.437#far with this "one thinks"--even the "one" contains an INTERPRETATION of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.438#the process, and does not belong to the process itself. One infers here
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.439#according to the usual grammatical formula--"To think is an activity;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.440#every activity requires an agency that is active; consequently"... It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.441#was pretty much on the same lines that the older atomism sought, besides
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.442#the operating "power," the material particle wherein it resides and out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.443#of which it operates--the atom. More rigorous minds, however, learnt at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.444#last to get along without this "earth-residuum," and perhaps some day we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.445#shall accustom ourselves, even from the logician's point of view, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.446#get along without the little "one" (to which the worthy old "ego" has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.447#refined itself).
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.448#18. It is certainly not the least charm of a theory that it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.449#refutable; it is precisely thereby that it attracts the more subtle
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.450#minds. It seems that the hundred-times-refuted theory of the "free will"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.451#owes its persistence to this charm alone; some one is always appearing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.452#who feels himself strong enough to refute it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.453#19. Philosophers are accustomed to speak of the will as though it were
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.454#the best-known thing in the world; indeed, Schopenhauer has given us
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.455#to understand that the will alone is really known to us, absolutely and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.456#completely known, without deduction or addition. But it again and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.457#again seems to me that in this case Schopenhauer also only did what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.458#philosophers are in the habit of doing--he seems to have adopted a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.459#POPULAR PREJUDICE and exaggerated it. Willing seems to me to be above
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.460#all something COMPLICATED, something that is a unity only in name--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.461#it is precisely in a name that popular prejudice lurks, which has got
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.462#the mastery over the inadequate precautions of philosophers in all ages.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.463#So let us for once be more cautious, let us be "unphilosophical": let
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.464#us say that in all willing there is firstly a plurality of sensations,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.465#namely, the sensation of the condition "AWAY FROM WHICH we go," the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.466#sensation of the condition "TOWARDS WHICH we go," the sensation of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.467#"FROM" and "TOWARDS" itself, and then besides, an accompanying muscular
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.468#sensation, which, even without our putting in motion "arms and legs,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.469#commences its action by force of habit, directly we "will" anything.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.470#Therefore, just as sensations (and indeed many kinds of sensations) are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.471#to be recognized as ingredients of the will, so, in the second place,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.472#thinking is also to be recognized; in every act of the will there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.473#a ruling thought;--and let us not imagine it possible to sever this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.474#thought from the "willing," as if the will would then remain over!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.475#In the third place, the will is not only a complex of sensation and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.476#thinking, but it is above all an EMOTION, and in fact the emotion of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.477#command. That which is termed "freedom of the will" is essentially the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.478#emotion of supremacy in respect to him who must obey: "I am free, 'he'
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.479#must obey"--this consciousness is inherent in every will; and equally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.480#so the straining of the attention, the straight look which fixes itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.481#exclusively on one thing, the unconditional judgment that "this and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.482#nothing else is necessary now," the inward certainty that obedience
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.483#will be rendered--and whatever else pertains to the position of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.484#commander. A man who WILLS commands something within himself which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.485#renders obedience, or which he believes renders obedience. But now let
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.486#us notice what is the strangest thing about the will,--this affair so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.487#extremely complex, for which the people have only one name. Inasmuch as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.488#in the given circumstances we are at the same time the commanding AND
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.489#the obeying parties, and as the obeying party we know the sensations of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.490#constraint, impulsion, pressure, resistance, and motion, which usually
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.491#commence immediately after the act of will; inasmuch as, on the other
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.492#hand, we are accustomed to disregard this duality, and to deceive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.493#ourselves about it by means of the synthetic term "I": a whole series
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.494#of erroneous conclusions, and consequently of false judgments about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.495#will itself, has become attached to the act of willing--to such a degree
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.496#that he who wills believes firmly that willing SUFFICES for action.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.497#Since in the majority of cases there has only been exercise of will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.498#when the effect of the command--consequently obedience, and therefore
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.499#action--was to be EXPECTED, the APPEARANCE has translated itself into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.500#the sentiment, as if there were a NECESSITY OF EFFECT; in a word, he who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.501#wills believes with a fair amount of certainty that will and action are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.502#somehow one; he ascribes the success, the carrying out of the willing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.503#to the will itself, and thereby enjoys an increase of the sensation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.504#of power which accompanies all success. "Freedom of Will"--that is the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.505#expression for the complex state of delight of the person exercising
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.506#volition, who commands and at the same time identifies himself with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.507#the executor of the order--who, as such, enjoys also the triumph over
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.508#obstacles, but thinks within himself that it was really his own will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.509#that overcame them. In this way the person exercising volition adds the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.510#feelings of delight of his successful executive instruments, the useful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.511#"underwills" or under-souls--indeed, our body is but a social structure
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.512#composed of many souls--to his feelings of delight as commander. L'EFFET
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.513#C'EST MOI. what happens here is what happens in every well-constructed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.514#and happy commonwealth, namely, that the governing class identifies
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.515#itself with the successes of the commonwealth. In all willing it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.516#absolutely a question of commanding and obeying, on the basis, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.517#already said, of a social structure composed of many "souls", on which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.518#account a philosopher should claim the right to include willing-as-such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.519#within the sphere of morals--regarded as the doctrine of the relations
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.520#of supremacy under which the phenomenon of "life" manifests itself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.521#20. That the separate philosophical ideas are not anything optional or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.522#autonomously evolving, but grow up in connection and relationship with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.523#each other, that, however suddenly and arbitrarily they seem to appear
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.524#in the history of thought, they nevertheless belong just as much to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.525#a system as the collective members of the fauna of a Continent--is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.526#betrayed in the end by the circumstance: how unfailingly the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.527#diverse philosophers always fill in again a definite fundamental scheme
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.528#of POSSIBLE philosophies. Under an invisible spell, they always revolve
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.529#once more in the same orbit, however independent of each other they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.530#may feel themselves with their critical or systematic wills, something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.531#within them leads them, something impels them in definite order the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.532#one after the other--to wit, the innate methodology and relationship
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.533#of their ideas. Their thinking is, in fact, far less a discovery than a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.534#re-recognizing, a remembering, a return and a home-coming to a far-off,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.535#ancient common-household of the soul, out of which those ideas formerly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.536#grew: philosophizing is so far a kind of atavism of the highest order.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.537#The wonderful family resemblance of all Indian, Greek, and German
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.538#philosophizing is easily enough explained. In fact, where there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.539#affinity of language, owing to the common philosophy of grammar--I mean
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.540#owing to the unconscious domination and guidance of similar grammatical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.541#functions--it cannot but be that everything is prepared at the outset
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.542#for a similar development and succession of philosophical systems,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.543#just as the way seems barred against certain other possibilities of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.544#world-interpretation. It is highly probable that philosophers within the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.545#domain of the Ural-Altaic languages (where the conception of the subject
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.546#is least developed) look otherwise "into the world," and will be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.547#found on paths of thought different from those of the Indo-Germans and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.548#Mussulmans, the spell of certain grammatical functions is ultimately
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.549#also the spell of PHYSIOLOGICAL valuations and racial conditions.--So
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.550#much by way of rejecting Locke's superficiality with regard to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.551#origin of ideas.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.552#21. The CAUSA SUI is the best self-contradiction that has yet been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.553#conceived, it is a sort of logical violation and unnaturalness; but the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.554#extravagant pride of man has managed to entangle itself profoundly and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.555#frightfully with this very folly. The desire for "freedom of will"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.556#in the superlative, metaphysical sense, such as still holds sway,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.557#unfortunately, in the minds of the half-educated, the desire to bear
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.558#the entire and ultimate responsibility for one's actions oneself, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.559#to absolve God, the world, ancestors, chance, and society therefrom,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.560#involves nothing less than to be precisely this CAUSA SUI, and, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.561#more than Munchausen daring, to pull oneself up into existence by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.562#hair, out of the slough of nothingness. If any one should find out in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.563#this manner the crass stupidity of the celebrated conception of "free
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.564#will" and put it out of his head altogether, I beg of him to carry
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.565#his "enlightenment" a step further, and also put out of his head the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.566#contrary of this monstrous conception of "free will": I mean "non-free
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.567#will," which is tantamount to a misuse of cause and effect. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.568#should not wrongly MATERIALISE "cause" and "effect," as the natural
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.569#philosophers do (and whoever like them naturalize in thinking at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.570#present), according to the prevailing mechanical doltishness which makes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.571#the cause press and push until it "effects" its end; one should use
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.572#"cause" and "effect" only as pure CONCEPTIONS, that is to say, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.573#conventional fictions for the purpose of designation and mutual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.574#understanding,--NOT for explanation. In "being-in-itself" there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.575#nothing of "casual-connection," of "necessity," or of "psychological
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.576#non-freedom"; there the effect does NOT follow the cause, there "law"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.577#does not obtain. It is WE alone who have devised cause, sequence,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.578#reciprocity, relativity, constraint, number, law, freedom, motive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.579#and purpose; and when we interpret and intermix this symbol-world,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.580#as "being-in-itself," with things, we act once more as we have always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.581#acted--MYTHOLOGICALLY. The "non-free will" is mythology; in real life
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.582#it is only a question of STRONG and WEAK wills.--It is almost always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.583#a symptom of what is lacking in himself, when a thinker, in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.584#"causal-connection" and "psychological necessity," manifests something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.585#of compulsion, indigence, obsequiousness, oppression, and non-freedom;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.586#it is suspicious to have such feelings--the person betrays himself. And
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.587#in general, if I have observed correctly, the "non-freedom of the will"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.588#is regarded as a problem from two entirely opposite standpoints, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.589#always in a profoundly PERSONAL manner: some will not give up their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.590#"responsibility," their belief in THEMSELVES, the personal right to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.591#THEIR merits, at any price (the vain races belong to this class); others
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.592#on the contrary, do not wish to be answerable for anything, or blamed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.593#for anything, and owing to an inward self-contempt, seek to GET OUT OF
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.594#THE BUSINESS, no matter how. The latter, when they write books, are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.595#in the habit at present of taking the side of criminals; a sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.596#socialistic sympathy is their favourite disguise. And as a matter of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.597#fact, the fatalism of the weak-willed embellishes itself surprisingly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.598#when it can pose as "la religion de la souffrance humaine"; that is ITS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.599#"good taste."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.600#22. Let me be pardoned, as an old philologist who cannot desist from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.601#the mischief of putting his finger on bad modes of interpretation, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.602#"Nature's conformity to law," of which you physicists talk so proudly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.603#as though--why, it exists only owing to your interpretation and bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.604#"philology." It is no matter of fact, no "text," but rather just a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.605#naively humanitarian adjustment and perversion of meaning, with which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.606#you make abundant concessions to the democratic instincts of the modern
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.607#soul! "Everywhere equality before the law--Nature is not different in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.608#that respect, nor better than we": a fine instance of secret motive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.609#in which the vulgar antagonism to everything privileged and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.610#autocratic--likewise a second and more refined atheism--is once more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.611#disguised. "Ni dieu, ni maitre"--that, also, is what you want; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.612#therefore "Cheers for natural law!"--is it not so? But, as has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.613#said, that is interpretation, not text; and somebody might come along,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.614#who, with opposite intentions and modes of interpretation, could read
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.615#out of the same "Nature," and with regard to the same phenomena, just
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.616#the tyrannically inconsiderate and relentless enforcement of the claims
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.617#of power--an interpreter who should so place the unexceptionalness and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.618#unconditionalness of all "Will to Power" before your eyes, that almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.619#every word, and the word "tyranny" itself, would eventually seem
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.620#unsuitable, or like a weakening and softening metaphor--as being too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.621#human; and who should, nevertheless, end by asserting the same about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.622#this world as you do, namely, that it has a "necessary" and "calculable"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.623#course, NOT, however, because laws obtain in it, but because they are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.624#absolutely LACKING, and every power effects its ultimate consequences
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.625#every moment. Granted that this also is only interpretation--and you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.626#will be eager enough to make this objection?--well, so much the better.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.627#23. All psychology hitherto has run aground on moral prejudices and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.628#timidities, it has not dared to launch out into the depths. In so far
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.629#as it is allowable to recognize in that which has hitherto been written,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.630#evidence of that which has hitherto been kept silent, it seems as if
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.631#nobody had yet harboured the notion of psychology as the Morphology
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.632#and DEVELOPMENT-DOCTRINE OF THE WILL TO POWER, as I conceive of it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.633#The power of moral prejudices has penetrated deeply into the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.634#intellectual world, the world apparently most indifferent and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.635#unprejudiced, and has obviously operated in an injurious, obstructive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.636#blinding, and distorting manner. A proper physio-psychology has to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.637#contend with unconscious antagonism in the heart of the investigator,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.638#it has "the heart" against it even a doctrine of the reciprocal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.639#conditionalness of the "good" and the "bad" impulses, causes (as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.640#refined immorality) distress and aversion in a still strong and manly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.641#conscience--still more so, a doctrine of the derivation of all good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.642#impulses from bad ones. If, however, a person should regard even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.643#the emotions of hatred, envy, covetousness, and imperiousness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.644#as life-conditioning emotions, as factors which must be present,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.645#fundamentally and essentially, in the general economy of life (which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.646#must, therefore, be further developed if life is to be further
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.647#developed), he will suffer from such a view of things as from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.648#sea-sickness. And yet this hypothesis is far from being the strangest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.649#and most painful in this immense and almost new domain of dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.650#knowledge, and there are in fact a hundred good reasons why every one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.651#should keep away from it who CAN do so! On the other hand, if one has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.652#once drifted hither with one's bark, well! very good! now let us set our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.653#teeth firmly! let us open our eyes and keep our hand fast on the helm!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.654#We sail away right OVER morality, we crush out, we destroy perhaps the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.655#remains of our own morality by daring to make our voyage thither--but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.656#what do WE matter. Never yet did a PROFOUNDER world of insight reveal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.657#itself to daring travelers and adventurers, and the psychologist who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.658#thus "makes a sacrifice"--it is not the sacrifizio dell' intelletto,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.659#on the contrary!--will at least be entitled to demand in return that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.660#psychology shall once more be recognized as the queen of the sciences,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.661#for whose service and equipment the other sciences exist. For psychology
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:1.662#is once more the path to the fundamental problems.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.1#CHAPTER II. THE FREE SPIRIT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.2#24. O sancta simplicitas! In what strange simplification and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.3#falsification man lives! One can never cease wondering when once one has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.4#got eyes for beholding this marvel! How we have made everything around
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.5#us clear and free and easy and simple! how we have been able to give
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.6#our senses a passport to everything superficial, our thoughts a godlike
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.7#desire for wanton pranks and wrong inferences!--how from the beginning,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.8#we have contrived to retain our ignorance in order to enjoy an almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.9#inconceivable freedom, thoughtlessness, imprudence, heartiness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.10#and gaiety--in order to enjoy life! And only on this solidified,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.11#granite-like foundation of ignorance could knowledge rear itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.12#hitherto, the will to knowledge on the foundation of a far more powerful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.13#will, the will to ignorance, to the uncertain, to the untrue! Not as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.14#its opposite, but--as its refinement! It is to be hoped, indeed, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.15#LANGUAGE, here as elsewhere, will not get over its awkwardness, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.16#it will continue to talk of opposites where there are only degrees
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.17#and many refinements of gradation; it is equally to be hoped that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.18#incarnated Tartuffery of morals, which now belongs to our unconquerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.19#"flesh and blood," will turn the words round in the mouths of us
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.20#discerning ones. Here and there we understand it, and laugh at the way
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.21#in which precisely the best knowledge seeks most to retain us in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.22#SIMPLIFIED, thoroughly artificial, suitably imagined, and suitably
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.23#falsified world: at the way in which, whether it will or not, it loves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.24#error, because, as living itself, it loves life!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.25#25. After such a cheerful commencement, a serious word would fain be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.26#heard; it appeals to the most serious minds. Take care, ye philosophers
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.27#and friends of knowledge, and beware of martyrdom! Of suffering "for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.28#truth's sake"! even in your own defense! It spoils all the innocence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.29#and fine neutrality of your conscience; it makes you headstrong against
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.30#objections and red rags; it stupefies, animalizes, and brutalizes, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.31#in the struggle with danger, slander, suspicion, expulsion, and even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.32#worse consequences of enmity, ye have at last to play your last card
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.33#as protectors of truth upon earth--as though "the Truth" were such an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.34#innocent and incompetent creature as to require protectors! and you of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.35#all people, ye knights of the sorrowful countenance, Messrs Loafers and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.36#Cobweb-spinners of the spirit! Finally, ye know sufficiently well that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.37#it cannot be of any consequence if YE just carry your point; ye know
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.38#that hitherto no philosopher has carried his point, and that there might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.39#be a more laudable truthfulness in every little interrogative mark
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.40#which you place after your special words and favourite doctrines (and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.41#occasionally after yourselves) than in all the solemn pantomime and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.42#trumping games before accusers and law-courts! Rather go out of the way!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.43#Flee into concealment! And have your masks and your ruses, that ye may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.44#be mistaken for what you are, or somewhat feared! And pray, don't forget
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.45#the garden, the garden with golden trellis-work! And have people around
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.46#you who are as a garden--or as music on the waters at eventide, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.47#already the day becomes a memory. Choose the GOOD solitude, the free,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.48#wanton, lightsome solitude, which also gives you the right still to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.49#remain good in any sense whatsoever! How poisonous, how crafty, how bad,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.50#does every long war make one, which cannot be waged openly by means
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.51#of force! How PERSONAL does a long fear make one, a long watching
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.52#of enemies, of possible enemies! These pariahs of society, these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.53#long-pursued, badly-persecuted ones--also the compulsory recluses, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.54#Spinozas or Giordano Brunos--always become in the end, even under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.55#most intellectual masquerade, and perhaps without being themselves aware
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.56#of it, refined vengeance-seekers and poison-Brewers (just lay bare
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.57#the foundation of Spinoza's ethics and theology!), not to speak of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.58#the stupidity of moral indignation, which is the unfailing sign in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.59#philosopher that the sense of philosophical humour has left him. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.60#martyrdom of the philosopher, his "sacrifice for the sake of truth,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.61#forces into the light whatever of the agitator and actor lurks in him;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.62#and if one has hitherto contemplated him only with artistic curiosity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.63#with regard to many a philosopher it is easy to understand the dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.64#desire to see him also in his deterioration (deteriorated into a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.65#"martyr," into a stage-and-tribune-bawler). Only, that it is necessary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.66#with such a desire to be clear WHAT spectacle one will see in any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.67#case--merely a satyric play, merely an epilogue farce, merely the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.68#continued proof that the long, real tragedy IS AT AN END, supposing that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.69#every philosophy has been a long tragedy in its origin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.70#26. Every select man strives instinctively for a citadel and a privacy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.71#where he is FREE from the crowd, the many, the majority--where he may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.72#forget "men who are the rule," as their exception;--exclusive only of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.73#the case in which he is pushed straight to such men by a still stronger
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.74#instinct, as a discerner in the great and exceptional sense. Whoever, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.75#intercourse with men, does not occasionally glisten in all the green
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.76#and grey colours of distress, owing to disgust, satiety, sympathy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.77#gloominess, and solitariness, is assuredly not a man of elevated tastes;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.78#supposing, however, that he does not voluntarily take all this burden
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.79#and disgust upon himself, that he persistently avoids it, and remains,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.80#as I said, quietly and proudly hidden in his citadel, one thing is then
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.81#certain: he was not made, he was not predestined for knowledge. For as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.82#such, he would one day have to say to himself: "The devil take my good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.83#taste! but 'the rule' is more interesting than the exception--than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.84#myself, the exception!" And he would go DOWN, and above all, he would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.85#go "inside." The long and serious study of the AVERAGE man--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.86#consequently much disguise, self-overcoming, familiarity, and bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.87#intercourse (all intercourse is bad intercourse except with one's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.88#equals):--that constitutes a necessary part of the life-history of every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.89#philosopher; perhaps the most disagreeable, odious, and disappointing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.90#part. If he is fortunate, however, as a favourite child of knowledge
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.91#should be, he will meet with suitable auxiliaries who will shorten and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.92#lighten his task; I mean so-called cynics, those who simply recognize
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.93#the animal, the commonplace and "the rule" in themselves, and at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.94#same time have so much spirituality and ticklishness as to make them
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.95#talk of themselves and their like BEFORE WITNESSES--sometimes they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.96#wallow, even in books, as on their own dung-hill. Cynicism is the only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.97#form in which base souls approach what is called honesty; and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.98#higher man must open his ears to all the coarser or finer cynicism, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.99#congratulate himself when the clown becomes shameless right before
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.100#him, or the scientific satyr speaks out. There are even cases where
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.101#enchantment mixes with the disgust--namely, where by a freak of nature,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.102#genius is bound to some such indiscreet billy-goat and ape, as in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.103#case of the Abbe Galiani, the profoundest, acutest, and perhaps also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.104#filthiest man of his century--he was far profounder than Voltaire, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.105#consequently also, a good deal more silent. It happens more frequently,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.106#as has been hinted, that a scientific head is placed on an ape's body, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.107#fine exceptional understanding in a base soul, an occurrence by no means
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.108#rare, especially among doctors and moral physiologists. And whenever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.109#anyone speaks without bitterness, or rather quite innocently, of man
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.110#as a belly with two requirements, and a head with one; whenever any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.111#sees, seeks, and WANTS to see only hunger, sexual instinct, and vanity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.112#as the real and only motives of human actions; in short, when any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.113#speaks "badly"--and not even "ill"--of man, then ought the lover of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.114#knowledge to hearken attentively and diligently; he ought, in general,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.115#to have an open ear wherever there is talk without indignation. For the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.116#indignant man, and he who perpetually tears and lacerates himself with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.117#his own teeth (or, in place of himself, the world, God, or society),
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.118#may indeed, morally speaking, stand higher than the laughing and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.119#self-satisfied satyr, but in every other sense he is the more ordinary,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.120#more indifferent, and less instructive case. And no one is such a LIAR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.121#as the indignant man.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.122#27. It is difficult to be understood, especially when one thinks and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.123#lives gangasrotogati [Footnote: Like the river Ganges: presto.] among
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.124#those only who think and live otherwise--namely, kurmagati [Footnote:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.125#Like the tortoise: lento.], or at best "froglike," mandeikagati
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.126#[Footnote: Like the frog: staccato.] (I do everything to be "difficultly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.127#understood" myself!)--and one should be heartily grateful for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.128#good will to some refinement of interpretation. As regards "the good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.129#friends," however, who are always too easy-going, and think that as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.130#friends they have a right to ease, one does well at the very first to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.131#grant them a play-ground and romping-place for misunderstanding--one can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.132#thus laugh still; or get rid of them altogether, these good friends--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.133#laugh then also!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.134#28. What is most difficult to render from one language into another
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.135#is the TEMPO of its style, which has its basis in the character of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.136#race, or to speak more physiologically, in the average TEMPO of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.137#assimilation of its nutriment. There are honestly meant translations,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.138#which, as involuntary vulgarizations, are almost falsifications of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.139#original, merely because its lively and merry TEMPO (which overleaps and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.140#obviates all dangers in word and expression) could not also be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.141#rendered. A German is almost incapacitated for PRESTO in his language;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.142#consequently also, as may be reasonably inferred, for many of the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.143#delightful and daring NUANCES of free, free-spirited thought. And just
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.144#as the buffoon and satyr are foreign to him in body and conscience,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.145#so Aristophanes and Petronius are untranslatable for him. Everything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.146#ponderous, viscous, and pompously clumsy, all long-winded and wearying
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.147#species of style, are developed in profuse variety among Germans--pardon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.148#me for stating the fact that even Goethe's prose, in its mixture of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.149#stiffness and elegance, is no exception, as a reflection of the "good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.150#old time" to which it belongs, and as an expression of German taste at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.151#time when there was still a "German taste," which was a rococo-taste
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.152#in moribus et artibus. Lessing is an exception, owing to his histrionic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.153#nature, which understood much, and was versed in many things; he who was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.154#not the translator of Bayle to no purpose, who took refuge willingly in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.155#the shadow of Diderot and Voltaire, and still more willingly among the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.156#Roman comedy-writers--Lessing loved also free-spiritism in the TEMPO,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.157#and flight out of Germany. But how could the German language, even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.158#in the prose of Lessing, imitate the TEMPO of Machiavelli, who in his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.159#"Principe" makes us breathe the dry, fine air of Florence, and cannot
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.160#help presenting the most serious events in a boisterous allegrissimo,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.161#perhaps not without a malicious artistic sense of the contrast he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.162#ventures to present--long, heavy, difficult, dangerous thoughts, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.163#a TEMPO of the gallop, and of the best, wantonest humour? Finally, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.164#would venture on a German translation of Petronius, who, more than any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.165#great musician hitherto, was a master of PRESTO in invention, ideas, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.166#words? What matter in the end about the swamps of the sick, evil world,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.167#or of the "ancient world," when like him, one has the feet of a wind,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.168#the rush, the breath, the emancipating scorn of a wind, which makes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.169#everything healthy, by making everything RUN! And with regard to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.170#Aristophanes--that transfiguring, complementary genius, for whose
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.171#sake one PARDONS all Hellenism for having existed, provided one has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.172#understood in its full profundity ALL that there requires pardon and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.173#transfiguration; there is nothing that has caused me to meditate more on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.174#PLATO'S secrecy and sphinx-like nature, than the happily preserved petit
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.175#fait that under the pillow of his death-bed there was found no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.176#"Bible," nor anything Egyptian, Pythagorean, or Platonic--but a book of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.177#Aristophanes. How could even Plato have endured life--a Greek life which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.178#he repudiated--without an Aristophanes!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.179#29. It is the business of the very few to be independent; it is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.180#privilege of the strong. And whoever attempts it, even with the best
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.181#right, but without being OBLIGED to do so, proves that he is probably
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.182#not only strong, but also daring beyond measure. He enters into a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.183#labyrinth, he multiplies a thousandfold the dangers which life in itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.184#already brings with it; not the least of which is that no one can see
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.185#how and where he loses his way, becomes isolated, and is torn piecemeal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.186#by some minotaur of conscience. Supposing such a one comes to grief, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.187#is so far from the comprehension of men that they neither feel it, nor
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.188#sympathize with it. And he cannot any longer go back! He cannot even go
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.189#back again to the sympathy of men!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.190#30. Our deepest insights must--and should--appear as follies, and under
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.191#certain circumstances as crimes, when they come unauthorizedly to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.192#the ears of those who are not disposed and predestined for them. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.193#exoteric and the esoteric, as they were formerly distinguished by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.194#philosophers--among the Indians, as among the Greeks, Persians, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.195#Mussulmans, in short, wherever people believed in gradations of rank and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.196#NOT in equality and equal rights--are not so much in contradistinction
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.197#to one another in respect to the exoteric class, standing without, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.198#viewing, estimating, measuring, and judging from the outside, and not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.199#from the inside; the more essential distinction is that the class in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.200#question views things from below upwards--while the esoteric class views
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.201#things FROM ABOVE DOWNWARDS. There are heights of the soul from which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.202#tragedy itself no longer appears to operate tragically; and if all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.203#woe in the world were taken together, who would dare to decide whether
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.204#the sight of it would NECESSARILY seduce and constrain to sympathy, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.205#thus to a doubling of the woe?... That which serves the higher class of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.206#men for nourishment or refreshment, must be almost poison to an entirely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.207#different and lower order of human beings. The virtues of the common
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.208#man would perhaps mean vice and weakness in a philosopher; it might be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.209#possible for a highly developed man, supposing him to degenerate and go
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.210#to ruin, to acquire qualities thereby alone, for the sake of which he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.211#would have to be honoured as a saint in the lower world into which he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.212#had sunk. There are books which have an inverse value for the soul and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.213#the health according as the inferior soul and the lower vitality, or the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.214#higher and more powerful, make use of them. In the former case they are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.215#dangerous, disturbing, unsettling books, in the latter case they are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.216#herald-calls which summon the bravest to THEIR bravery. Books for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.217#general reader are always ill-smelling books, the odour of paltry people
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.218#clings to them. Where the populace eat and drink, and even where they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.219#reverence, it is accustomed to stink. One should not go into churches if
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.220#one wishes to breathe PURE air.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.221#31. In our youthful years we still venerate and despise without the art
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.222#of NUANCE, which is the best gain of life, and we have rightly to do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.223#hard penance for having fallen upon men and things with Yea and Nay.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.224#Everything is so arranged that the worst of all tastes, THE TASTE FOR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.225#THE UNCONDITIONAL, is cruelly befooled and abused, until a man learns
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.226#to introduce a little art into his sentiments, and prefers to try
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.227#conclusions with the artificial, as do the real artists of life. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.228#angry and reverent spirit peculiar to youth appears to allow itself no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.229#peace, until it has suitably falsified men and things, to be able
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.230#to vent its passion upon them: youth in itself even, is something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.231#falsifying and deceptive. Later on, when the young soul, tortured by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.232#continual disillusions, finally turns suspiciously against itself--still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.233#ardent and savage even in its suspicion and remorse of conscience: how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.234#it upbraids itself, how impatiently it tears itself, how it revenges
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.235#itself for its long self-blinding, as though it had been a voluntary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.236#blindness! In this transition one punishes oneself by distrust of one's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.237#sentiments; one tortures one's enthusiasm with doubt, one feels even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.238#good conscience to be a danger, as if it were the self-concealment and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.239#lassitude of a more refined uprightness; and above all, one espouses
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.240#upon principle the cause AGAINST "youth."--A decade later, and one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.241#comprehends that all this was also still--youth!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.242#32. Throughout the longest period of human history--one calls it the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.243#prehistoric period--the value or non-value of an action was inferred
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.244#from its CONSEQUENCES; the action in itself was not taken into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.245#consideration, any more than its origin; but pretty much as in China at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.246#present, where the distinction or disgrace of a child redounds to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.247#its parents, the retro-operating power of success or failure was what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.248#induced men to think well or ill of an action. Let us call this period
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.249#the PRE-MORAL period of mankind; the imperative, "Know thyself!" was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.250#then still unknown.--In the last ten thousand years, on the other hand,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.251#on certain large portions of the earth, one has gradually got so far,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.252#that one no longer lets the consequences of an action, but its origin,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.253#decide with regard to its worth: a great achievement as a whole, an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.254#important refinement of vision and of criterion, the unconscious effect
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.255#of the supremacy of aristocratic values and of the belief in "origin,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.256#the mark of a period which may be designated in the narrower sense as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.257#the MORAL one: the first attempt at self-knowledge is thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.258#made. Instead of the consequences, the origin--what an inversion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.259#of perspective! And assuredly an inversion effected only after long
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.260#struggle and wavering! To be sure, an ominous new superstition, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.261#peculiar narrowness of interpretation, attained supremacy precisely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.262#thereby: the origin of an action was interpreted in the most definite
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.263#sense possible, as origin out of an INTENTION; people were agreed in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.264#belief that the value of an action lay in the value of its intention.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.265#The intention as the sole origin and antecedent history of an action:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.266#under the influence of this prejudice moral praise and blame have been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.267#bestowed, and men have judged and even philosophized almost up to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.268#present day.--Is it not possible, however, that the necessity may now
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.269#have arisen of again making up our minds with regard to the reversing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.270#and fundamental shifting of values, owing to a new self-consciousness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.271#and acuteness in man--is it not possible that we may be standing on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.272#the threshold of a period which to begin with, would be distinguished
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.273#negatively as ULTRA-MORAL: nowadays when, at least among us immoralists,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.274#the suspicion arises that the decisive value of an action lies precisely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.275#in that which is NOT INTENTIONAL, and that all its intentionalness, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.276#that is seen, sensible, or "sensed" in it, belongs to its surface or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.277#skin--which, like every skin, betrays something, but CONCEALS still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.278#more? In short, we believe that the intention is only a sign or symptom,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.279#which first requires an explanation--a sign, moreover, which has too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.280#many interpretations, and consequently hardly any meaning in itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.281#alone: that morality, in the sense in which it has been understood
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.282#hitherto, as intention-morality, has been a prejudice, perhaps a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.283#prematureness or preliminariness, probably something of the same rank
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.284#as astrology and alchemy, but in any case something which must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.285#surmounted. The surmounting of morality, in a certain sense even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.286#self-mounting of morality--let that be the name for the long-secret
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.287#labour which has been reserved for the most refined, the most upright,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.288#and also the most wicked consciences of today, as the living touchstones
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.289#of the soul.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.290#33. It cannot be helped: the sentiment of surrender, of sacrifice for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.291#one's neighbour, and all self-renunciation-morality, must be mercilessly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.292#called to account, and brought to judgment; just as the aesthetics
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.293#of "disinterested contemplation," under which the emasculation of art
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.294#nowadays seeks insidiously enough to create itself a good conscience.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.295#There is far too much witchery and sugar in the sentiments "for others"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.296#and "NOT for myself," for one not needing to be doubly distrustful here,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.297#and for one asking promptly: "Are they not perhaps--DECEPTIONS?"--That
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.298#they PLEASE--him who has them, and him who enjoys their fruit, and also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.299#the mere spectator--that is still no argument in their FAVOUR, but just
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.300#calls for caution. Let us therefore be cautious!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.301#34. At whatever standpoint of philosophy one may place oneself nowadays,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.302#seen from every position, the ERRONEOUSNESS of the world in which we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.303#think we live is the surest and most certain thing our eyes can light
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.304#upon: we find proof after proof thereof, which would fain allure us into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.305#surmises concerning a deceptive principle in the "nature of things."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.306#He, however, who makes thinking itself, and consequently "the spirit,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.307#responsible for the falseness of the world--an honourable exit, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.308#every conscious or unconscious advocatus dei avails himself of--he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.309#who regards this world, including space, time, form, and movement, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.310#falsely DEDUCED, would have at least good reason in the end to become
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.311#distrustful also of all thinking; has it not hitherto been playing upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.312#us the worst of scurvy tricks? and what guarantee would it give that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.313#it would not continue to do what it has always been doing? In all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.314#seriousness, the innocence of thinkers has something touching and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.315#respect-inspiring in it, which even nowadays permits them to wait upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.316#consciousness with the request that it will give them HONEST answers:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.317#for example, whether it be "real" or not, and why it keeps the outer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.318#world so resolutely at a distance, and other questions of the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.319#description. The belief in "immediate certainties" is a MORAL NAIVETE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.320#which does honour to us philosophers; but--we have now to cease being
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.321#"MERELY moral" men! Apart from morality, such belief is a folly which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.322#does little honour to us! If in middle-class life an ever-ready distrust
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.323#is regarded as the sign of a "bad character," and consequently as an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.324#imprudence, here among us, beyond the middle-class world and its Yeas
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.325#and Nays, what should prevent our being imprudent and saying: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.326#philosopher has at length a RIGHT to "bad character," as the being who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.327#has hitherto been most befooled on earth--he is now under OBLIGATION
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.328#to distrustfulness, to the wickedest squinting out of every abyss of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.329#suspicion.--Forgive me the joke of this gloomy grimace and turn of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.330#expression; for I myself have long ago learned to think and estimate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.331#differently with regard to deceiving and being deceived, and I keep at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.332#least a couple of pokes in the ribs ready for the blind rage with which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.333#philosophers struggle against being deceived. Why NOT? It is nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.334#more than a moral prejudice that truth is worth more than semblance; it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.335#is, in fact, the worst proved supposition in the world. So much must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.336#conceded: there could have been no life at all except upon the basis
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.337#of perspective estimates and semblances; and if, with the virtuous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.338#enthusiasm and stupidity of many philosophers, one wished to do away
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.339#altogether with the "seeming world"--well, granted that YOU could do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.340#that,--at least nothing of your "truth" would thereby remain! Indeed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.341#what is it that forces us in general to the supposition that there is an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.342#essential opposition of "true" and "false"? Is it not enough to suppose
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.343#degrees of seemingness, and as it were lighter and darker shades and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.344#tones of semblance--different valeurs, as the painters say? Why might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.345#not the world WHICH CONCERNS US--be a fiction? And to any one who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.346#suggested: "But to a fiction belongs an originator?"--might it not be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.347#bluntly replied: WHY? May not this "belong" also belong to the fiction?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.348#Is it not at length permitted to be a little ironical towards the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.349#subject, just as towards the predicate and object? Might not the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.350#philosopher elevate himself above faith in grammar? All respect
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.351#to governesses, but is it not time that philosophy should renounce
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.352#governess-faith?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.353#35. O Voltaire! O humanity! O idiocy! There is something ticklish in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.354#"the truth," and in the SEARCH for the truth; and if man goes about it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.355#too humanely--"il ne cherche le vrai que pour faire le bien"--I wager he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.356#finds nothing!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.357#36. Supposing that nothing else is "given" as real but our world of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.358#desires and passions, that we cannot sink or rise to any other "reality"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.359#but just that of our impulses--for thinking is only a relation of these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.360#impulses to one another:--are we not permitted to make the attempt and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.361#to ask the question whether this which is "given" does not SUFFICE, by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.362#means of our counterparts, for the understanding even of the so-called
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.363#mechanical (or "material") world? I do not mean as an illusion, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.364#"semblance," a "representation" (in the Berkeleyan and Schopenhauerian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.365#sense), but as possessing the same degree of reality as our emotions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.366#themselves--as a more primitive form of the world of emotions, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.367#which everything still lies locked in a mighty unity, which afterwards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.368#branches off and develops itself in organic processes (naturally also,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.369#refines and debilitates)--as a kind of instinctive life in which all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.370#organic functions, including self-regulation, assimilation, nutrition,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.371#secretion, and change of matter, are still synthetically united with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.372#one another--as a PRIMARY FORM of life?--In the end, it is not only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.373#permitted to make this attempt, it is commanded by the conscience of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.374#LOGICAL METHOD. Not to assume several kinds of causality, so long as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.375#the attempt to get along with a single one has not been pushed to its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.376#furthest extent (to absurdity, if I may be allowed to say so): that is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.377#a morality of method which one may not repudiate nowadays--it follows
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.378#"from its definition," as mathematicians say. The question is ultimately
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.379#whether we really recognize the will as OPERATING, whether we believe in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.380#the causality of the will; if we do so--and fundamentally our belief IN
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.381#THIS is just our belief in causality itself--we MUST make the attempt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.382#to posit hypothetically the causality of the will as the only causality.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.383#"Will" can naturally only operate on "will"--and not on "matter" (not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.384#on "nerves," for instance): in short, the hypothesis must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.385#hazarded, whether will does not operate on will wherever "effects"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.386#are recognized--and whether all mechanical action, inasmuch as a power
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.387#operates therein, is not just the power of will, the effect of will.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.388#Granted, finally, that we succeeded in explaining our entire instinctive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.389#life as the development and ramification of one fundamental form of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.390#will--namely, the Will to Power, as my thesis puts it; granted that all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.391#organic functions could be traced back to this Will to Power, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.392#the solution of the problem of generation and nutrition--it is one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.393#problem--could also be found therein: one would thus have acquired the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.394#right to define ALL active force unequivocally as WILL TO POWER. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.395#world seen from within, the world defined and designated according to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.396#its "intelligible character"--it would simply be "Will to Power," and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.397#nothing else.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.398#37. "What? Does not that mean in popular language: God is disproved, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.399#not the devil?"--On the contrary! On the contrary, my friends! And who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.400#the devil also compels you to speak popularly!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.401#38. As happened finally in all the enlightenment of modern times with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.402#the French Revolution (that terrible farce, quite superfluous when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.403#judged close at hand, into which, however, the noble and visionary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.404#spectators of all Europe have interpreted from a distance their own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.405#indignation and enthusiasm so long and passionately, UNTIL THE TEXT HAS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.406#DISAPPEARED UNDER THE INTERPRETATION), so a noble posterity might once
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.407#more misunderstand the whole of the past, and perhaps only thereby make
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.408#ITS aspect endurable.--Or rather, has not this already happened? Have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.409#not we ourselves been--that "noble posterity"? And, in so far as we now
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.410#comprehend this, is it not--thereby already past?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.411#39. Nobody will very readily regard a doctrine as true merely because
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.412#it makes people happy or virtuous--excepting, perhaps, the amiable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.413#"Idealists," who are enthusiastic about the good, true, and beautiful,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.414#and let all kinds of motley, coarse, and good-natured desirabilities
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.415#swim about promiscuously in their pond. Happiness and virtue are no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.416#arguments. It is willingly forgotten, however, even on the part of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.417#thoughtful minds, that to make unhappy and to make bad are just as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.418#little counter-arguments. A thing could be TRUE, although it were in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.419#the highest degree injurious and dangerous; indeed, the fundamental
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.420#constitution of existence might be such that one succumbed by a full
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.421#knowledge of it--so that the strength of a mind might be measured by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.422#the amount of "truth" it could endure--or to speak more plainly, by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.423#extent to which it REQUIRED truth attenuated, veiled, sweetened, damped,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.424#and falsified. But there is no doubt that for the discovery of certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.425#PORTIONS of truth the wicked and unfortunate are more favourably
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.426#situated and have a greater likelihood of success; not to speak of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.427#wicked who are happy--a species about whom moralists are silent. Perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.428#severity and craft are more favourable conditions for the development of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.429#strong, independent spirits and philosophers than the gentle, refined,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.430#yielding good-nature, and habit of taking things easily, which are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.431#prized, and rightly prized in a learned man. Presupposing always,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.432#to begin with, that the term "philosopher" be not confined to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.433#philosopher who writes books, or even introduces HIS philosophy into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.434#books!--Stendhal furnishes a last feature of the portrait of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.435#free-spirited philosopher, which for the sake of German taste I will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.436#not omit to underline--for it is OPPOSED to German taste. "Pour etre
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.437#bon philosophe," says this last great psychologist, "il faut etre sec,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.438#clair, sans illusion. Un banquier, qui a fait fortune, a une partie du
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.439#caractere requis pour faire des decouvertes en philosophie, c'est-a-dire
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.440#pour voir clair dans ce qui est."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.441#40. Everything that is profound loves the mask: the profoundest things
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.442#have a hatred even of figure and likeness. Should not the CONTRARY only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.443#be the right disguise for the shame of a God to go about in? A question
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.444#worth asking!--it would be strange if some mystic has not already
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.445#ventured on the same kind of thing. There are proceedings of such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.446#delicate nature that it is well to overwhelm them with coarseness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.447#and make them unrecognizable; there are actions of love and of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.448#extravagant magnanimity after which nothing can be wiser than to take
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.449#a stick and thrash the witness soundly: one thereby obscures his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.450#recollection. Many a one is able to obscure and abuse his own memory, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.451#order at least to have vengeance on this sole party in the secret:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.452#shame is inventive. They are not the worst things of which one is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.453#most ashamed: there is not only deceit behind a mask--there is so much
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.454#goodness in craft. I could imagine that a man with something costly and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.455#fragile to conceal, would roll through life clumsily and rotundly like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.456#an old, green, heavily-hooped wine-cask: the refinement of his shame
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.457#requiring it to be so. A man who has depths in his shame meets his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.458#destiny and his delicate decisions upon paths which few ever reach,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.459#and with regard to the existence of which his nearest and most intimate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.460#friends may be ignorant; his mortal danger conceals itself from their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.461#eyes, and equally so his regained security. Such a hidden nature,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.462#which instinctively employs speech for silence and concealment, and is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.463#inexhaustible in evasion of communication, DESIRES and insists that a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.464#mask of himself shall occupy his place in the hearts and heads of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.465#friends; and supposing he does not desire it, his eyes will some day be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.466#opened to the fact that there is nevertheless a mask of him there--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.467#that it is well to be so. Every profound spirit needs a mask; nay, more,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.468#around every profound spirit there continually grows a mask, owing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.469#the constantly false, that is to say, SUPERFICIAL interpretation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.470#of every word he utters, every step he takes, every sign of life he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.471#manifests.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.472#41. One must subject oneself to one's own tests that one is destined
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.473#for independence and command, and do so at the right time. One must not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.474#avoid one's tests, although they constitute perhaps the most dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.475#game one can play, and are in the end tests made only before ourselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.476#and before no other judge. Not to cleave to any person, be it even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.477#dearest--every person is a prison and also a recess. Not to cleave to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.478#a fatherland, be it even the most suffering and necessitous--it is even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.479#less difficult to detach one's heart from a victorious fatherland. Not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.480#to cleave to a sympathy, be it even for higher men, into whose peculiar
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.481#torture and helplessness chance has given us an insight. Not to cleave
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.482#to a science, though it tempt one with the most valuable discoveries,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.483#apparently specially reserved for us. Not to cleave to one's own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.484#liberation, to the voluptuous distance and remoteness of the bird, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.485#always flies further aloft in order always to see more under it--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.486#danger of the flier. Not to cleave to our own virtues, nor become as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.487#a whole a victim to any of our specialties, to our "hospitality" for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.488#instance, which is the danger of dangers for highly developed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.489#and wealthy souls, who deal prodigally, almost indifferently with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.490#themselves, and push the virtue of liberality so far that it becomes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.491#a vice. One must know how TO CONSERVE ONESELF--the best test of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.492#independence.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.493#42. A new order of philosophers is appearing; I shall venture to baptize
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.494#them by a name not without danger. As far as I understand them, as far
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.495#as they allow themselves to be understood--for it is their nature to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.496#WISH to remain something of a puzzle--these philosophers of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.497#future might rightly, perhaps also wrongly, claim to be designated as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.498#"tempters." This name itself is after all only an attempt, or, if it be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.499#preferred, a temptation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.500#43. Will they be new friends of "truth," these coming philosophers? Very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.501#probably, for all philosophers hitherto have loved their truths. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.502#assuredly they will not be dogmatists. It must be contrary to their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.503#pride, and also contrary to their taste, that their truth should still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.504#be truth for every one--that which has hitherto been the secret wish
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.505#and ultimate purpose of all dogmatic efforts. "My opinion is MY opinion:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.506#another person has not easily a right to it"--such a philosopher of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.507#future will say, perhaps. One must renounce the bad taste of wishing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.508#agree with many people. "Good" is no longer good when one's neighbour
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.509#takes it into his mouth. And how could there be a "common good"! The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.510#expression contradicts itself; that which can be common is always of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.511#small value. In the end things must be as they are and have always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.512#been--the great things remain for the great, the abysses for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.513#profound, the delicacies and thrills for the refined, and, to sum up
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.514#shortly, everything rare for the rare.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.515#44. Need I say expressly after all this that they will be free, VERY
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.516#free spirits, these philosophers of the future--as certainly also they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.517#will not be merely free spirits, but something more, higher, greater,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.518#and fundamentally different, which does not wish to be misunderstood and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.519#mistaken? But while I say this, I feel under OBLIGATION almost as much
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.520#to them as to ourselves (we free spirits who are their heralds and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.521#forerunners), to sweep away from ourselves altogether a stupid old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.522#prejudice and misunderstanding, which, like a fog, has too long made the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.523#conception of "free spirit" obscure. In every country of Europe, and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.524#same in America, there is at present something which makes an abuse of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.525#this name a very narrow, prepossessed, enchained class of spirits,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.526#who desire almost the opposite of what our intentions and instincts
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.527#prompt--not to mention that in respect to the NEW philosophers who are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.528#appearing, they must still more be closed windows and bolted doors.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.529#Briefly and regrettably, they belong to the LEVELLERS, these wrongly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.530#named "free spirits"--as glib-tongued and scribe-fingered slaves of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.531#the democratic taste and its "modern ideas" all of them men without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.532#solitude, without personal solitude, blunt honest fellows to whom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.533#neither courage nor honourable conduct ought to be denied, only, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.534#are not free, and are ludicrously superficial, especially in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.535#innate partiality for seeing the cause of almost ALL human misery and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.536#failure in the old forms in which society has hitherto existed--a notion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.537#which happily inverts the truth entirely! What they would fain attain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.538#with all their strength, is the universal, green-meadow happiness of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.539#herd, together with security, safety, comfort, and alleviation of life
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.540#for every one, their two most frequently chanted songs and doctrines
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.541#are called "Equality of Rights" and "Sympathy with All Sufferers"--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.542#suffering itself is looked upon by them as something which must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.543#DONE AWAY WITH. We opposite ones, however, who have opened our eye and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.544#conscience to the question how and where the plant "man" has hitherto
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.545#grown most vigorously, believe that this has always taken place under
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.546#the opposite conditions, that for this end the dangerousness of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.547#situation had to be increased enormously, his inventive faculty and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.548#dissembling power (his "spirit") had to develop into subtlety and daring
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.549#under long oppression and compulsion, and his Will to Life had to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.550#increased to the unconditioned Will to Power--we believe that severity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.551#violence, slavery, danger in the street and in the heart, secrecy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.552#stoicism, tempter's art and devilry of every kind,--that everything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.553#wicked, terrible, tyrannical, predatory, and serpentine in man, serves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.554#as well for the elevation of the human species as its opposite--we do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.555#not even say enough when we only say THIS MUCH, and in any case we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.556#find ourselves here, both with our speech and our silence, at the OTHER
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.557#extreme of all modern ideology and gregarious desirability, as their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.558#antipodes perhaps? What wonder that we "free spirits" are not exactly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.559#the most communicative spirits? that we do not wish to betray in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.560#respect WHAT a spirit can free itself from, and WHERE perhaps it will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.561#then be driven? And as to the import of the dangerous formula, "Beyond
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.562#Good and Evil," with which we at least avoid confusion, we ARE something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.563#else than "libres-penseurs," "liben pensatori" "free-thinkers,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.564#and whatever these honest advocates of "modern ideas" like to call
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.565#themselves. Having been at home, or at least guests, in many realms of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.566#the spirit, having escaped again and again from the gloomy, agreeable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.567#nooks in which preferences and prejudices, youth, origin, the accident
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.568#of men and books, or even the weariness of travel seemed to confine us,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.569#full of malice against the seductions of dependency which he concealed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.570#in honours, money, positions, or exaltation of the senses, grateful even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.571#for distress and the vicissitudes of illness, because they always free
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.572#us from some rule, and its "prejudice," grateful to the God, devil,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.573#sheep, and worm in us, inquisitive to a fault, investigators to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.574#point of cruelty, with unhesitating fingers for the intangible, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.575#teeth and stomachs for the most indigestible, ready for any business
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.576#that requires sagacity and acute senses, ready for every adventure,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.577#owing to an excess of "free will", with anterior and posterior souls,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.578#into the ultimate intentions of which it is difficult to pry, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.579#foregrounds and backgrounds to the end of which no foot may run, hidden
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.580#ones under the mantles of light, appropriators, although we resemble
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.581#heirs and spendthrifts, arrangers and collectors from morning till
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.582#night, misers of our wealth and our full-crammed drawers, economical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.583#in learning and forgetting, inventive in scheming, sometimes proud of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.584#tables of categories, sometimes pedants, sometimes night-owls of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.585#work even in full day, yea, if necessary, even scarecrows--and it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.586#necessary nowadays, that is to say, inasmuch as we are the born, sworn,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.587#jealous friends of SOLITUDE, of our own profoundest midnight and midday
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.588#solitude--such kind of men are we, we free spirits! And perhaps ye are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:2.589#also something of the same kind, ye coming ones? ye NEW philosophers?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.1#CHAPTER III. THE RELIGIOUS MOOD
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.2#45. The human soul and its limits, the range of man's inner experiences
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.3#hitherto attained, the heights, depths, and distances of these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.4#experiences, the entire history of the soul UP TO THE PRESENT TIME,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.5#and its still unexhausted possibilities: this is the preordained
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.6#hunting-domain for a born psychologist and lover of a "big hunt". But
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.7#how often must he say despairingly to himself: "A single individual!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.8#alas, only a single individual! and this great forest, this virgin
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.9#forest!" So he would like to have some hundreds of hunting assistants,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.10#and fine trained hounds, that he could send into the history of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.11#human soul, to drive HIS game together. In vain: again and again he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.12#experiences, profoundly and bitterly, how difficult it is to find
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.13#assistants and dogs for all the things that directly excite his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.14#curiosity. The evil of sending scholars into new and dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.15#hunting-domains, where courage, sagacity, and subtlety in every sense
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.16#are required, is that they are no longer serviceable just when the "BIG
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.17#hunt," and also the great danger commences,--it is precisely then that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.18#they lose their keen eye and nose. In order, for instance, to divine and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.19#determine what sort of history the problem of KNOWLEDGE AND CONSCIENCE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.20#has hitherto had in the souls of homines religiosi, a person would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.21#perhaps himself have to possess as profound, as bruised, as immense an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.22#experience as the intellectual conscience of Pascal; and then he would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.23#still require that wide-spread heaven of clear, wicked spirituality,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.24#which, from above, would be able to oversee, arrange, and effectively
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.25#formulize this mass of dangerous and painful experiences.--But who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.26#could do me this service! And who would have time to wait for such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.27#servants!--they evidently appear too rarely, they are so improbable at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.28#all times! Eventually one must do everything ONESELF in order to know
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.29#something; which means that one has MUCH to do!--But a curiosity like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.30#mine is once for all the most agreeable of vices--pardon me! I mean to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.31#say that the love of truth has its reward in heaven, and already upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.32#earth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.33#46. Faith, such as early Christianity desired, and not infrequently
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.34#achieved in the midst of a skeptical and southernly free-spirited world,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.35#which had centuries of struggle between philosophical schools behind
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.36#it and in it, counting besides the education in tolerance which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.37#the Imperium Romanum gave--this faith is NOT that sincere, austere
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.38#slave-faith by which perhaps a Luther or a Cromwell, or some other
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.39#northern barbarian of the spirit remained attached to his God and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.40#Christianity, it is much rather the faith of Pascal, which resembles in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.41#a terrible manner a continuous suicide of reason--a tough, long-lived,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.42#worm-like reason, which is not to be slain at once and with a single
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.43#blow. The Christian faith from the beginning, is sacrifice the sacrifice
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.44#of all freedom, all pride, all self-confidence of spirit, it is at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.45#the same time subjection, self-derision, and self-mutilation. There is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.46#cruelty and religious Phoenicianism in this faith, which is adapted to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.47#tender, many-sided, and very fastidious conscience, it takes for granted
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.48#that the subjection of the spirit is indescribably PAINFUL, that all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.49#past and all the habits of such a spirit resist the absurdissimum, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.50#the form of which "faith" comes to it. Modern men, with their obtuseness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.51#as regards all Christian nomenclature, have no longer the sense for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.52#terribly superlative conception which was implied to an antique taste by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.53#the paradox of the formula, "God on the Cross". Hitherto there had never
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.54#and nowhere been such boldness in inversion, nor anything at once so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.55#dreadful, questioning, and questionable as this formula: it promised a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.56#transvaluation of all ancient values--It was the Orient, the PROFOUND
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.57#Orient, it was the Oriental slave who thus took revenge on Rome and its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.58#noble, light-minded toleration, on the Roman "Catholicism" of non-faith,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.59#and it was always not the faith, but the freedom from the faith, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.60#half-stoical and smiling indifference to the seriousness of the faith,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.61#which made the slaves indignant at their masters and revolt against
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.62#them. "Enlightenment" causes revolt, for the slave desires the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.63#unconditioned, he understands nothing but the tyrannous, even in morals,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.64#he loves as he hates, without NUANCE, to the very depths, to the point
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.65#of pain, to the point of sickness--his many HIDDEN sufferings make
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.66#him revolt against the noble taste which seems to DENY suffering. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.67#skepticism with regard to suffering, fundamentally only an attitude of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.68#aristocratic morality, was not the least of the causes, also, of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.69#last great slave-insurrection which began with the French Revolution.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.70#47. Wherever the religious neurosis has appeared on the earth so far,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.71#we find it connected with three dangerous prescriptions as to regimen:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.72#solitude, fasting, and sexual abstinence--but without its being possible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.73#to determine with certainty which is cause and which is effect, or IF
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.74#any relation at all of cause and effect exists there. This latter doubt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.75#is justified by the fact that one of the most regular symptoms among
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.76#savage as well as among civilized peoples is the most sudden and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.77#excessive sensuality, which then with equal suddenness transforms into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.78#penitential paroxysms, world-renunciation, and will-renunciation, both
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.79#symptoms perhaps explainable as disguised epilepsy? But nowhere is it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.80#MORE obligatory to put aside explanations around no other type has there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.81#grown such a mass of absurdity and superstition, no other type seems to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.82#have been more interesting to men and even to philosophers--perhaps it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.83#is time to become just a little indifferent here, to learn caution, or,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.84#better still, to look AWAY, TO GO AWAY--Yet in the background of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.85#most recent philosophy, that of Schopenhauer, we find almost as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.86#problem in itself, this terrible note of interrogation of the religious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.87#crisis and awakening. How is the negation of will POSSIBLE? how is the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.88#saint possible?--that seems to have been the very question with which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.89#Schopenhauer made a start and became a philosopher. And thus it was a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.90#genuine Schopenhauerian consequence, that his most convinced adherent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.91#(perhaps also his last, as far as Germany is concerned), namely, Richard
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.92#Wagner, should bring his own life-work to an end just here, and should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.93#finally put that terrible and eternal type upon the stage as Kundry,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.94#type vecu, and as it loved and lived, at the very time that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.95#mad-doctors in almost all European countries had an opportunity to study
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.96#the type close at hand, wherever the religious neurosis--or as I call
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.97#it, "the religious mood"--made its latest epidemical outbreak and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.98#display as the "Salvation Army"--If it be a question, however, as to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.99#what has been so extremely interesting to men of all sorts in all ages,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.100#and even to philosophers, in the whole phenomenon of the saint, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.101#is undoubtedly the appearance of the miraculous therein--namely, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.102#immediate SUCCESSION OF OPPOSITES, of states of the soul regarded as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.103#morally antithetical: it was believed here to be self-evident that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.104#a "bad man" was all at once turned into a "saint," a good man. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.105#hitherto existing psychology was wrecked at this point, is it not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.106#possible it may have happened principally because psychology had placed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.107#itself under the dominion of morals, because it BELIEVED in oppositions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.108#of moral values, and saw, read, and INTERPRETED these oppositions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.109#into the text and facts of the case? What? "Miracle" only an error of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.110#interpretation? A lack of philology?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.111#48. It seems that the Latin races are far more deeply attached to their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.112#Catholicism than we Northerners are to Christianity generally, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.113#that consequently unbelief in Catholic countries means something quite
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.114#different from what it does among Protestants--namely, a sort of revolt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.115#against the spirit of the race, while with us it is rather a return to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.116#the spirit (or non-spirit) of the race.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.117#We Northerners undoubtedly derive our origin from barbarous races, even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.118#as regards our talents for religion--we have POOR talents for it. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.119#may make an exception in the case of the Celts, who have theretofore
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.120#furnished also the best soil for Christian infection in the North: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.121#Christian ideal blossomed forth in France as much as ever the pale sun
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.122#of the north would allow it. How strangely pious for our taste are still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.123#these later French skeptics, whenever there is any Celtic blood in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.124#origin! How Catholic, how un-German does Auguste Comte's Sociology
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.125#seem to us, with the Roman logic of its instincts! How Jesuitical, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.126#amiable and shrewd cicerone of Port Royal, Sainte-Beuve, in spite of all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.127#his hostility to Jesuits! And even Ernest Renan: how inaccessible to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.128#us Northerners does the language of such a Renan appear, in whom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.129#every instant the merest touch of religious thrill throws his refined
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.130#voluptuous and comfortably couching soul off its balance! Let us repeat
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.131#after him these fine sentences--and what wickedness and haughtiness is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.132#immediately aroused by way of answer in our probably less beautiful but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.133#harder souls, that is to say, in our more German souls!--"DISONS DONC
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.134#HARDIMENT QUE LA RELIGION EST UN PRODUIT DE L'HOMME NORMAL, QUE L'HOMME
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.135#EST LE PLUS DANS LE VRAI QUANT IL EST LE PLUS RELIGIEUX ET LE PLUS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.136#ASSURE D'UNE DESTINEE INFINIE.... C'EST QUAND IL EST BON QU'IL VEUT QUE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.137#LA VIRTU CORRESPONDE A UN ORDER ETERNAL, C'EST QUAND IL CONTEMPLE LES
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.138#CHOSES D'UNE MANIERE DESINTERESSEE QU'IL TROUVE LA MORT REVOLTANTE ET
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.139#ABSURDE. COMMENT NE PAS SUPPOSER QUE C'EST DANS CES MOMENTS-LA, QUE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.140#L'HOMME VOIT LE MIEUX?"... These sentences are so extremely ANTIPODAL
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.141#to my ears and habits of thought, that in my first impulse of rage
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.142#on finding them, I wrote on the margin, "LA NIAISERIE RELIGIEUSE PAR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.143#EXCELLENCE!"--until in my later rage I even took a fancy to them, these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.144#sentences with their truth absolutely inverted! It is so nice and such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.145#distinction to have one's own antipodes!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.146#49. That which is so astonishing in the religious life of the ancient
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.147#Greeks is the irrestrainable stream of GRATITUDE which it pours
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.148#forth--it is a very superior kind of man who takes SUCH an attitude
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.149#towards nature and life.--Later on, when the populace got the upper hand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.150#in Greece, FEAR became rampant also in religion; and Christianity was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.151#preparing itself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.152#50. The passion for God: there are churlish, honest-hearted, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.153#importunate kinds of it, like that of Luther--the whole of Protestantism
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.154#lacks the southern DELICATEZZA. There is an Oriental exaltation of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.155#mind in it, like that of an undeservedly favoured or elevated slave, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.156#in the case of St. Augustine, for instance, who lacks in an offensive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.157#manner, all nobility in bearing and desires. There is a feminine
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.158#tenderness and sensuality in it, which modestly and unconsciously longs
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.159#for a UNIO MYSTICA ET PHYSICA, as in the case of Madame de Guyon. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.160#many cases it appears, curiously enough, as the disguise of a girl's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.161#or youth's puberty; here and there even as the hysteria of an old maid,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.162#also as her last ambition. The Church has frequently canonized the woman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.163#in such a case.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.164#51. The mightiest men have hitherto always bowed reverently before
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.165#the saint, as the enigma of self-subjugation and utter voluntary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.166#privation--why did they thus bow? They divined in him--and as it were
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.167#behind the questionableness of his frail and wretched appearance--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.168#superior force which wished to test itself by such a subjugation; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.169#strength of will, in which they recognized their own strength and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.170#love of power, and knew how to honour it: they honoured something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.171#in themselves when they honoured the saint. In addition to this, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.172#contemplation of the saint suggested to them a suspicion: such an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.173#enormity of self-negation and anti-naturalness will not have been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.174#coveted for nothing--they have said, inquiringly. There is perhaps a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.175#reason for it, some very great danger, about which the ascetic might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.176#wish to be more accurately informed through his secret interlocutors and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.177#visitors? In a word, the mighty ones of the world learned to have a new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.178#fear before him, they divined a new power, a strange, still unconquered
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.179#enemy:--it was the "Will to Power" which obliged them to halt before the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.180#saint. They had to question him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.181#52. In the Jewish "Old Testament," the book of divine justice, there are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.182#men, things, and sayings on such an immense scale, that Greek and Indian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.183#literature has nothing to compare with it. One stands with fear and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.184#reverence before those stupendous remains of what man was formerly, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.185#one has sad thoughts about old Asia and its little out-pushed peninsula
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.186#Europe, which would like, by all means, to figure before Asia as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.187#"Progress of Mankind." To be sure, he who is himself only a slender,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.188#tame house-animal, and knows only the wants of a house-animal (like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.189#our cultured people of today, including the Christians of "cultured"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.190#Christianity), need neither be amazed nor even sad amid those ruins--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.191#taste for the Old Testament is a touchstone with respect to "great" and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.192#"small": perhaps he will find that the New Testament, the book of grace,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.193#still appeals more to his heart (there is much of the odour of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.194#genuine, tender, stupid beadsman and petty soul in it). To have bound
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.195#up this New Testament (a kind of ROCOCO of taste in every respect) along
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.196#with the Old Testament into one book, as the "Bible," as "The Book in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.197#Itself," is perhaps the greatest audacity and "sin against the Spirit"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.198#which literary Europe has upon its conscience.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.199#53. Why Atheism nowadays? "The father" in God is thoroughly refuted;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.200#equally so "the judge," "the rewarder." Also his "free will": he does
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.201#not hear--and even if he did, he would not know how to help. The worst
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.202#is that he seems incapable of communicating himself clearly; is he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.203#uncertain?--This is what I have made out (by questioning and listening
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.204#at a variety of conversations) to be the cause of the decline of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.205#European theism; it appears to me that though the religious instinct is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.206#in vigorous growth,--it rejects the theistic satisfaction with profound
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.207#distrust.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.208#54. What does all modern philosophy mainly do? Since Descartes--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.209#indeed more in defiance of him than on the basis of his procedure--an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.210#ATTENTAT has been made on the part of all philosophers on the old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.211#conception of the soul, under the guise of a criticism of the subject
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.212#and predicate conception--that is to say, an ATTENTAT on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.213#fundamental presupposition of Christian doctrine. Modern philosophy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.214#as epistemological skepticism, is secretly or openly ANTI-CHRISTIAN,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.215#although (for keener ears, be it said) by no means anti-religious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.216#Formerly, in effect, one believed in "the soul" as one believed in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.217#grammar and the grammatical subject: one said, "I" is the condition,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.218#"think" is the predicate and is conditioned--to think is an activity for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.219#which one MUST suppose a subject as cause. The attempt was then made,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.220#with marvelous tenacity and subtlety, to see if one could not get out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.221#of this net,--to see if the opposite was not perhaps true: "think" the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.222#condition, and "I" the conditioned; "I," therefore, only a synthesis
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.223#which has been MADE by thinking itself. KANT really wished to prove
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.224#that, starting from the subject, the subject could not be proved--nor
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.225#the object either: the possibility of an APPARENT EXISTENCE of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.226#subject, and therefore of "the soul," may not always have been strange
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.227#to him,--the thought which once had an immense power on earth as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.228#Vedanta philosophy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.229#55. There is a great ladder of religious cruelty, with many rounds; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.230#three of these are the most important. Once on a time men sacrificed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.231#human beings to their God, and perhaps just those they loved the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.232#best--to this category belong the firstling sacrifices of all primitive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.233#religions, and also the sacrifice of the Emperor Tiberius in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.234#Mithra-Grotto on the Island of Capri, that most terrible of all Roman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.235#anachronisms. Then, during the moral epoch of mankind, they sacrificed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.236#to their God the strongest instincts they possessed, their "nature";
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.237#THIS festal joy shines in the cruel glances of ascetics and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.238#"anti-natural" fanatics. Finally, what still remained to be sacrificed?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.239#Was it not necessary in the end for men to sacrifice everything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.240#comforting, holy, healing, all hope, all faith in hidden harmonies, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.241#future blessedness and justice? Was it not necessary to sacrifice God
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.242#himself, and out of cruelty to themselves to worship stone, stupidity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.243#gravity, fate, nothingness? To sacrifice God for nothingness--this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.244#paradoxical mystery of the ultimate cruelty has been reserved for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.245#rising generation; we all know something thereof already.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.246#56. Whoever, like myself, prompted by some enigmatical desire, has long
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.247#endeavoured to go to the bottom of the question of pessimism and free it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.248#from the half-Christian, half-German narrowness and stupidity in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.249#it has finally presented itself to this century, namely, in the form of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.250#Schopenhauer's philosophy; whoever, with an Asiatic and super-Asiatic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.251#eye, has actually looked inside, and into the most world-renouncing of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.252#all possible modes of thought--beyond good and evil, and no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.253#like Buddha and Schopenhauer, under the dominion and delusion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.254#morality,--whoever has done this, has perhaps just thereby, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.255#really desiring it, opened his eyes to behold the opposite ideal: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.256#ideal of the most world-approving, exuberant, and vivacious man, who has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.257#not only learnt to compromise and arrange with that which was and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.258#is, but wishes to have it again AS IT WAS AND IS, for all eternity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.259#insatiably calling out da capo, not only to himself, but to the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.260#piece and play; and not only the play, but actually to him who requires
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.261#the play--and makes it necessary; because he always requires
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.262#himself anew--and makes himself necessary.--What? And this would not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.263#be--circulus vitiosus deus?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.264#57. The distance, and as it were the space around man, grows with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.265#strength of his intellectual vision and insight: his world becomes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.266#profounder; new stars, new enigmas, and notions are ever coming into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.267#view. Perhaps everything on which the intellectual eye has exercised
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.268#its acuteness and profundity has just been an occasion for its exercise,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.269#something of a game, something for children and childish minds. Perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.270#the most solemn conceptions that have caused the most fighting and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.271#suffering, the conceptions "God" and "sin," will one day seem to us of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.272#no more importance than a child's plaything or a child's pain seems to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.273#an old man;--and perhaps another plaything and another pain will then
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.274#be necessary once more for "the old man"--always childish enough, an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.275#eternal child!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.276#58. Has it been observed to what extent outward idleness, or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.277#semi-idleness, is necessary to a real religious life (alike for its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.278#favourite microscopic labour of self-examination, and for its soft
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.279#placidity called "prayer," the state of perpetual readiness for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.280#"coming of God"), I mean the idleness with a good conscience, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.281#idleness of olden times and of blood, to which the aristocratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.282#sentiment that work is DISHONOURING--that it vulgarizes body and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.283#soul--is not quite unfamiliar? And that consequently the modern, noisy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.284#time-engrossing, conceited, foolishly proud laboriousness educates
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.285#and prepares for "unbelief" more than anything else? Among these, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.286#instance, who are at present living apart from religion in Germany, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.287#find "free-thinkers" of diversified species and origin, but above all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.288#a majority of those in whom laboriousness from generation to generation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.289#has dissolved the religious instincts; so that they no longer know what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.290#purpose religions serve, and only note their existence in the world
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.291#with a kind of dull astonishment. They feel themselves already fully
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.292#occupied, these good people, be it by their business or by their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.293#pleasures, not to mention the "Fatherland," and the newspapers, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.294#their "family duties"; it seems that they have no time whatever left
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.295#for religion; and above all, it is not obvious to them whether it is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.296#question of a new business or a new pleasure--for it is impossible, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.297#say to themselves, that people should go to church merely to spoil
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.298#their tempers. They are by no means enemies of religious customs;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.299#should certain circumstances, State affairs perhaps, require their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.300#participation in such customs, they do what is required, as so many
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.301#things are done--with a patient and unassuming seriousness, and without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.302#much curiosity or discomfort;--they live too much apart and outside
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.303#to feel even the necessity for a FOR or AGAINST in such matters. Among
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.304#those indifferent persons may be reckoned nowadays the majority of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.305#German Protestants of the middle classes, especially in the great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.306#laborious centres of trade and commerce; also the majority of laborious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.307#scholars, and the entire University personnel (with the exception of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.308#the theologians, whose existence and possibility there always gives
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.309#psychologists new and more subtle puzzles to solve). On the part of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.310#pious, or merely church-going people, there is seldom any idea of HOW
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.311#MUCH good-will, one might say arbitrary will, is now necessary for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.312#German scholar to take the problem of religion seriously; his whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.313#profession (and as I have said, his whole workmanlike laboriousness, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.314#which he is compelled by his modern conscience) inclines him to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.315#lofty and almost charitable serenity as regards religion, with which is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.316#occasionally mingled a slight disdain for the "uncleanliness" of spirit
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.317#which he takes for granted wherever any one still professes to belong
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.318#to the Church. It is only with the help of history (NOT through his own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.319#personal experience, therefore) that the scholar succeeds in bringing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.320#himself to a respectful seriousness, and to a certain timid deference
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.321#in presence of religions; but even when his sentiments have reached the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.322#stage of gratitude towards them, he has not personally advanced one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.323#step nearer to that which still maintains itself as Church or as piety;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.324#perhaps even the contrary. The practical indifference to religious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.325#matters in the midst of which he has been born and brought up, usually
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.326#sublimates itself in his case into circumspection and cleanliness, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.327#shuns contact with religious men and things; and it may be just the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.328#depth of his tolerance and humanity which prompts him to avoid the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.329#delicate trouble which tolerance itself brings with it.--Every age has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.330#its own divine type of naivete, for the discovery of which other ages
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.331#may envy it: and how much naivete--adorable, childlike, and boundlessly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.332#foolish naivete is involved in this belief of the scholar in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.333#his superiority, in the good conscience of his tolerance, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.334#unsuspecting, simple certainty with which his instinct treats the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.335#religious man as a lower and less valuable type, beyond, before, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.336#ABOVE which he himself has developed--he, the little arrogant dwarf
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.337#and mob-man, the sedulously alert, head-and-hand drudge of "ideas," of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.338#"modern ideas"!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.339#59. Whoever has seen deeply into the world has doubtless divined what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.340#wisdom there is in the fact that men are superficial. It is their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.341#preservative instinct which teaches them to be flighty, lightsome, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.342#false. Here and there one finds a passionate and exaggerated adoration
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.343#of "pure forms" in philosophers as well as in artists: it is not to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.344#doubted that whoever has NEED of the cult of the superficial to that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.345#extent, has at one time or another made an unlucky dive BENEATH it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.346#Perhaps there is even an order of rank with respect to those burnt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.347#children, the born artists who find the enjoyment of life only in trying
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.348#to FALSIFY its image (as if taking wearisome revenge on it), one might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.349#guess to what degree life has disgusted them, by the extent to which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.350#they wish to see its image falsified, attenuated, ultrified, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.351#deified,--one might reckon the homines religiosi among the artists, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.352#their HIGHEST rank. It is the profound, suspicious fear of an incurable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.353#pessimism which compels whole centuries to fasten their teeth into a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.354#religious interpretation of existence: the fear of the instinct which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.355#divines that truth might be attained TOO soon, before man has become
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.356#strong enough, hard enough, artist enough.... Piety, the "Life in God,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.357#regarded in this light, would appear as the most elaborate and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.358#ultimate product of the FEAR of truth, as artist-adoration
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.359#and artist-intoxication in presence of the most logical of all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.360#falsifications, as the will to the inversion of truth, to untruth at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.361#any price. Perhaps there has hitherto been no more effective means of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.362#beautifying man than piety, by means of it man can become so artful, so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.363#superficial, so iridescent, and so good, that his appearance no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.364#offends.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.365#60. To love mankind FOR GOD'S SAKE--this has so far been the noblest and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.366#remotest sentiment to which mankind has attained. That love to mankind,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.367#without any redeeming intention in the background, is only an ADDITIONAL
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.368#folly and brutishness, that the inclination to this love has first to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.369#get its proportion, its delicacy, its gram of salt and sprinkling
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.370#of ambergris from a higher inclination--whoever first perceived
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.371#and "experienced" this, however his tongue may have stammered as it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.372#attempted to express such a delicate matter, let him for all time be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.373#holy and respected, as the man who has so far flown highest and gone
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.374#astray in the finest fashion!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.375#61. The philosopher, as WE free spirits understand him--as the man of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.376#the greatest responsibility, who has the conscience for the general
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.377#development of mankind,--will use religion for his disciplining and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.378#educating work, just as he will use the contemporary political
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.379#and economic conditions. The selecting and disciplining
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.380#influence--destructive, as well as creative and fashioning--which can be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.381#exercised by means of religion is manifold and varied, according to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.382#sort of people placed under its spell and protection. For those who are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.383#strong and independent, destined and trained to command, in whom the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.384#judgment and skill of a ruling race is incorporated, religion is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.385#an additional means for overcoming resistance in the exercise of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.386#authority--as a bond which binds rulers and subjects in common,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.387#betraying and surrendering to the former the conscience of the latter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.388#their inmost heart, which would fain escape obedience. And in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.389#case of the unique natures of noble origin, if by virtue of superior
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.390#spirituality they should incline to a more retired and contemplative
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.391#life, reserving to themselves only the more refined forms of government
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.392#(over chosen disciples or members of an order), religion itself may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.393#be used as a means for obtaining peace from the noise and trouble of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.394#managing GROSSER affairs, and for securing immunity from the UNAVOIDABLE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.395#filth of all political agitation. The Brahmins, for instance, understood
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.396#this fact. With the help of a religious organization, they secured to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.397#themselves the power of nominating kings for the people, while their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.398#sentiments prompted them to keep apart and outside, as men with a higher
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.399#and super-regal mission. At the same time religion gives inducement and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.400#opportunity to some of the subjects to qualify themselves for future
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.401#ruling and commanding the slowly ascending ranks and classes, in which,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.402#through fortunate marriage customs, volitional power and delight in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.403#self-control are on the increase. To them religion offers sufficient
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.404#incentives and temptations to aspire to higher intellectuality, and to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.405#experience the sentiments of authoritative self-control, of silence, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.406#of solitude. Asceticism and Puritanism are almost indispensable means of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.407#educating and ennobling a race which seeks to rise above its hereditary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.408#baseness and work itself upwards to future supremacy. And finally, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.409#ordinary men, to the majority of the people, who exist for service and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.410#general utility, and are only so far entitled to exist, religion gives
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.411#invaluable contentedness with their lot and condition, peace of heart,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.412#ennoblement of obedience, additional social happiness and sympathy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.413#with something of transfiguration and embellishment, something of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.414#justification of all the commonplaceness, all the meanness, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.415#the semi-animal poverty of their souls. Religion, together with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.416#religious significance of life, sheds sunshine over such perpetually
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.417#harassed men, and makes even their own aspect endurable to them, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.418#operates upon them as the Epicurean philosophy usually operates upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.419#sufferers of a higher order, in a refreshing and refining manner,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.420#almost TURNING suffering TO ACCOUNT, and in the end even hallowing and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.421#vindicating it. There is perhaps nothing so admirable in Christianity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.422#and Buddhism as their art of teaching even the lowest to elevate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.423#themselves by piety to a seemingly higher order of things, and thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.424#to retain their satisfaction with the actual world in which they find it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.425#difficult enough to live--this very difficulty being necessary.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.426#62. To be sure--to make also the bad counter-reckoning against such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.427#religions, and to bring to light their secret dangers--the cost is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.428#always excessive and terrible when religions do NOT operate as an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.429#educational and disciplinary medium in the hands of the philosopher, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.430#rule voluntarily and PARAMOUNTLY, when they wish to be the final end,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.431#and not a means along with other means. Among men, as among all other
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.432#animals, there is a surplus of defective, diseased, degenerating,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.433#infirm, and necessarily suffering individuals; the successful cases,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.434#among men also, are always the exception; and in view of the fact that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.435#man is THE ANIMAL NOT YET PROPERLY ADAPTED TO HIS ENVIRONMENT, the rare
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.436#exception. But worse still. The higher the type a man represents, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.437#greater is the improbability that he will SUCCEED; the accidental, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.438#law of irrationality in the general constitution of mankind, manifests
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.439#itself most terribly in its destructive effect on the higher orders of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.440#men, the conditions of whose lives are delicate, diverse, and difficult
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.441#to determine. What, then, is the attitude of the two greatest religions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.442#above-mentioned to the SURPLUS of failures in life? They endeavour
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.443#to preserve and keep alive whatever can be preserved; in fact, as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.444#religions FOR SUFFERERS, they take the part of these upon principle;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.445#they are always in favour of those who suffer from life as from a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.446#disease, and they would fain treat every other experience of life as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.447#false and impossible. However highly we may esteem this indulgent and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.448#preservative care (inasmuch as in applying to others, it has applied,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.449#and applies also to the highest and usually the most suffering type of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.450#man), the hitherto PARAMOUNT religions--to give a general appreciation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.451#of them--are among the principal causes which have kept the type of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.452#"man" upon a lower level--they have preserved too much THAT WHICH SHOULD
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.453#HAVE PERISHED. One has to thank them for invaluable services; and who is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.454#sufficiently rich in gratitude not to feel poor at the contemplation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.455#of all that the "spiritual men" of Christianity have done for Europe
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.456#hitherto! But when they had given comfort to the sufferers, courage to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.457#the oppressed and despairing, a staff and support to the helpless,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.458#and when they had allured from society into convents and spiritual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.459#penitentiaries the broken-hearted and distracted: what else had they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.460#to do in order to work systematically in that fashion, and with a good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.461#conscience, for the preservation of all the sick and suffering, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.462#means, in deed and in truth, to work for the DETERIORATION OF THE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.463#EUROPEAN RACE? To REVERSE all estimates of value--THAT is what they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.464#had to do! And to shatter the strong, to spoil great hopes, to cast
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.465#suspicion on the delight in beauty, to break down everything autonomous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.466#manly, conquering, and imperious--all instincts which are natural to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.467#highest and most successful type of "man"--into uncertainty, distress
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.468#of conscience, and self-destruction; forsooth, to invert all love of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.469#earthly and of supremacy over the earth, into hatred of the earth and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.470#earthly things--THAT is the task the Church imposed on itself, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.471#was obliged to impose, until, according to its standard of value,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.472#"unworldliness," "unsensuousness," and "higher man" fused into one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.473#sentiment. If one could observe the strangely painful, equally coarse
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.474#and refined comedy of European Christianity with the derisive and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.475#impartial eye of an Epicurean god, I should think one would never cease
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.476#marvelling and laughing; does it not actually seem that some single will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.477#has ruled over Europe for eighteen centuries in order to make a SUBLIME
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.478#ABORTION of man? He, however, who, with opposite requirements (no longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.479#Epicurean) and with some divine hammer in his hand, could approach this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.480#almost voluntary degeneration and stunting of mankind, as exemplified in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.481#the European Christian (Pascal, for instance), would he not have to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.482#cry aloud with rage, pity, and horror: "Oh, you bunglers, presumptuous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.483#pitiful bunglers, what have you done! Was that a work for your hands?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.484#How you have hacked and botched my finest stone! What have you presumed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.485#to do!"--I should say that Christianity has hitherto been the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.486#portentous of presumptions. Men, not great enough, nor hard enough,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.487#to be entitled as artists to take part in fashioning MAN; men,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.488#not sufficiently strong and far-sighted to ALLOW, with sublime
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.489#self-constraint, the obvious law of the thousandfold failures and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.490#perishings to prevail; men, not sufficiently noble to see the radically
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.491#different grades of rank and intervals of rank that separate man from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.492#man:--SUCH men, with their "equality before God," have hitherto swayed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.493#the destiny of Europe; until at last a dwarfed, almost ludicrous species
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.494#has been produced, a gregarious animal, something obliging, sickly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:3.495#mediocre, the European of the present day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.1#CHAPTER IV. APOPHTHEGMS AND INTERLUDES
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.2#63. He who is a thorough teacher takes things seriously--and even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.3#himself--only in relation to his pupils.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.4#64. "Knowledge for its own sake"--that is the last snare laid by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.5#morality: we are thereby completely entangled in morals once more.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.6#65. The charm of knowledge would be small, were it not so much shame has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.7#to be overcome on the way to it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.8#65A. We are most dishonourable towards our God: he is not PERMITTED to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.9#sin.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.10#66. The tendency of a person to allow himself to be degraded, robbed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.11#deceived, and exploited might be the diffidence of a God among men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.12#67. Love to one only is a barbarity, for it is exercised at the expense
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.13#of all others. Love to God also!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.14#68. "I did that," says my memory. "I could not have done that," says my
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.15#pride, and remains inexorable. Eventually--the memory yields.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.16#69. One has regarded life carelessly, if one has failed to see the hand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.17#that--kills with leniency.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.18#70. If a man has character, he has also his typical experience, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.19#always recurs.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.20#71. THE SAGE AS ASTRONOMER.--So long as thou feelest the stars as an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.21#"above thee," thou lackest the eye of the discerning one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.22#72. It is not the strength, but the duration of great sentiments that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.23#makes great men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.24#73. He who attains his ideal, precisely thereby surpasses it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.25#73A. Many a peacock hides his tail from every eye--and calls it his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.26#pride.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.27#74. A man of genius is unbearable, unless he possess at least two things
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.28#besides: gratitude and purity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.29#75. The degree and nature of a man's sensuality extends to the highest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.30#altitudes of his spirit.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.31#76. Under peaceful conditions the militant man attacks himself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.32#77. With his principles a man seeks either to dominate, or justify,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.33#or honour, or reproach, or conceal his habits: two men with the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.34#principles probably seek fundamentally different ends therewith.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.35#78. He who despises himself, nevertheless esteems himself thereby, as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.36#despiser.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.37#79. A soul which knows that it is loved, but does not itself love,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.38#betrays its sediment: its dregs come up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.39#80. A thing that is explained ceases to concern us--What did the God
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.40#mean who gave the advice, "Know thyself!" Did it perhaps imply "Cease to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.41#be concerned about thyself! become objective!"--And Socrates?--And the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.42#"scientific man"?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.43#81. It is terrible to die of thirst at sea. Is it necessary that you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.44#should so salt your truth that it will no longer--quench thirst?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.45#82. "Sympathy for all"--would be harshness and tyranny for THEE, my good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.46#neighbour.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.47#83. INSTINCT--When the house is on fire one forgets even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.48#dinner--Yes, but one recovers it from among the ashes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.49#84. Woman learns how to hate in proportion as she--forgets how to charm.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.50#85. The same emotions are in man and woman, but in different TEMPO, on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.51#that account man and woman never cease to misunderstand each other.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.52#86. In the background of all their personal vanity, women themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.53#have still their impersonal scorn--for "woman".
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.54#87. FETTERED HEART, FREE SPIRIT--When one firmly fetters one's heart
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.55#and keeps it prisoner, one can allow one's spirit many liberties: I said
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.56#this once before But people do not believe it when I say so, unless they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.57#know it already.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.58#88. One begins to distrust very clever persons when they become
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.59#embarrassed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.60#89. Dreadful experiences raise the question whether he who experiences
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.61#them is not something dreadful also.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.62#90. Heavy, melancholy men turn lighter, and come temporarily to their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.63#surface, precisely by that which makes others heavy--by hatred and love.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.64#91. So cold, so icy, that one burns one's finger at the touch of him!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.65#Every hand that lays hold of him shrinks back!--And for that very reason
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.66#many think him red-hot.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.67#92. Who has not, at one time or another--sacrificed himself for the sake
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.68#of his good name?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.69#93. In affability there is no hatred of men, but precisely on that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.70#account a great deal too much contempt of men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.71#94. The maturity of man--that means, to have reacquired the seriousness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.72#that one had as a child at play.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.73#95. To be ashamed of one's immorality is a step on the ladder at the end
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.74#of which one is ashamed also of one's morality.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.75#96. One should part from life as Ulysses parted from Nausicaa--blessing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.76#it rather than in love with it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.77#97. What? A great man? I always see merely the play-actor of his own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.78#ideal.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.79#98. When one trains one's conscience, it kisses one while it bites.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.80#99. THE DISAPPOINTED ONE SPEAKS--"I listened for the echo and I heard
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.81#only praise."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.82#100. We all feign to ourselves that we are simpler than we are, we thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.83#relax ourselves away from our fellows.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.84#101. A discerning one might easily regard himself at present as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.85#animalization of God.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.86#102. Discovering reciprocal love should really disenchant the lover with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.87#regard to the beloved. "What! She is modest enough to love even you? Or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.88#stupid enough? Or--or---"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.89#103. THE DANGER IN HAPPINESS.--"Everything now turns out best for me, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.90#now love every fate:--who would like to be my fate?"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.91#104. Not their love of humanity, but the impotence of their love,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.92#prevents the Christians of today--burning us.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.93#105. The pia fraus is still more repugnant to the taste (the "piety")
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.94#of the free spirit (the "pious man of knowledge") than the impia fraus.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.95#Hence the profound lack of judgment, in comparison with the Church,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.96#characteristic of the type "free spirit"--as ITS non-freedom.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.97#106. By means of music the very passions enjoy themselves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.98#107. A sign of strong character, when once the resolution has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.99#taken, to shut the ear even to the best counter-arguments. Occasionally,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.100#therefore, a will to stupidity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.101#108. There is no such thing as moral phenomena, but only a moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.102#interpretation of phenomena.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.103#109. The criminal is often enough not equal to his deed: he extenuates
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.104#and maligns it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.105#110. The advocates of a criminal are seldom artists enough to turn the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.106#beautiful terribleness of the deed to the advantage of the doer.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.107#111. Our vanity is most difficult to wound just when our pride has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.108#wounded.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.109#112. To him who feels himself preordained to contemplation and not to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.110#belief, all believers are too noisy and obtrusive; he guards against
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.111#them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.112#113. "You want to prepossess him in your favour? Then you must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.113#embarrassed before him."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.114#114. The immense expectation with regard to sexual love, and the coyness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.115#in this expectation, spoils all the perspectives of women at the outset.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.116#115. Where there is neither love nor hatred in the game, woman's play is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.117#mediocre.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.118#116. The great epochs of our life are at the points when we gain courage
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.119#to rebaptize our badness as the best in us.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.120#117. The will to overcome an emotion, is ultimately only the will of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.121#another, or of several other, emotions.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.122#118. There is an innocence of admiration: it is possessed by him to whom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.123#it has not yet occurred that he himself may be admired some day.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.124#119. Our loathing of dirt may be so great as to prevent our cleaning
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.125#ourselves--"justifying" ourselves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.126#120. Sensuality often forces the growth of love too much, so that its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.127#root remains weak, and is easily torn up.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.128#121. It is a curious thing that God learned Greek when he wished to turn
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.129#author--and that he did not learn it better.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.130#122. To rejoice on account of praise is in many cases merely politeness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.131#of heart--and the very opposite of vanity of spirit.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.132#123. Even concubinage has been corrupted--by marriage.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.133#124. He who exults at the stake, does not triumph over pain, but because
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.134#of the fact that he does not feel pain where he expected it. A parable.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.135#125. When we have to change an opinion about any one, we charge heavily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.136#to his account the inconvenience he thereby causes us.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.137#126. A nation is a detour of nature to arrive at six or seven great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.138#men.--Yes, and then to get round them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.139#127. In the eyes of all true women science is hostile to the sense of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.140#shame. They feel as if one wished to peep under their skin with it--or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.141#worse still! under their dress and finery.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.142#128. The more abstract the truth you wish to teach, the more must you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.143#allure the senses to it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.144#129. The devil has the most extensive perspectives for God; on that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.145#account he keeps so far away from him:--the devil, in effect, as the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.146#oldest friend of knowledge.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.147#130. What a person IS begins to betray itself when his talent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.148#decreases,--when he ceases to show what he CAN do. Talent is also an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.149#adornment; an adornment is also a concealment.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.150#131. The sexes deceive themselves about each other: the reason is that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.151#in reality they honour and love only themselves (or their own ideal, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.152#express it more agreeably). Thus man wishes woman to be peaceable: but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.153#in fact woman is ESSENTIALLY unpeaceable, like the cat, however well she
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.154#may have assumed the peaceable demeanour.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.155#132. One is punished best for one's virtues.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.156#133. He who cannot find the way to HIS ideal, lives more frivolously and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.157#shamelessly than the man without an ideal.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.158#134. From the senses originate all trustworthiness, all good conscience,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.159#all evidence of truth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.160#135. Pharisaism is not a deterioration of the good man; a considerable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.161#part of it is rather an essential condition of being good.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.162#136. The one seeks an accoucheur for his thoughts, the other seeks some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.163#one whom he can assist: a good conversation thus originates.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.164#137. In intercourse with scholars and artists one readily makes mistakes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.165#of opposite kinds: in a remarkable scholar one not infrequently finds
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.166#a mediocre man; and often, even in a mediocre artist, one finds a very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.167#remarkable man.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.168#138. We do the same when awake as when dreaming: we only invent and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.169#imagine him with whom we have intercourse--and forget it immediately.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.170#139. In revenge and in love woman is more barbarous than man.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.171#140. ADVICE AS A RIDDLE.--"If the band is not to break, bite it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.172#first--secure to make!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.173#141. The belly is the reason why man does not so readily take himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.174#for a God.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.175#142. The chastest utterance I ever heard: "Dans le veritable amour c'est
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.176#l'ame qui enveloppe le corps."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.177#143. Our vanity would like what we do best to pass precisely for what is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.178#most difficult to us.--Concerning the origin of many systems of morals.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.179#144. When a woman has scholarly inclinations there is generally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.180#something wrong with her sexual nature. Barrenness itself conduces to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.181#certain virility of taste; man, indeed, if I may say so, is "the barren
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.182#animal."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.183#145. Comparing man and woman generally, one may say that woman would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.184#not have the genius for adornment, if she had not the instinct for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.185#SECONDARY role.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.186#146. He who fights with monsters should be careful lest he thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.187#become a monster. And if thou gaze long into an abyss, the abyss will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.188#also gaze into thee.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.189#147. From old Florentine novels--moreover, from life: Buona femmina e
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.190#mala femmina vuol bastone.--Sacchetti, Nov. 86.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.191#148. To seduce their neighbour to a favourable opinion, and afterwards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.192#to believe implicitly in this opinion of their neighbour--who can do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.193#this conjuring trick so well as women?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.194#149. That which an age considers evil is usually an unseasonable echo of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.195#what was formerly considered good--the atavism of an old ideal.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.196#150. Around the hero everything becomes a tragedy; around the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.197#demigod everything becomes a satyr-play; and around God everything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.198#becomes--what? perhaps a "world"?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.199#151. It is not enough to possess a talent: one must also have your
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.200#permission to possess it;--eh, my friends?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.201#152. "Where there is the tree of knowledge, there is always Paradise":
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.202#so say the most ancient and the most modern serpents.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.203#153. What is done out of love always takes place beyond good and evil.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.204#154. Objection, evasion, joyous distrust, and love of irony are signs of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.205#health; everything absolute belongs to pathology.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.206#155. The sense of the tragic increases and declines with sensuousness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.207#156. Insanity in individuals is something rare--but in groups, parties,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.208#nations, and epochs it is the rule.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.209#157. The thought of suicide is a great consolation: by means of it one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.210#gets successfully through many a bad night.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.211#158. Not only our reason, but also our conscience, truckles to our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.212#strongest impulse--the tyrant in us.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.213#159. One MUST repay good and ill; but why just to the person who did us
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.214#good or ill?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.215#160. One no longer loves one's knowledge sufficiently after one has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.216#communicated it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.217#161. Poets act shamelessly towards their experiences: they exploit them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.218#162. "Our fellow-creature is not our neighbour, but our neighbour's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.219#neighbour":--so thinks every nation.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.220#163. Love brings to light the noble and hidden qualities of a lover--his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.221#rare and exceptional traits: it is thus liable to be deceptive as to his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.222#normal character.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.223#164. Jesus said to his Jews: "The law was for servants;--love God as I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.224#love him, as his Son! What have we Sons of God to do with morals!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.225#165. IN SIGHT OF EVERY PARTY.--A shepherd has always need of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.226#bell-wether--or he has himself to be a wether occasionally.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.227#166. One may indeed lie with the mouth; but with the accompanying
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.228#grimace one nevertheless tells the truth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.229#167. To vigorous men intimacy is a matter of shame--and something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.230#precious.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.231#168. Christianity gave Eros poison to drink; he did not die of it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.232#certainly, but degenerated to Vice.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.233#169. To talk much about oneself may also be a means of concealing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.234#oneself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.235#170. In praise there is more obtrusiveness than in blame.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.236#171. Pity has an almost ludicrous effect on a man of knowledge, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.237#tender hands on a Cyclops.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.238#172. One occasionally embraces some one or other, out of love to mankind
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.239#(because one cannot embrace all); but this is what one must never
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.240#confess to the individual.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.241#173. One does not hate as long as one disesteems, but only when one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.242#esteems equal or superior.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.243#174. Ye Utilitarians--ye, too, love the UTILE only as a VEHICLE for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.244#your inclinations,--ye, too, really find the noise of its wheels
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.245#insupportable!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.246#175. One loves ultimately one's desires, not the thing desired.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.247#176. The vanity of others is only counter to our taste when it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.248#counter to our vanity.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.249#177. With regard to what "truthfulness" is, perhaps nobody has ever been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.250#sufficiently truthful.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.251#178. One does not believe in the follies of clever men: what a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.252#forfeiture of the rights of man!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.253#179. The consequences of our actions seize us by the forelock, very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.254#indifferent to the fact that we have meanwhile "reformed."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.255#180. There is an innocence in lying which is the sign of good faith in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.256#cause.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.257#181. It is inhuman to bless when one is being cursed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.258#182. The familiarity of superiors embitters one, because it may not be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.259#returned.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.260#183. "I am affected, not because you have deceived me, but because I can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.261#no longer believe in you."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.262#184. There is a haughtiness of kindness which has the appearance of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.263#wickedness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.264#185. "I dislike him."--Why?--"I am not a match for him."--Did any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:4.265#ever answer so?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.1#CHAPTER V. THE NATURAL HISTORY OF MORALS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.2#186. The moral sentiment in Europe at present is perhaps as subtle,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.3#belated, diverse, sensitive, and refined, as the "Science of Morals"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.4#belonging thereto is recent, initial, awkward, and coarse-fingered:--an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.5#interesting contrast, which sometimes becomes incarnate and obvious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.6#in the very person of a moralist. Indeed, the expression, "Science
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.7#of Morals" is, in respect to what is designated thereby, far too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.8#presumptuous and counter to GOOD taste,--which is always a foretaste of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.9#more modest expressions. One ought to avow with the utmost fairness WHAT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.10#is still necessary here for a long time, WHAT is alone proper for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.11#present: namely, the collection of material, the comprehensive survey
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.12#and classification of an immense domain of delicate sentiments of worth,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.13#and distinctions of worth, which live, grow, propagate, and perish--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.14#perhaps attempts to give a clear idea of the recurring and more common
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.15#forms of these living crystallizations--as preparation for a THEORY OF
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.16#TYPES of morality. To be sure, people have not hitherto been so modest.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.17#All the philosophers, with a pedantic and ridiculous seriousness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.18#demanded of themselves something very much higher, more pretentious, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.19#ceremonious, when they concerned themselves with morality as a science:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.20#they wanted to GIVE A BASIC to morality--and every philosopher hitherto
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.21#has believed that he has given it a basis; morality itself, however, has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.22#been regarded as something "given." How far from their awkward pride
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.23#was the seemingly insignificant problem--left in dust and decay--of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.24#description of forms of morality, notwithstanding that the finest hands
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.25#and senses could hardly be fine enough for it! It was precisely owing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.26#moral philosophers' knowing the moral facts imperfectly, in an arbitrary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.27#epitome, or an accidental abridgement--perhaps as the morality of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.28#their environment, their position, their church, their Zeitgeist, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.29#climate and zone--it was precisely because they were badly instructed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.30#with regard to nations, eras, and past ages, and were by no means eager
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.31#to know about these matters, that they did not even come in sight of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.32#real problems of morals--problems which only disclose themselves by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.33#a comparison of MANY kinds of morality. In every "Science of Morals"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.34#hitherto, strange as it may sound, the problem of morality itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.35#has been OMITTED: there has been no suspicion that there was anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.36#problematic there! That which philosophers called "giving a basis to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.37#morality," and endeavoured to realize, has, when seen in a right light,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.38#proved merely a learned form of good FAITH in prevailing morality, a new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.39#means of its EXPRESSION, consequently just a matter-of-fact within the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.40#sphere of a definite morality, yea, in its ultimate motive, a sort of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.41#denial that it is LAWFUL for this morality to be called in question--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.42#in any case the reverse of the testing, analyzing, doubting, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.43#vivisecting of this very faith. Hear, for instance, with what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.44#innocence--almost worthy of honour--Schopenhauer represents his own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.45#task, and draw your conclusions concerning the scientificness of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.46#"Science" whose latest master still talks in the strain of children and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.47#old wives: "The principle," he says (page 136 of the Grundprobleme der
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.48#Ethik), [Footnote: Pages 54-55 of Schopenhauer's Basis of Morality,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.49#translated by Arthur B. Bullock, M.A. (1903).] "the axiom about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.50#purport of which all moralists are PRACTICALLY agreed: neminem laede,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.51#immo omnes quantum potes juva--is REALLY the proposition which all moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.52#teachers strive to establish, ... the REAL basis of ethics which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.53#has been sought, like the philosopher's stone, for centuries."--The
