urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.239#of every twenty words at random, and "guesses" the probably appropriate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.240#sense to them--just as little do we see a tree correctly and completely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.241#in respect to its leaves, branches, colour, and shape; we find it so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.242#much easier to fancy the chance of a tree. Even in the midst of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.243#most remarkable experiences, we still do just the same; we fabricate the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.244#greater part of the experience, and can hardly be made to contemplate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.245#any event, EXCEPT as "inventors" thereof. All this goes to prove
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.246#that from our fundamental nature and from remote ages we have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.247#been--ACCUSTOMED TO LYING. Or, to express it more politely and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.248#hypocritically, in short, more pleasantly--one is much more of an artist
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.249#than one is aware of.--In an animated conversation, I often see the face
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.250#of the person with whom I am speaking so clearly and sharply defined
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.251#before me, according to the thought he expresses, or which I believe to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.252#be evoked in his mind, that the degree of distinctness far exceeds the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.253#STRENGTH of my visual faculty--the delicacy of the play of the muscles
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.254#and of the expression of the eyes MUST therefore be imagined by me.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.255#Probably the person put on quite a different expression, or none at all.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.256#193. Quidquid luce fuit, tenebris agit: but also contrariwise. What we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.257#experience in dreams, provided we experience it often, pertains at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.258#last just as much to the general belongings of our soul as anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.259#"actually" experienced; by virtue thereof we are richer or poorer, we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.260#have a requirement more or less, and finally, in broad daylight, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.261#even in the brightest moments of our waking life, we are ruled to some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.262#extent by the nature of our dreams. Supposing that someone has often
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.263#flown in his dreams, and that at last, as soon as he dreams, he is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.264#conscious of the power and art of flying as his privilege and his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.265#peculiarly enviable happiness; such a person, who believes that on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.266#slightest impulse, he can actualize all sorts of curves and angles, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.267#knows the sensation of a certain divine levity, an "upwards"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.268#without effort or constraint, a "downwards" without descending
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.269#or lowering--without TROUBLE!--how could the man with such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.270#dream-experiences and dream-habits fail to find "happiness" differently
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.271#coloured and defined, even in his waking hours! How could he fail--to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.272#long DIFFERENTLY for happiness? "Flight," such as is described by poets,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.273#must, when compared with his own "flying," be far too earthly, muscular,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.274#violent, far too "troublesome" for him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.275#194. The difference among men does not manifest itself only in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.276#difference of their lists of desirable things--in their regarding
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.277#different good things as worth striving for, and being disagreed as to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.278#the greater or less value, the order of rank, of the commonly recognized
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.279#desirable things:--it manifests itself much more in what they regard as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.280#actually HAVING and POSSESSING a desirable thing. As regards a woman,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.281#for instance, the control over her body and her sexual gratification
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.282#serves as an amply sufficient sign of ownership and possession to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.283#more modest man; another with a more suspicious and ambitious thirst for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.284#possession, sees the "questionableness," the mere apparentness of such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.285#ownership, and wishes to have finer tests in order to know especially
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.286#whether the woman not only gives herself to him, but also gives up for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.287#his sake what she has or would like to have--only THEN does he look upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.288#her as "possessed." A third, however, has not even here got to the limit
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.289#of his distrust and his desire for possession: he asks himself whether
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.290#the woman, when she gives up everything for him, does not perhaps do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.291#so for a phantom of him; he wishes first to be thoroughly, indeed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.292#profoundly well known; in order to be loved at all he ventures to let
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.293#himself be found out. Only then does he feel the beloved one fully in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.294#his possession, when she no longer deceives herself about him, when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.295#she loves him just as much for the sake of his devilry and concealed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.296#insatiability, as for his goodness, patience, and spirituality. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.297#man would like to possess a nation, and he finds all the higher arts of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.298#Cagliostro and Catalina suitable for his purpose. Another, with a more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.299#refined thirst for possession, says to himself: "One may not deceive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.300#where one desires to possess"--he is irritated and impatient at the idea
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.301#that a mask of him should rule in the hearts of the people: "I must,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.302#therefore, MAKE myself known, and first of all learn to know myself!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.303#Among helpful and charitable people, one almost always finds the awkward
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.304#craftiness which first gets up suitably him who has to be helped, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.305#though, for instance, he should "merit" help, seek just THEIR help, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.306#would show himself deeply grateful, attached, and subservient to them
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.307#for all help. With these conceits, they take control of the needy as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.308#property, just as in general they are charitable and helpful out of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.309#desire for property. One finds them jealous when they are crossed or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.310#forestalled in their charity. Parents involuntarily make something like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.311#themselves out of their children--they call that "education"; no mother
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.312#doubts at the bottom of her heart that the child she has borne is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.313#thereby her property, no father hesitates about his right to HIS OWN
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.314#ideas and notions of worth. Indeed, in former times fathers deemed it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.315#right to use their discretion concerning the life or death of the newly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.316#born (as among the ancient Germans). And like the father, so also do the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.317#teacher, the class, the priest, and the prince still see in every new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.318#individual an unobjectionable opportunity for a new possession. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.319#consequence is...
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.320#195. The Jews--a people "born for slavery," as Tacitus and the whole
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.321#ancient world say of them; "the chosen people among the nations," as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.322#they themselves say and believe--the Jews performed the miracle of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.323#inversion of valuations, by means of which life on earth obtained a new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.324#and dangerous charm for a couple of millenniums. Their prophets fused
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.325#into one the expressions "rich," "godless," "wicked," "violent,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.326#"sensual," and for the first time coined the word "world" as a term of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.327#reproach. In this inversion of valuations (in which is also included
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.328#the use of the word "poor" as synonymous with "saint" and "friend") the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.329#significance of the Jewish people is to be found; it is with THEM that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.330#the SLAVE-INSURRECTION IN MORALS commences.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.331#196. It is to be INFERRED that there are countless dark bodies near the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.332#sun--such as we shall never see. Among ourselves, this is an allegory;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.333#and the psychologist of morals reads the whole star-writing merely as an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.334#allegorical and symbolic language in which much may be unexpressed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.335#197. The beast of prey and the man of prey (for instance, Caesar Borgia)
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.336#are fundamentally misunderstood, "nature" is misunderstood, so long as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.337#one seeks a "morbidness" in the constitution of these healthiest of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.338#all tropical monsters and growths, or even an innate "hell" in them--as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.339#almost all moralists have done hitherto. Does it not seem that there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.340#a hatred of the virgin forest and of the tropics among moralists? And
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.341#that the "tropical man" must be discredited at all costs, whether
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.342#as disease and deterioration of mankind, or as his own hell and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.343#self-torture? And why? In favour of the "temperate zones"? In favour
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.344#of the temperate men? The "moral"? The mediocre?--This for the chapter:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.345#"Morals as Timidity."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.346#198. All the systems of morals which address themselves with a view to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.347#their "happiness," as it is called--what else are they but suggestions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.348#for behaviour adapted to the degree of DANGER from themselves in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.349#the individuals live; recipes for their passions, their good and bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.350#propensities, insofar as such have the Will to Power and would like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.351#to play the master; small and great expediencies and elaborations,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.352#permeated with the musty odour of old family medicines and old-wife
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.353#wisdom; all of them grotesque and absurd in their form--because
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.354#they address themselves to "all," because they generalize where
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.355#generalization is not authorized; all of them speaking unconditionally,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.356#and taking themselves unconditionally; all of them flavoured not merely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.357#with one grain of salt, but rather endurable only, and sometimes even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.358#seductive, when they are over-spiced and begin to smell dangerously,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.359#especially of "the other world." That is all of little value when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.360#estimated intellectually, and is far from being "science," much less
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.361#"wisdom"; but, repeated once more, and three times repeated, it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.362#expediency, expediency, expediency, mixed with stupidity, stupidity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.363#stupidity--whether it be the indifference and statuesque coldness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.364#towards the heated folly of the emotions, which the Stoics advised and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.365#fostered; or the no-more-laughing and no-more-weeping of Spinoza, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.366#destruction of the emotions by their analysis and vivisection, which he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.367#recommended so naively; or the lowering of the emotions to an innocent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.368#mean at which they may be satisfied, the Aristotelianism of morals;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.369#or even morality as the enjoyment of the emotions in a voluntary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.370#attenuation and spiritualization by the symbolism of art, perhaps as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.371#music, or as love of God, and of mankind for God's sake--for in religion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.372#the passions are once more enfranchised, provided that...; or, finally,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.373#even the complaisant and wanton surrender to the emotions, as has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.374#been taught by Hafis and Goethe, the bold letting-go of the reins, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.375#spiritual and corporeal licentia morum in the exceptional cases of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.376#wise old codgers and drunkards, with whom it "no longer has much
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.377#danger."--This also for the chapter: "Morals as Timidity."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.378#199. Inasmuch as in all ages, as long as mankind has existed, there have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.379#also been human herds (family alliances, communities, tribes, peoples,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.380#states, churches), and always a great number who obey in proportion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.381#to the small number who command--in view, therefore, of the fact that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.382#obedience has been most practiced and fostered among mankind hitherto,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.383#one may reasonably suppose that, generally speaking, the need thereof is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.384#now innate in every one, as a kind of FORMAL CONSCIENCE which gives
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.385#the command "Thou shalt unconditionally do something, unconditionally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.386#refrain from something", in short, "Thou shalt". This need tries to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.387#satisfy itself and to fill its form with a content, according to its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.388#strength, impatience, and eagerness, it at once seizes as an omnivorous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.389#appetite with little selection, and accepts whatever is shouted into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.390#its ear by all sorts of commanders--parents, teachers, laws, class
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.391#prejudices, or public opinion. The extraordinary limitation of human
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.392#development, the hesitation, protractedness, frequent retrogression, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.393#turning thereof, is attributable to the fact that the herd-instinct of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.394#obedience is transmitted best, and at the cost of the art of command. If
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.395#one imagine this instinct increasing to its greatest extent, commanders
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.396#and independent individuals will finally be lacking altogether, or they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.397#will suffer inwardly from a bad conscience, and will have to impose
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.398#a deception on themselves in the first place in order to be able to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.399#command just as if they also were only obeying. This condition of things
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.400#actually exists in Europe at present--I call it the moral hypocrisy of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.401#the commanding class. They know no other way of protecting themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.402#from their bad conscience than by playing the role of executors of older
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.403#and higher orders (of predecessors, of the constitution, of justice, of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.404#the law, or of God himself), or they even justify themselves by maxims
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.405#from the current opinions of the herd, as "first servants of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.406#people," or "instruments of the public weal". On the other hand, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.407#gregarious European man nowadays assumes an air as if he were the only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.408#kind of man that is allowable, he glorifies his qualities, such as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.409#public spirit, kindness, deference, industry, temperance, modesty,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.410#indulgence, sympathy, by virtue of which he is gentle, endurable, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.411#useful to the herd, as the peculiarly human virtues. In cases, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.412#where it is believed that the leader and bell-wether cannot be dispensed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.413#with, attempt after attempt is made nowadays to replace commanders
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.414#by the summing together of clever gregarious men all representative
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.415#constitutions, for example, are of this origin. In spite of all, what a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.416#blessing, what a deliverance from a weight becoming unendurable, is the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.417#appearance of an absolute ruler for these gregarious Europeans--of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.418#fact the effect of the appearance of Napoleon was the last great proof
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.419#the history of the influence of Napoleon is almost the history of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.420#the higher happiness to which the entire century has attained in its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.421#worthiest individuals and periods.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.422#200. The man of an age of dissolution which mixes the races with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.423#one another, who has the inheritance of a diversified descent in his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.424#body--that is to say, contrary, and often not only contrary, instincts
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.425#and standards of value, which struggle with one another and are seldom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.426#at peace--such a man of late culture and broken lights, will, on an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.427#average, be a weak man. His fundamental desire is that the war which is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.428#IN HIM should come to an end; happiness appears to him in the character
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.429#of a soothing medicine and mode of thought (for instance, Epicurean
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.430#or Christian); it is above all things the happiness of repose, of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.431#undisturbedness, of repletion, of final unity--it is the "Sabbath of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.432#Sabbaths," to use the expression of the holy rhetorician, St. Augustine,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.433#who was himself such a man.--Should, however, the contrariety and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.434#conflict in such natures operate as an ADDITIONAL incentive and stimulus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.435#to life--and if, on the other hand, in addition to their powerful and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.436#irreconcilable instincts, they have also inherited and indoctrinated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.437#into them a proper mastery and subtlety for carrying on the conflict
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.438#with themselves (that is to say, the faculty of self-control and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.439#self-deception), there then arise those marvelously incomprehensible and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.440#inexplicable beings, those enigmatical men, predestined for conquering
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.441#and circumventing others, the finest examples of which are Alcibiades
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.442#and Caesar (with whom I should like to associate the FIRST of Europeans
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.443#according to my taste, the Hohenstaufen, Frederick the Second), and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.444#among artists, perhaps Leonardo da Vinci. They appear precisely in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.445#same periods when that weaker type, with its longing for repose, comes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.446#to the front; the two types are complementary to each other, and spring
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.447#from the same causes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.448#201. As long as the utility which determines moral estimates is only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.449#gregarious utility, as long as the preservation of the community is only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.450#kept in view, and the immoral is sought precisely and exclusively in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.451#what seems dangerous to the maintenance of the community, there can be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.452#no "morality of love to one's neighbour." Granted even that there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.453#already a little constant exercise of consideration, sympathy, fairness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.454#gentleness, and mutual assistance, granted that even in this condition
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.455#of society all those instincts are already active which are latterly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.456#distinguished by honourable names as "virtues," and eventually almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.457#coincide with the conception "morality": in that period they do not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.458#as yet belong to the domain of moral valuations--they are still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.459#ULTRA-MORAL. A sympathetic action, for instance, is neither called good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.460#nor bad, moral nor immoral, in the best period of the Romans; and should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.461#it be praised, a sort of resentful disdain is compatible with this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.462#praise, even at the best, directly the sympathetic action is compared
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.463#with one which contributes to the welfare of the whole, to the RES
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.464#PUBLICA. After all, "love to our neighbour" is always a secondary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.465#matter, partly conventional and arbitrarily manifested in relation to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.466#our FEAR OF OUR NEIGHBOUR. After the fabric of society seems on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.467#whole established and secured against external dangers, it is this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.468#fear of our neighbour which again creates new perspectives of moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.469#valuation. Certain strong and dangerous instincts, such as the love of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.470#enterprise, foolhardiness, revengefulness, astuteness, rapacity, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.471#love of power, which up till then had not only to be honoured from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.472#point of view of general utility--under other names, of course, than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.473#those here given--but had to be fostered and cultivated (because they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.474#were perpetually required in the common danger against the common
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.475#enemies), are now felt in their dangerousness to be doubly strong--when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.476#the outlets for them are lacking--and are gradually branded as immoral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.477#and given over to calumny. The contrary instincts and inclinations now
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.478#attain to moral honour, the gregarious instinct gradually draws its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.479#conclusions. How much or how little dangerousness to the community or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.480#to equality is contained in an opinion, a condition, an emotion, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.481#disposition, or an endowment--that is now the moral perspective, here
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.482#again fear is the mother of morals. It is by the loftiest and strongest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.483#instincts, when they break out passionately and carry the individual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.484#far above and beyond the average, and the low level of the gregarious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.485#conscience, that the self-reliance of the community is destroyed, its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.486#belief in itself, its backbone, as it were, breaks, consequently these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.487#very instincts will be most branded and defamed. The lofty independent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.488#spirituality, the will to stand alone, and even the cogent reason, are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.489#felt to be dangers, everything that elevates the individual above the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.490#herd, and is a source of fear to the neighbour, is henceforth called
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.491#EVIL, the tolerant, unassuming, self-adapting, self-equalizing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.492#disposition, the MEDIOCRITY of desires, attains to moral distinction and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.493#honour. Finally, under very peaceful circumstances, there is always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.494#less opportunity and necessity for training the feelings to severity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.495#and rigour, and now every form of severity, even in justice, begins
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.496#to disturb the conscience, a lofty and rigorous nobleness and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.497#self-responsibility almost offends, and awakens distrust, "the lamb,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.498#and still more "the sheep," wins respect. There is a point of diseased
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.499#mellowness and effeminacy in the history of society, at which society
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.500#itself takes the part of him who injures it, the part of the CRIMINAL,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.501#and does so, in fact, seriously and honestly. To punish, appears to it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.502#to be somehow unfair--it is certain that the idea of "punishment" and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.503#"the obligation to punish" are then painful and alarming to people. "Is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.504#it not sufficient if the criminal be rendered HARMLESS? Why should we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.505#still punish? Punishment itself is terrible!"--with these questions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.506#gregarious morality, the morality of fear, draws its ultimate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.507#conclusion. If one could at all do away with danger, the cause of fear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.508#one would have done away with this morality at the same time, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.509#would no longer be necessary, it WOULD NOT CONSIDER ITSELF any longer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.510#necessary!--Whoever examines the conscience of the present-day European,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.511#will always elicit the same imperative from its thousand moral folds
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.512#and hidden recesses, the imperative of the timidity of the herd "we wish
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.513#that some time or other there may be NOTHING MORE TO FEAR!" Some time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.514#or other--the will and the way THERETO is nowadays called "progress" all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.515#over Europe.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.516#202. Let us at once say again what we have already said a hundred
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.517#times, for people's ears nowadays are unwilling to hear such truths--OUR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.518#truths. We know well enough how offensive it sounds when any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.519#plainly, and without metaphor, counts man among the animals, but it will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.520#be accounted to us almost a CRIME, that it is precisely in respect to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.521#men of "modern ideas" that we have constantly applied the terms "herd,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.522#"herd-instincts," and such like expressions. What avail is it? We cannot
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.523#do otherwise, for it is precisely here that our new insight is. We
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.524#have found that in all the principal moral judgments, Europe has become
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.525#unanimous, including likewise the countries where European influence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.526#prevails in Europe people evidently KNOW what Socrates thought he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.527#did not know, and what the famous serpent of old once promised to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.528#teach--they "know" today what is good and evil. It must then sound hard
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.529#and be distasteful to the ear, when we always insist that that which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.530#here thinks it knows, that which here glorifies itself with praise
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.531#and blame, and calls itself good, is the instinct of the herding human
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.532#animal, the instinct which has come and is ever coming more and more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.533#to the front, to preponderance and supremacy over other instincts,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.534#according to the increasing physiological approximation and resemblance
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.535#of which it is the symptom. MORALITY IN EUROPE AT PRESENT IS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.536#HERDING-ANIMAL MORALITY, and therefore, as we understand the matter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.537#only one kind of human morality, beside which, before which, and after
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.538#which many other moralities, and above all HIGHER moralities, are or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.539#should be possible. Against such a "possibility," against such a "should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.540#be," however, this morality defends itself with all its strength, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.541#says obstinately and inexorably "I am morality itself and nothing else
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.542#is morality!" Indeed, with the help of a religion which has humoured
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.543#and flattered the sublimest desires of the herding-animal, things have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.544#reached such a point that we always find a more visible expression of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.545#this morality even in political and social arrangements: the DEMOCRATIC
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.546#movement is the inheritance of the Christian movement. That its TEMPO,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.547#however, is much too slow and sleepy for the more impatient ones, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.548#those who are sick and distracted by the herding-instinct, is indicated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.549#by the increasingly furious howling, and always less disguised
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.550#teeth-gnashing of the anarchist dogs, who are now roving through the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.551#highways of European culture. Apparently in opposition to the peacefully
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.552#industrious democrats and Revolution-ideologues, and still more so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.553#to the awkward philosophasters and fraternity-visionaries who call
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.554#themselves Socialists and want a "free society," those are really at one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.555#with them all in their thorough and instinctive hostility to every form
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.556#of society other than that of the AUTONOMOUS herd (to the extent even of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.557#repudiating the notions "master" and "servant"--ni dieu ni maitre, says
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.558#a socialist formula); at one in their tenacious opposition to every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.559#special claim, every special right and privilege (this means ultimately
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.560#opposition to EVERY right, for when all are equal, no one needs "rights"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.561#any longer); at one in their distrust of punitive justice (as though it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.562#were a violation of the weak, unfair to the NECESSARY consequences of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.563#all former society); but equally at one in their religion of sympathy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.564#in their compassion for all that feels, lives, and suffers (down to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.565#very animals, up even to "God"--the extravagance of "sympathy for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.566#God" belongs to a democratic age); altogether at one in the cry and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.567#impatience of their sympathy, in their deadly hatred of suffering
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.568#generally, in their almost feminine incapacity for witnessing it or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.569#ALLOWING it; at one in their involuntary beglooming and heart-softening,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.570#under the spell of which Europe seems to be threatened with a new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.571#Buddhism; at one in their belief in the morality of MUTUAL sympathy, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.572#though it were morality in itself, the climax, the ATTAINED climax of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.573#mankind, the sole hope of the future, the consolation of the present,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.574#the great discharge from all the obligations of the past; altogether at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.575#one in their belief in the community as the DELIVERER, in the herd, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.576#therefore in "themselves."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.577#203. We, who hold a different belief--we, who regard the democratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.578#movement, not only as a degenerating form of political organization, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.579#as equivalent to a degenerating, a waning type of man, as involving his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.580#mediocrising and depreciation: where have WE to fix our hopes? In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.581#NEW PHILOSOPHERS--there is no other alternative: in minds strong and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.582#original enough to initiate opposite estimates of value, to transvalue
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.583#and invert "eternal valuations"; in forerunners, in men of the future,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.584#who in the present shall fix the constraints and fasten the knots which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.585#will compel millenniums to take NEW paths. To teach man the future
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.586#of humanity as his WILL, as depending on human will, and to make
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.587#preparation for vast hazardous enterprises and collective attempts in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.588#rearing and educating, in order thereby to put an end to the frightful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.589#rule of folly and chance which has hitherto gone by the name of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.590#"history" (the folly of the "greatest number" is only its last
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.591#form)--for that purpose a new type of philosopher and commander will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.592#some time or other be needed, at the very idea of which everything that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.593#has existed in the way of occult, terrible, and benevolent beings might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.594#look pale and dwarfed. The image of such leaders hovers before OUR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.595#eyes:--is it lawful for me to say it aloud, ye free spirits? The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.596#conditions which one would partly have to create and partly utilize for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.597#their genesis; the presumptive methods and tests by virtue of which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.598#a soul should grow up to such an elevation and power as to feel a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.599#CONSTRAINT to these tasks; a transvaluation of values, under the new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.600#pressure and hammer of which a conscience should be steeled and a heart
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.601#transformed into brass, so as to bear the weight of such responsibility;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.602#and on the other hand the necessity for such leaders, the dreadful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.603#danger that they might be lacking, or miscarry and degenerate:--these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.604#are OUR real anxieties and glooms, ye know it well, ye free spirits!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.605#these are the heavy distant thoughts and storms which sweep across the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.606#heaven of OUR life. There are few pains so grievous as to have seen,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.607#divined, or experienced how an exceptional man has missed his way and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.608#deteriorated; but he who has the rare eye for the universal danger
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.609#of "man" himself DETERIORATING, he who like us has recognized the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.610#extraordinary fortuitousness which has hitherto played its game in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.611#respect to the future of mankind--a game in which neither the hand, nor
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.612#even a "finger of God" has participated!--he who divines the fate that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.613#is hidden under the idiotic unwariness and blind confidence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.614#"modern ideas," and still more under the whole of Christo-European
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.615#morality--suffers from an anguish with which no other is to be compared.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.616#He sees at a glance all that could still BE MADE OUT OF MAN through
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.617#a favourable accumulation and augmentation of human powers and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.618#arrangements; he knows with all the knowledge of his conviction how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.619#unexhausted man still is for the greatest possibilities, and how often
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.620#in the past the type man has stood in presence of mysterious decisions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.621#and new paths:--he knows still better from his painfulest recollections
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.622#on what wretched obstacles promising developments of the highest rank
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.623#have hitherto usually gone to pieces, broken down, sunk, and become
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.624#contemptible. The UNIVERSAL DEGENERACY OF MANKIND to the level of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.625#the "man of the future"--as idealized by the socialistic fools and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.626#shallow-pates--this degeneracy and dwarfing of man to an absolutely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.627#gregarious animal (or as they call it, to a man of "free society"),
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.628#this brutalizing of man into a pigmy with equal rights and claims, is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.629#undoubtedly POSSIBLE! He who has thought out this possibility to its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.630#ultimate conclusion knows ANOTHER loathing unknown to the rest of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:5.631#mankind--and perhaps also a new MISSION!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.1#CHAPTER VI. WE SCHOLARS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.2#204. At the risk that moralizing may also reveal itself here as that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.3#which it has always been--namely, resolutely MONTRER SES PLAIES,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.4#according to Balzac--I would venture to protest against an improper and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.5#injurious alteration of rank, which quite unnoticed, and as if with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.6#best conscience, threatens nowadays to establish itself in the relations
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.7#of science and philosophy. I mean to say that one must have the right
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.8#out of one's own EXPERIENCE--experience, as it seems to me, always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.9#implies unfortunate experience?--to treat of such an important question
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.10#of rank, so as not to speak of colour like the blind, or AGAINST science
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.11#like women and artists ("Ah! this dreadful science!" sigh their instinct
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.12#and their shame, "it always FINDS THINGS OUT!"). The declaration of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.13#independence of the scientific man, his emancipation from philosophy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.14#is one of the subtler after-effects of democratic organization and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.15#disorganization: the self-glorification and self-conceitedness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.16#the learned man is now everywhere in full bloom, and in its best
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.17#springtime--which does not mean to imply that in this case self-praise
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.18#smells sweet. Here also the instinct of the populace cries, "Freedom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.19#from all masters!" and after science has, with the happiest results,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.20#resisted theology, whose "hand-maid" it had been too long, it now
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.21#proposes in its wantonness and indiscretion to lay down laws for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.22#philosophy, and in its turn to play the "master"--what am I saying!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.23#to play the PHILOSOPHER on its own account. My memory--the memory of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.24#a scientific man, if you please!--teems with the naivetes of insolence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.25#which I have heard about philosophy and philosophers from young
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.26#naturalists and old physicians (not to mention the most cultured and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.27#most conceited of all learned men, the philologists and schoolmasters,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.28#who are both the one and the other by profession). On one occasion it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.29#was the specialist and the Jack Horner who instinctively stood on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.30#defensive against all synthetic tasks and capabilities; at another time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.31#it was the industrious worker who had got a scent of OTIUM and refined
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.32#luxuriousness in the internal economy of the philosopher, and felt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.33#himself aggrieved and belittled thereby. On another occasion it was the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.34#colour-blindness of the utilitarian, who sees nothing in philosophy but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.35#a series of REFUTED systems, and an extravagant expenditure which "does
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.36#nobody any good". At another time the fear of disguised mysticism and of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.37#the boundary-adjustment of knowledge became conspicuous, at another
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.38#time the disregard of individual philosophers, which had involuntarily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.39#extended to disregard of philosophy generally. In fine, I found most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.40#frequently, behind the proud disdain of philosophy in young scholars,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.41#the evil after-effect of some particular philosopher, to whom on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.42#whole obedience had been foresworn, without, however, the spell of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.43#scornful estimates of other philosophers having been got rid of--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.44#result being a general ill-will to all philosophy. (Such seems to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.45#me, for instance, the after-effect of Schopenhauer on the most modern
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.46#Germany: by his unintelligent rage against Hegel, he has succeeded in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.47#severing the whole of the last generation of Germans from its connection
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.48#with German culture, which culture, all things considered, has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.49#an elevation and a divining refinement of the HISTORICAL SENSE, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.50#precisely at this point Schopenhauer himself was poor, irreceptive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.51#and un-German to the extent of ingeniousness.) On the whole, speaking
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.52#generally, it may just have been the humanness, all-too-humanness of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.53#modern philosophers themselves, in short, their contemptibleness, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.54#has injured most radically the reverence for philosophy and opened the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.55#doors to the instinct of the populace. Let it but be acknowledged to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.56#what an extent our modern world diverges from the whole style of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.57#world of Heraclitus, Plato, Empedocles, and whatever else all the royal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.58#and magnificent anchorites of the spirit were called, and with what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.59#justice an honest man of science MAY feel himself of a better family and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.60#origin, in view of such representatives of philosophy, who, owing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.61#the fashion of the present day, are just as much aloft as they are down
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.62#below--in Germany, for instance, the two lions of Berlin, the anarchist
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.63#Eugen Duhring and the amalgamist Eduard von Hartmann. It is especially
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.64#the sight of those hotch-potch philosophers, who call themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.65#"realists," or "positivists," which is calculated to implant a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.66#dangerous distrust in the soul of a young and ambitious scholar those
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.67#philosophers, at the best, are themselves but scholars and specialists,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.68#that is very evident! All of them are persons who have been vanquished
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.69#and BROUGHT BACK AGAIN under the dominion of science, who at one time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.70#or another claimed more from themselves, without having a right to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.71#"more" and its responsibility--and who now, creditably, rancorously, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.72#vindictively, represent in word and deed, DISBELIEF in the master-task
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.73#and supremacy of philosophy After all, how could it be otherwise?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.74#Science flourishes nowadays and has the good conscience clearly visible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.75#on its countenance, while that to which the entire modern philosophy has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.76#gradually sunk, the remnant of philosophy of the present day, excites
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.77#distrust and displeasure, if not scorn and pity Philosophy reduced to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.78#a "theory of knowledge," no more in fact than a diffident science of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.79#epochs and doctrine of forbearance a philosophy that never even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.80#gets beyond the threshold, and rigorously DENIES itself the right
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.81#to enter--that is philosophy in its last throes, an end, an agony,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.82#something that awakens pity. How could such a philosophy--RULE!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.83#205. The dangers that beset the evolution of the philosopher are, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.84#fact, so manifold nowadays, that one might doubt whether this fruit
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.85#could still come to maturity. The extent and towering structure of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.86#sciences have increased enormously, and therewith also the probability
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.87#that the philosopher will grow tired even as a learner, or will attach
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.88#himself somewhere and "specialize" so that he will no longer attain to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.89#his elevation, that is to say, to his superspection, his circumspection,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.90#and his DESPECTION. Or he gets aloft too late, when the best of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.91#maturity and strength is past, or when he is impaired, coarsened, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.92#deteriorated, so that his view, his general estimate of things, is no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.93#longer of much importance. It is perhaps just the refinement of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.94#intellectual conscience that makes him hesitate and linger on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.95#way, he dreads the temptation to become a dilettante, a millepede, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.96#milleantenna, he knows too well that as a discerner, one who has lost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.97#his self-respect no longer commands, no longer LEADS, unless he should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.98#aspire to become a great play-actor, a philosophical Cagliostro and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.99#spiritual rat-catcher--in short, a misleader. This is in the last
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.100#instance a question of taste, if it has not really been a question of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.101#conscience. To double once more the philosopher's difficulties, there is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.102#also the fact that he demands from himself a verdict, a Yea or Nay, not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.103#concerning science, but concerning life and the worth of life--he learns
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.104#unwillingly to believe that it is his right and even his duty to obtain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.105#this verdict, and he has to seek his way to the right and the belief
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.106#only through the most extensive (perhaps disturbing and destroying)
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.107#experiences, often hesitating, doubting, and dumbfounded. In fact, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.108#philosopher has long been mistaken and confused by the multitude, either
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.109#with the scientific man and ideal scholar, or with the religiously
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.110#elevated, desensualized, desecularized visionary and God-intoxicated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.111#man; and even yet when one hears anybody praised, because he lives
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.112#"wisely," or "as a philosopher," it hardly means anything more than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.113#"prudently and apart." Wisdom: that seems to the populace to be a kind
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.114#of flight, a means and artifice for withdrawing successfully from a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.115#bad game; but the GENUINE philosopher--does it not seem so to US,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.116#my friends?--lives "unphilosophically" and "unwisely," above all,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.117#IMPRUDENTLY, and feels the obligation and burden of a hundred attempts
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.118#and temptations of life--he risks HIMSELF constantly, he plays THIS bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.119#game.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.120#206. In relation to the genius, that is to say, a being who either
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.121#ENGENDERS or PRODUCES--both words understood in their fullest sense--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.122#man of learning, the scientific average man, has always something of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.123#the old maid about him; for, like her, he is not conversant with the two
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.124#principal functions of man. To both, of course, to the scholar and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.125#to the old maid, one concedes respectability, as if by way of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.126#indemnification--in these cases one emphasizes the respectability--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.127#yet, in the compulsion of this concession, one has the same admixture
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.128#of vexation. Let us examine more closely: what is the scientific man?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.129#Firstly, a commonplace type of man, with commonplace virtues: that is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.130#to say, a non-ruling, non-authoritative, and non-self-sufficient type
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.131#of man; he possesses industry, patient adaptableness to rank and file,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.132#equability and moderation in capacity and requirement; he has the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.133#instinct for people like himself, and for that which they require--for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.134#instance: the portion of independence and green meadow without which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.135#there is no rest from labour, the claim to honour and consideration
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.136#(which first and foremost presupposes recognition and recognisability),
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.137#the sunshine of a good name, the perpetual ratification of his value and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.138#usefulness, with which the inward DISTRUST which lies at the bottom of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.139#the heart of all dependent men and gregarious animals, has again and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.140#again to be overcome. The learned man, as is appropriate, has also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.141#maladies and faults of an ignoble kind: he is full of petty envy, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.142#has a lynx-eye for the weak points in those natures to whose elevations
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.143#he cannot attain. He is confiding, yet only as one who lets himself go,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.144#but does not FLOW; and precisely before the man of the great current he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.145#stands all the colder and more reserved--his eye is then like a smooth
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.146#and irresponsive lake, which is no longer moved by rapture or sympathy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.147#The worst and most dangerous thing of which a scholar is capable results
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.148#from the instinct of mediocrity of his type, from the Jesuitism of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.149#mediocrity, which labours instinctively for the destruction of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.150#the exceptional man, and endeavours to break--or still better, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.151#relax--every bent bow To relax, of course, with consideration, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.152#naturally with an indulgent hand--to RELAX with confiding sympathy
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.153#that is the real art of Jesuitism, which has always understood how to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.154#introduce itself as the religion of sympathy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.155#207. However gratefully one may welcome the OBJECTIVE spirit--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.156#who has not been sick to death of all subjectivity and its confounded
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.157#IPSISIMOSITY!--in the end, however, one must learn caution even with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.158#regard to one's gratitude, and put a stop to the exaggeration with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.159#which the unselfing and depersonalizing of the spirit has recently been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.160#celebrated, as if it were the goal in itself, as if it were salvation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.161#and glorification--as is especially accustomed to happen in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.162#pessimist school, which has also in its turn good reasons for paying the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.163#highest honours to "disinterested knowledge" The objective man, who no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.164#longer curses and scolds like the pessimist, the IDEAL man of learning
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.165#in whom the scientific instinct blossoms forth fully after a thousand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.166#complete and partial failures, is assuredly one of the most costly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.167#instruments that exist, but his place is in the hand of one who is more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.168#powerful He is only an instrument, we may say, he is a MIRROR--he is no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.169#"purpose in himself" The objective man is in truth a mirror accustomed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.170#to prostration before everything that wants to be known, with such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.171#desires only as knowing or "reflecting" implies--he waits until
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.172#something comes, and then expands himself sensitively, so that even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.173#light footsteps and gliding-past of spiritual beings may not be lost on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.174#his surface and film Whatever "personality" he still possesses seems to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.175#him accidental, arbitrary, or still oftener, disturbing, so much has he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.176#come to regard himself as the passage and reflection of outside forms
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.177#and events He calls up the recollection of "himself" with an effort,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.178#and not infrequently wrongly, he readily confounds himself with other
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.179#persons, he makes mistakes with regard to his own needs, and here only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.180#is he unrefined and negligent Perhaps he is troubled about the health,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.181#or the pettiness and confined atmosphere of wife and friend, or the lack
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.182#of companions and society--indeed, he sets himself to reflect on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.183#suffering, but in vain! His thoughts already rove away to the MORE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.184#GENERAL case, and tomorrow he knows as little as he knew yesterday how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.185#to help himself He does not now take himself seriously and devote time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.186#to himself he is serene, NOT from lack of trouble, but from lack
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.187#of capacity for grasping and dealing with HIS trouble The habitual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.188#complaisance with respect to all objects and experiences, the radiant
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.189#and impartial hospitality with which he receives everything that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.190#comes his way, his habit of inconsiderate good-nature, of dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.191#indifference as to Yea and Nay: alas! there are enough of cases in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.192#he has to atone for these virtues of his!--and as man generally, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.193#becomes far too easily the CAPUT MORTUUM of such virtues. Should one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.194#wish love or hatred from him--I mean love and hatred as God, woman, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.195#animal understand them--he will do what he can, and furnish what he can.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.196#But one must not be surprised if it should not be much--if he should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.197#show himself just at this point to be false, fragile, questionable, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.198#deteriorated. His love is constrained, his hatred is artificial, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.199#rather UN TOUR DE FORCE, a slight ostentation and exaggeration. He is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.200#only genuine so far as he can be objective; only in his serene totality
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.201#is he still "nature" and "natural." His mirroring and eternally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.202#self-polishing soul no longer knows how to affirm, no longer how to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.203#deny; he does not command; neither does he destroy. "JE NE MEPRISE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.204#PRESQUE RIEN"--he says, with Leibniz: let us not overlook nor undervalue
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.205#the PRESQUE! Neither is he a model man; he does not go in advance of any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.206#one, nor after, either; he places himself generally too far off to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.207#any reason for espousing the cause of either good or evil. If he has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.208#been so long confounded with the PHILOSOPHER, with the Caesarian trainer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.209#and dictator of civilization, he has had far too much honour, and what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.210#is more essential in him has been overlooked--he is an instrument,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.211#something of a slave, though certainly the sublimest sort of slave, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.212#nothing in himself--PRESQUE RIEN! The objective man is an instrument,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.213#a costly, easily injured, easily tarnished measuring instrument and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.214#mirroring apparatus, which is to be taken care of and respected; but he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.215#is no goal, not outgoing nor upgoing, no complementary man in whom the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.216#REST of existence justifies itself, no termination--and still less a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.217#commencement, an engendering, or primary cause, nothing hardy, powerful,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.218#self-centred, that wants to be master; but rather only a soft, inflated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.219#delicate, movable potter's-form, that must wait for some kind of content
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.220#and frame to "shape" itself thereto--for the most part a man without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.221#frame and content, a "selfless" man. Consequently, also, nothing for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.222#women, IN PARENTHESI.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.223#208. When a philosopher nowadays makes known that he is not a skeptic--I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.224#hope that has been gathered from the foregoing description of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.225#objective spirit?--people all hear it impatiently; they regard him on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.226#that account with some apprehension, they would like to ask so many,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.227#many questions... indeed among timid hearers, of whom there are now so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.228#many, he is henceforth said to be dangerous. With his repudiation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.229#skepticism, it seems to them as if they heard some evil-threatening
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.230#sound in the distance, as if a new kind of explosive were being tried
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.231#somewhere, a dynamite of the spirit, perhaps a newly discovered Russian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.232#NIHILINE, a pessimism BONAE VOLUNTATIS, that not only denies, means
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.233#denial, but--dreadful thought! PRACTISES denial. Against this kind of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.234#"good-will"--a will to the veritable, actual negation of life--there is,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.235#as is generally acknowledged nowadays, no better soporific and sedative
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.236#than skepticism, the mild, pleasing, lulling poppy of skepticism;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.237#and Hamlet himself is now prescribed by the doctors of the day as an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.238#antidote to the "spirit," and its underground noises. "Are not our ears
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.239#already full of bad sounds?" say the skeptics, as lovers of repose, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.240#almost as a kind of safety police; "this subterranean Nay is terrible!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.241#Be still, ye pessimistic moles!" The skeptic, in effect, that delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.242#creature, is far too easily frightened; his conscience is schooled so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.243#as to start at every Nay, and even at that sharp, decided Yea, and feels
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.244#something like a bite thereby. Yea! and Nay!--they seem to him opposed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.245#to morality; he loves, on the contrary, to make a festival to his virtue
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.246#by a noble aloofness, while perhaps he says with Montaigne: "What do I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.247#know?" Or with Socrates: "I know that I know nothing." Or: "Here I do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.248#not trust myself, no door is open to me." Or: "Even if the door were
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.249#open, why should I enter immediately?" Or: "What is the use of any hasty
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.250#hypotheses? It might quite well be in good taste to make no hypotheses
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.251#at all. Are you absolutely obliged to straighten at once what is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.252#crooked? to stuff every hole with some kind of oakum? Is there not time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.253#enough for that? Has not the time leisure? Oh, ye demons, can ye not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.254#at all WAIT? The uncertain also has its charms, the Sphinx, too, is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.255#Circe, and Circe, too, was a philosopher."--Thus does a skeptic console
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.256#himself; and in truth he needs some consolation. For skepticism is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.257#the most spiritual expression of a certain many-sided physiological
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.258#temperament, which in ordinary language is called nervous debility and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.259#sickliness; it arises whenever races or classes which have been long
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.260#separated, decisively and suddenly blend with one another. In the new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.261#generation, which has inherited as it were different standards and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.262#valuations in its blood, everything is disquiet, derangement, doubt, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.263#tentativeness; the best powers operate restrictively, the very virtues
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.264#prevent each other growing and becoming strong, equilibrium, ballast,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.265#and perpendicular stability are lacking in body and soul. That, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.266#which is most diseased and degenerated in such nondescripts is the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.267#WILL; they are no longer familiar with independence of decision, or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.268#the courageous feeling of pleasure in willing--they are doubtful of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.269#"freedom of the will" even in their dreams Our present-day Europe,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.270#the scene of a senseless, precipitate attempt at a radical blending of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.271#classes, and CONSEQUENTLY of races, is therefore skeptical in all its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.272#heights and depths, sometimes exhibiting the mobile skepticism which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.273#springs impatiently and wantonly from branch to branch, sometimes with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.274#gloomy aspect, like a cloud over-charged with interrogative signs--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.275#often sick unto death of its will! Paralysis of will, where do we not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.276#find this cripple sitting nowadays! And yet how bedecked oftentimes' How
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.277#seductively ornamented! There are the finest gala dresses and disguises
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.278#for this disease, and that, for instance, most of what places itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.279#nowadays in the show-cases as "objectiveness," "the scientific spirit,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.280#"L'ART POUR L'ART," and "pure voluntary knowledge," is only decked-out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.281#skepticism and paralysis of will--I am ready to answer for this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.282#diagnosis of the European disease--The disease of the will is diffused
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.283#unequally over Europe, it is worst and most varied where civilization
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.284#has longest prevailed, it decreases according as "the barbarian"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.285#still--or again--asserts his claims under the loose drapery of Western
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.286#culture It is therefore in the France of today, as can be readily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.287#disclosed and comprehended, that the will is most infirm, and France,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.288#which has always had a masterly aptitude for converting even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.289#portentous crises of its spirit into something charming and seductive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.290#now manifests emphatically its intellectual ascendancy over Europe,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.291#by being the school and exhibition of all the charms of skepticism The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.292#power to will and to persist, moreover, in a resolution, is already
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.293#somewhat stronger in Germany, and again in the North of Germany it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.294#is stronger than in Central Germany, it is considerably stronger in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.295#England, Spain, and Corsica, associated with phlegm in the former and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.296#with hard skulls in the latter--not to mention Italy, which is too young
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.297#yet to know what it wants, and must first show whether it can exercise
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.298#will, but it is strongest and most surprising of all in that immense
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.299#middle empire where Europe as it were flows back to Asia--namely, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.300#Russia There the power to will has been long stored up and accumulated,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.301#there the will--uncertain whether to be negative or affirmative--waits
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.302#threateningly to be discharged (to borrow their pet phrase from our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.303#physicists) Perhaps not only Indian wars and complications in Asia would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.304#be necessary to free Europe from its greatest danger, but also internal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.305#subversion, the shattering of the empire into small states, and above
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.306#all the introduction of parliamentary imbecility, together with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.307#obligation of every one to read his newspaper at breakfast I do not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.308#say this as one who desires it, in my heart I should rather prefer the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.309#contrary--I mean such an increase in the threatening attitude of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.310#Russia, that Europe would have to make up its mind to become equally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.311#threatening--namely, TO ACQUIRE ONE WILL, by means of a new caste to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.312#rule over the Continent, a persistent, dreadful will of its own, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.313#can set its aims thousands of years ahead; so that the long spun-out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.314#comedy of its petty-statism, and its dynastic as well as its democratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.315#many-willed-ness, might finally be brought to a close. The time for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.316#petty politics is past; the next century will bring the struggle for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.317#dominion of the world--the COMPULSION to great politics.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.318#209. As to how far the new warlike age on which we Europeans have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.319#evidently entered may perhaps favour the growth of another and stronger
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.320#kind of skepticism, I should like to express myself preliminarily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.321#merely by a parable, which the lovers of German history will already
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.322#understand. That unscrupulous enthusiast for big, handsome grenadiers
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.323#(who, as King of Prussia, brought into being a military and skeptical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.324#genius--and therewith, in reality, the new and now triumphantly emerged
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.325#type of German), the problematic, crazy father of Frederick the Great,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.326#had on one point the very knack and lucky grasp of the genius: he knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.327#what was then lacking in Germany, the want of which was a hundred times
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.328#more alarming and serious than any lack of culture and social form--his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.329#ill-will to the young Frederick resulted from the anxiety of a profound
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.330#instinct. MEN WERE LACKING; and he suspected, to his bitterest regret,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.331#that his own son was not man enough. There, however, he deceived
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.332#himself; but who would not have deceived himself in his place? He saw
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.333#his son lapsed to atheism, to the ESPRIT, to the pleasant frivolity of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.334#clever Frenchmen--he saw in the background the great bloodsucker, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.335#spider skepticism; he suspected the incurable wretchedness of a heart no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.336#longer hard enough either for evil or good, and of a broken will that no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.337#longer commands, is no longer ABLE to command. Meanwhile, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.338#there grew up in his son that new kind of harder and more dangerous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.339#skepticism--who knows TO WHAT EXTENT it was encouraged just by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.340#his father's hatred and the icy melancholy of a will condemned to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.341#solitude?--the skepticism of daring manliness, which is closely related
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.342#to the genius for war and conquest, and made its first entrance into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.343#Germany in the person of the great Frederick. This skepticism despises
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.344#and nevertheless grasps; it undermines and takes possession; it does
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.345#not believe, but it does not thereby lose itself; it gives the spirit a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.346#dangerous liberty, but it keeps strict guard over the heart. It is the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.347#GERMAN form of skepticism, which, as a continued Fredericianism, risen
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.348#to the highest spirituality, has kept Europe for a considerable time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.349#under the dominion of the German spirit and its critical and historical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.350#distrust Owing to the insuperably strong and tough masculine character
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.351#of the great German philologists and historical critics (who,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.352#rightly estimated, were also all of them artists of destruction
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.353#and dissolution), a NEW conception of the German spirit gradually
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.354#established itself--in spite of all Romanticism in music and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.355#philosophy--in which the leaning towards masculine skepticism was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.356#decidedly prominent whether, for instance, as fearlessness of gaze, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.357#courage and sternness of the dissecting hand, or as resolute will to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.358#dangerous voyages of discovery, to spiritualized North Pole expeditions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.359#under barren and dangerous skies. There may be good grounds for it when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.360#warm-blooded and superficial humanitarians cross themselves before this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.361#spirit, CET ESPRIT FATALISTE, IRONIQUE, MEPHISTOPHELIQUE, as Michelet
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.362#calls it, not without a shudder. But if one would realize how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.363#characteristic is this fear of the "man" in the German spirit which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.364#awakened Europe out of its "dogmatic slumber," let us call to mind the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.365#former conception which had to be overcome by this new one--and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.366#it is not so very long ago that a masculinized woman could dare, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.367#unbridled presumption, to recommend the Germans to the interest of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.368#Europe as gentle, good-hearted, weak-willed, and poetical fools.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.369#Finally, let us only understand profoundly enough Napoleon's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.370#astonishment when he saw Goethe it reveals what had been regarded for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.371#centuries as the "German spirit" "VOILA UN HOMME!"--that was as much as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.372#to say "But this is a MAN! And I only expected to see a German!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.373#210. Supposing, then, that in the picture of the philosophers of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.374#future, some trait suggests the question whether they must not perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.375#be skeptics in the last-mentioned sense, something in them would only be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.376#designated thereby--and not they themselves. With equal right they might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.377#call themselves critics, and assuredly they will be men of experiments.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.378#By the name with which I ventured to baptize them, I have already
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.379#expressly emphasized their attempting and their love of attempting is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.380#this because, as critics in body and soul, they will love to make use
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.381#of experiments in a new, and perhaps wider and more dangerous sense? In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.382#their passion for knowledge, will they have to go further in daring and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.383#painful attempts than the sensitive and pampered taste of a democratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.384#century can approve of?--There is no doubt these coming ones will be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.385#least able to dispense with the serious and not unscrupulous qualities
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.386#which distinguish the critic from the skeptic I mean the certainty as to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.387#standards of worth, the conscious employment of a unity of method,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.388#the wary courage, the standing-alone, and the capacity for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.389#self-responsibility, indeed, they will avow among themselves a DELIGHT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.390#in denial and dissection, and a certain considerate cruelty, which knows
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.391#how to handle the knife surely and deftly, even when the heart bleeds
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.392#They will be STERNER (and perhaps not always towards themselves only)
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.393#than humane people may desire, they will not deal with the "truth" in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.394#order that it may "please" them, or "elevate" and "inspire" them--they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.395#will rather have little faith in "TRUTH" bringing with it such revels
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.396#for the feelings. They will smile, those rigorous spirits, when any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.397#says in their presence "That thought elevates me, why should it not be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.398#true?" or "That work enchants me, why should it not be beautiful?" or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.399#"That artist enlarges me, why should he not be great?" Perhaps they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.400#will not only have a smile, but a genuine disgust for all that is thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.401#rapturous, idealistic, feminine, and hermaphroditic, and if any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.402#could look into their inmost hearts, he would not easily find therein
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.403#the intention to reconcile "Christian sentiments" with "antique taste,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.404#or even with "modern parliamentarism" (the kind of reconciliation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.405#necessarily found even among philosophers in our very uncertain and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.406#consequently very conciliatory century). Critical discipline, and every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.407#habit that conduces to purity and rigour in intellectual matters,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.408#will not only be demanded from themselves by these philosophers of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.409#the future, they may even make a display thereof as their special
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.410#adornment--nevertheless they will not want to be called critics on that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.411#account. It will seem to them no small indignity to philosophy to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.412#have it decreed, as is so welcome nowadays, that "philosophy itself is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.413#criticism and critical science--and nothing else whatever!" Though this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.414#estimate of philosophy may enjoy the approval of all the Positivists of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.415#France and Germany (and possibly it even flattered the heart and taste
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.416#of KANT: let us call to mind the titles of his principal works), our new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.417#philosophers will say, notwithstanding, that critics are instruments of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.418#the philosopher, and just on that account, as instruments, they are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.419#far from being philosophers themselves! Even the great Chinaman of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.420#Konigsberg was only a great critic.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.421#211. I insist upon it that people finally cease confounding
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.422#philosophical workers, and in general scientific men, with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.423#philosophers--that precisely here one should strictly give "each his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.424#own," and not give those far too much, these far too little. It may
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.425#be necessary for the education of the real philosopher that he himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.426#should have once stood upon all those steps upon which his servants,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.427#the scientific workers of philosophy, remain standing, and MUST remain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.428#standing he himself must perhaps have been critic, and dogmatist,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.429#and historian, and besides, poet, and collector, and traveler, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.430#riddle-reader, and moralist, and seer, and "free spirit," and almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.431#everything, in order to traverse the whole range of human values
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.432#and estimations, and that he may BE ABLE with a variety of eyes and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.433#consciences to look from a height to any distance, from a depth up
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.434#to any height, from a nook into any expanse. But all these are only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.435#preliminary conditions for his task; this task itself demands something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.436#else--it requires him TO CREATE VALUES. The philosophical workers, after
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.437#the excellent pattern of Kant and Hegel, have to fix and formalize some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.438#great existing body of valuations--that is to say, former DETERMINATIONS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.439#OF VALUE, creations of value, which have become prevalent, and are for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.440#a time called "truths"--whether in the domain of the LOGICAL, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.441#POLITICAL (moral), or the ARTISTIC. It is for these investigators to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.442#make whatever has happened and been esteemed hitherto, conspicuous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.443#conceivable, intelligible, and manageable, to shorten everything long,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.444#even "time" itself, and to SUBJUGATE the entire past: an immense and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.445#wonderful task, in the carrying out of which all refined pride, all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.446#tenacious will, can surely find satisfaction. THE REAL PHILOSOPHERS,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.447#HOWEVER, ARE COMMANDERS AND LAW-GIVERS; they say: "Thus SHALL it be!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.448#They determine first the Whither and the Why of mankind, and thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.449#set aside the previous labour of all philosophical workers, and all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.450#subjugators of the past--they grasp at the future with a creative
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.451#hand, and whatever is and was, becomes for them thereby a means, an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.452#instrument, and a hammer. Their "knowing" is CREATING, their creating
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.453#is a law-giving, their will to truth is--WILL TO POWER.--Are there at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.454#present such philosophers? Have there ever been such philosophers? MUST
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.455#there not be such philosophers some day? ...
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.456#212. It is always more obvious to me that the philosopher, as a man
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.457#INDISPENSABLE for the morrow and the day after the morrow, has ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.458#found himself, and HAS BEEN OBLIGED to find himself, in contradiction
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.459#to the day in which he lives; his enemy has always been the ideal of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.460#day. Hitherto all those extraordinary furtherers of humanity whom one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.461#calls philosophers--who rarely regarded themselves as lovers of wisdom,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.462#but rather as disagreeable fools and dangerous interrogators--have found
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.463#their mission, their hard, involuntary, imperative mission (in the end,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.464#however, the greatness of their mission), in being the bad conscience of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.465#their age. In putting the vivisector's knife to the breast of the very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.466#VIRTUES OF THEIR AGE, they have betrayed their own secret; it has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.467#for the sake of a NEW greatness of man, a new untrodden path to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.468#his aggrandizement. They have always disclosed how much hypocrisy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.469#indolence, self-indulgence, and self-neglect, how much falsehood was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.470#concealed under the most venerated types of contemporary morality, how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.471#much virtue was OUTLIVED, they have always said "We must remove hence to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.472#where YOU are least at home" In the face of a world of "modern ideas,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.473#which would like to confine every one in a corner, in a "specialty," a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.474#philosopher, if there could be philosophers nowadays, would be compelled
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.475#to place the greatness of man, the conception of "greatness," precisely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.476#in his comprehensiveness and multifariousness, in his all-roundness, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.477#would even determine worth and rank according to the amount and variety
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.478#of that which a man could bear and take upon himself, according to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.479#EXTENT to which a man could stretch his responsibility Nowadays the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.480#taste and virtue of the age weaken and attenuate the will, nothing is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.481#so adapted to the spirit of the age as weakness of will consequently, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.482#the ideal of the philosopher, strength of will, sternness, and capacity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.483#for prolonged resolution, must specially be included in the conception
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.484#of "greatness", with as good a right as the opposite doctrine, with its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.485#ideal of a silly, renouncing, humble, selfless humanity, was suited to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.486#an opposite age--such as the sixteenth century, which suffered from its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.487#accumulated energy of will, and from the wildest torrents and floods
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.488#of selfishness In the time of Socrates, among men only of worn-out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.489#instincts, old conservative Athenians who let themselves go--"for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.490#sake of happiness," as they said, for the sake of pleasure, as their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.491#conduct indicated--and who had continually on their lips the old pompous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.492#words to which they had long forfeited the right by the life they led,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.493#IRONY was perhaps necessary for greatness of soul, the wicked Socratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.494#assurance of the old physician and plebeian, who cut ruthlessly into his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.495#own flesh, as into the flesh and heart of the "noble," with a look that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.496#said plainly enough "Do not dissemble before me! here--we are equal!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.497#At present, on the contrary, when throughout Europe the herding-animal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.498#alone attains to honours, and dispenses honours, when "equality of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.499#right" can too readily be transformed into equality in wrong--I mean to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.500#say into general war against everything rare, strange, and privileged,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.501#against the higher man, the higher soul, the higher duty, the higher
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.502#responsibility, the creative plenipotence and lordliness--at present
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.503#it belongs to the conception of "greatness" to be noble, to wish to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.504#apart, to be capable of being different, to stand alone, to have to live
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.505#by personal initiative, and the philosopher will betray something of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.506#own ideal when he asserts "He shall be the greatest who can be the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.507#solitary, the most concealed, the most divergent, the man beyond good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.508#and evil, the master of his virtues, and of super-abundance of will;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.509#precisely this shall be called GREATNESS: as diversified as can be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.510#entire, as ample as can be full." And to ask once more the question: Is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.511#greatness POSSIBLE--nowadays?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.512#213. It is difficult to learn what a philosopher is, because it cannot
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.513#be taught: one must "know" it by experience--or one should have the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.514#pride NOT to know it. The fact that at present people all talk of things
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.515#of which they CANNOT have any experience, is true more especially
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.516#and unfortunately as concerns the philosopher and philosophical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.517#matters:--the very few know them, are permitted to know them, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.518#all popular ideas about them are false. Thus, for instance, the truly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.519#philosophical combination of a bold, exuberant spirituality which runs
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.520#at presto pace, and a dialectic rigour and necessity which makes no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.521#false step, is unknown to most thinkers and scholars from their own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.522#experience, and therefore, should any one speak of it in their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.523#presence, it is incredible to them. They conceive of every necessity as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.524#troublesome, as a painful compulsory obedience and state of constraint;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.525#thinking itself is regarded by them as something slow and hesitating,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.526#almost as a trouble, and often enough as "worthy of the SWEAT of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.527#noble"--but not at all as something easy and divine, closely related
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.528#to dancing and exuberance! "To think" and to take a matter "seriously,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.529#"arduously"--that is one and the same thing to them; such only has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.530#their "experience."--Artists have here perhaps a finer intuition; they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.531#who know only too well that precisely when they no longer do anything
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.532#"arbitrarily," and everything of necessity, their feeling of freedom,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.533#of subtlety, of power, of creatively fixing, disposing, and shaping,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.534#reaches its climax--in short, that necessity and "freedom of will" are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.535#then the same thing with them. There is, in fine, a gradation of rank
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.536#in psychical states, to which the gradation of rank in the problems
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.537#corresponds; and the highest problems repel ruthlessly every one who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.538#ventures too near them, without being predestined for their solution
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.539#by the loftiness and power of his spirituality. Of what use is it for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.540#nimble, everyday intellects, or clumsy, honest mechanics and empiricists
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.541#to press, in their plebeian ambition, close to such problems, and as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.542#it were into this "holy of holies"--as so often happens nowadays! But
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.543#coarse feet must never tread upon such carpets: this is provided for in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.544#the primary law of things; the doors remain closed to those intruders,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.545#though they may dash and break their heads thereon. People have always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.546#to be born to a high station, or, more definitely, they have to be BRED
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.547#for it: a person has only a right to philosophy--taking the word in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.548#its higher significance--in virtue of his descent; the ancestors, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.549#"blood," decide here also. Many generations must have prepared the way
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.550#for the coming of the philosopher; each of his virtues must have been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.551#separately acquired, nurtured, transmitted, and embodied; not only the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.552#bold, easy, delicate course and current of his thoughts, but above all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.553#the readiness for great responsibilities, the majesty of ruling glance
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.554#and contemning look, the feeling of separation from the multitude with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.555#their duties and virtues, the kindly patronage and defense of whatever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.556#is misunderstood and calumniated, be it God or devil, the delight and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.557#practice of supreme justice, the art of commanding, the amplitude of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.558#will, the lingering eye which rarely admires, rarely looks up, rarely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:6.559#loves....
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.1#CHAPTER VII. OUR VIRTUES
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.2#214. OUR Virtues?--It is probable that we, too, have still our virtues,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.3#although naturally they are not those sincere and massive virtues on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.4#account of which we hold our grandfathers in esteem and also at a little
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.5#distance from us. We Europeans of the day after tomorrow, we firstlings
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.6#of the twentieth century--with all our dangerous curiosity, our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.7#multifariousness and art of disguising, our mellow and seemingly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.8#sweetened cruelty in sense and spirit--we shall presumably, IF we must
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.9#have virtues, have those only which have come to agreement with our most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.10#secret and heartfelt inclinations, with our most ardent requirements:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.11#well, then, let us look for them in our labyrinths!--where, as we know,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.12#so many things lose themselves, so many things get quite lost! And is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.13#there anything finer than to SEARCH for one's own virtues? Is it not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.14#almost to BELIEVE in one's own virtues? But this "believing in one's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.15#own virtues"--is it not practically the same as what was formerly called
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.16#one's "good conscience," that long, respectable pigtail of an idea,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.17#which our grandfathers used to hang behind their heads, and often enough
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.18#also behind their understandings? It seems, therefore, that however
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.19#little we may imagine ourselves to be old-fashioned and grandfatherly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.20#respectable in other respects, in one thing we are nevertheless the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.21#worthy grandchildren of our grandfathers, we last Europeans with good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.22#consciences: we also still wear their pigtail.--Ah! if you only knew how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.23#soon, so very soon--it will be different!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.24#215. As in the stellar firmament there are sometimes two suns which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.25#determine the path of one planet, and in certain cases suns of different
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.26#colours shine around a single planet, now with red light, now with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.27#green, and then simultaneously illumine and flood it with motley
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.28#colours: so we modern men, owing to the complicated mechanism of our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.29#"firmament," are determined by DIFFERENT moralities; our actions shine
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.30#alternately in different colours, and are seldom unequivocal--and there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.31#are often cases, also, in which our actions are MOTLEY-COLOURED.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.32#216. To love one's enemies? I think that has been well learnt: it takes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.33#place thousands of times at present on a large and small scale; indeed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.34#at times the higher and sublimer thing takes place:--we learn to DESPISE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.35#when we love, and precisely when we love best; all of it, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.36#unconsciously, without noise, without ostentation, with the shame and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.37#secrecy of goodness, which forbids the utterance of the pompous word
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.38#and the formula of virtue. Morality as attitude--is opposed to our taste
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.39#nowadays. This is ALSO an advance, as it was an advance in our fathers
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.40#that religion as an attitude finally became opposed to their taste,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.41#including the enmity and Voltairean bitterness against religion (and all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.42#that formerly belonged to freethinker-pantomime). It is the music in our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.43#conscience, the dance in our spirit, to which Puritan litanies, moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.44#sermons, and goody-goodness won't chime.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.45#217. Let us be careful in dealing with those who attach great importance
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.46#to being credited with moral tact and subtlety in moral discernment!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.47#They never forgive us if they have once made a mistake BEFORE us
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.48#(or even with REGARD to us)--they inevitably become our instinctive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.49#calumniators and detractors, even when they still remain our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.50#"friends."--Blessed are the forgetful: for they "get the better" even of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.51#their blunders.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.52#218. The psychologists of France--and where else are there still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.53#psychologists nowadays?--have never yet exhausted their bitter and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.54#manifold enjoyment of the betise bourgeoise, just as though... in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.55#short, they betray something thereby. Flaubert, for instance, the honest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.56#citizen of Rouen, neither saw, heard, nor tasted anything else in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.57#end; it was his mode of self-torment and refined cruelty. As this is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.58#growing wearisome, I would now recommend for a change something else
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.59#for a pleasure--namely, the unconscious astuteness with which good, fat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.60#honest mediocrity always behaves towards loftier spirits and the tasks
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.61#they have to perform, the subtle, barbed, Jesuitical astuteness, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.62#is a thousand times subtler than the taste and understanding of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.63#middle-class in its best moments--subtler even than the understanding of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.64#its victims:--a repeated proof that "instinct" is the most intelligent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.65#of all kinds of intelligence which have hitherto been discovered. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.66#short, you psychologists, study the philosophy of the "rule" in its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.67#struggle with the "exception": there you have a spectacle fit for Gods
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.68#and godlike malignity! Or, in plainer words, practise vivisection on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.69#"good people," on the "homo bonae voluntatis," ON YOURSELVES!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.70#219. The practice of judging and condemning morally, is the favourite
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.71#revenge of the intellectually shallow on those who are less so, it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.72#also a kind of indemnity for their being badly endowed by nature,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.73#and finally, it is an opportunity for acquiring spirit and BECOMING
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.74#subtle--malice spiritualises. They are glad in their inmost heart that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.75#there is a standard according to which those who are over-endowed with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.76#intellectual goods and privileges, are equal to them, they contend for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.77#the "equality of all before God," and almost NEED the belief in God for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.78#this purpose. It is among them that the most powerful antagonists of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.79#atheism are found. If any one were to say to them "A lofty spirituality
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.80#is beyond all comparison with the honesty and respectability of a merely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.81#moral man"--it would make them furious, I shall take care not to say
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.82#so. I would rather flatter them with my theory that lofty spirituality
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.83#itself exists only as the ultimate product of moral qualities, that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.84#is a synthesis of all qualities attributed to the "merely moral" man,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.85#after they have been acquired singly through long training and practice,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.86#perhaps during a whole series of generations, that lofty spirituality
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.87#is precisely the spiritualising of justice, and the beneficent severity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.88#which knows that it is authorized to maintain GRADATIONS OF RANK in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.89#world, even among things--and not only among men.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.90#220. Now that the praise of the "disinterested person" is so popular
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.91#one must--probably not without some danger--get an idea of WHAT people
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.92#actually take an interest in, and what are the things generally which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.93#fundamentally and profoundly concern ordinary men--including the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.94#cultured, even the learned, and perhaps philosophers also, if
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.95#appearances do not deceive. The fact thereby becomes obvious that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.96#greater part of what interests and charms higher natures, and more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.97#refined and fastidious tastes, seems absolutely "uninteresting" to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.98#the average man--if, notwithstanding, he perceive devotion to these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.99#interests, he calls it desinteresse, and wonders how it is possible to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.100#act "disinterestedly." There have been philosophers who could give this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.101#popular astonishment a seductive and mystical, other-worldly expression
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.102#(perhaps because they did not know the higher nature by experience?),
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.103#instead of stating the naked and candidly reasonable truth that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.104#"disinterested" action is very interesting and "interested" action,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.105#provided that... "And love?"--What! Even an action for love's sake
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.106#shall be "unegoistic"? But you fools--! "And the praise of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.107#self-sacrificer?"--But whoever has really offered sacrifice knows that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.108#he wanted and obtained something for it--perhaps something from himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.109#for something from himself; that he relinquished here in order to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.110#more there, perhaps in general to be more, or even feel himself "more."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.111#But this is a realm of questions and answers in which a more fastidious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.112#spirit does not like to stay: for here truth has to stifle her yawns so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.113#much when she is obliged to answer. And after all, truth is a woman; one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.114#must not use force with her.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.115#221. "It sometimes happens," said a moralistic pedant and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.116#trifle-retailer, "that I honour and respect an unselfish man: not,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.117#however, because he is unselfish, but because I think he has a right to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.118#be useful to another man at his own expense. In short, the question
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.119#is always who HE is, and who THE OTHER is. For instance, in a person
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.120#created and destined for command, self-denial and modest retirement,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.121#instead of being virtues, would be the waste of virtues: so it seems
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.122#to me. Every system of unegoistic morality which takes itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.123#unconditionally and appeals to every one, not only sins against good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.124#taste, but is also an incentive to sins of omission, an ADDITIONAL
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.125#seduction under the mask of philanthropy--and precisely a seduction and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.126#injury to the higher, rarer, and more privileged types of men. Moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.127#systems must be compelled first of all to bow before the GRADATIONS OF
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.128#RANK; their presumption must be driven home to their conscience--until
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.129#they thoroughly understand at last that it is IMMORAL to say that 'what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.130#is right for one is proper for another.'"--So said my moralistic pedant
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.131#and bonhomme. Did he perhaps deserve to be laughed at when he thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.132#exhorted systems of morals to practise morality? But one should not be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.133#too much in the right if one wishes to have the laughers on ONE'S OWN
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.134#side; a grain of wrong pertains even to good taste.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.135#222. Wherever sympathy (fellow-suffering) is preached nowadays--and,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.136#if I gather rightly, no other religion is any longer preached--let the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.137#psychologist have his ears open through all the vanity, through all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.138#noise which is natural to these preachers (as to all preachers), he will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.139#hear a hoarse, groaning, genuine note of SELF-CONTEMPT. It belongs
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.140#to the overshadowing and uglifying of Europe, which has been on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.141#the increase for a century (the first symptoms of which are already
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.142#specified documentarily in a thoughtful letter of Galiani to Madame
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.143#d'Epinay)--IF IT IS NOT REALLY THE CAUSE THEREOF! The man of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.144#"modern ideas," the conceited ape, is excessively dissatisfied with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.145#himself--this is perfectly certain. He suffers, and his vanity wants him
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.146#only "to suffer with his fellows."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.147#223. The hybrid European--a tolerably ugly plebeian, taken all in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.148#all--absolutely requires a costume: he needs history as a storeroom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.149#of costumes. To be sure, he notices that none of the costumes fit him
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.150#properly--he changes and changes. Let us look at the nineteenth century
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.151#with respect to these hasty preferences and changes in its masquerades
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.152#of style, and also with respect to its moments of desperation on account
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.153#of "nothing suiting" us. It is in vain to get ourselves up as romantic,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.154#or classical, or Christian, or Florentine, or barocco, or "national,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.155#in moribus et artibus: it does not "clothe us"! But the "spirit,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.156#especially the "historical spirit," profits even by this desperation:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.157#once and again a new sample of the past or of the foreign is tested,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.158#put on, taken off, packed up, and above all studied--we are the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.159#studious age in puncto of "costumes," I mean as concerns morals,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.160#articles of belief, artistic tastes, and religions; we are prepared as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.161#no other age has ever been for a carnival in the grand style, for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.162#most spiritual festival--laughter and arrogance, for the transcendental
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.163#height of supreme folly and Aristophanic ridicule of the world. Perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.164#we are still discovering the domain of our invention just here, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.165#domain where even we can still be original, probably as parodists of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.166#the world's history and as God's Merry-Andrews,--perhaps, though nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.167#else of the present have a future, our laughter itself may have a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.168#future!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.169#224. The historical sense (or the capacity for divining quickly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.170#the order of rank of the valuations according to which a people, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.171#community, or an individual has lived, the "divining instinct" for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.172#relationships of these valuations, for the relation of the authority
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.173#of the valuations to the authority of the operating forces),--this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.174#historical sense, which we Europeans claim as our specialty, has come
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.175#to us in the train of the enchanting and mad semi-barbarity into which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.176#Europe has been plunged by the democratic mingling of classes and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.177#races--it is only the nineteenth century that has recognized this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.178#faculty as its sixth sense. Owing to this mingling, the past of every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.179#form and mode of life, and of cultures which were formerly closely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.180#contiguous and superimposed on one another, flows forth into us "modern
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.181#souls"; our instincts now run back in all directions, we ourselves are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.182#a kind of chaos: in the end, as we have said, the spirit perceives its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.183#advantage therein. By means of our semi-barbarity in body and in desire,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.184#we have secret access everywhere, such as a noble age never had; we have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.185#access above all to the labyrinth of imperfect civilizations, and to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.186#every form of semi-barbarity that has at any time existed on earth; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.187#in so far as the most considerable part of human civilization hitherto
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.188#has just been semi-barbarity, the "historical sense" implies almost the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.189#sense and instinct for everything, the taste and tongue for everything:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.190#whereby it immediately proves itself to be an IGNOBLE sense. For
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.191#instance, we enjoy Homer once more: it is perhaps our happiest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.192#acquisition that we know how to appreciate Homer, whom men of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.193#distinguished culture (as the French of the seventeenth century, like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.194#Saint-Evremond, who reproached him for his ESPRIT VASTE, and even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.195#Voltaire, the last echo of the century) cannot and could not so easily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.196#appropriate--whom they scarcely permitted themselves to enjoy. The very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.197#decided Yea and Nay of their palate, their promptly ready disgust, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.198#hesitating reluctance with regard to everything strange, their horror of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.199#the bad taste even of lively curiosity, and in general the averseness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.200#every distinguished and self-sufficing culture to avow a new desire,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.201#a dissatisfaction with its own condition, or an admiration of what is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.202#strange: all this determines and disposes them unfavourably even towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.203#the best things of the world which are not their property or could not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.204#become their prey--and no faculty is more unintelligible to such men
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.205#than just this historical sense, with its truckling, plebeian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.206#curiosity. The case is not different with Shakespeare, that marvelous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.207#Spanish-Moorish-Saxon synthesis of taste, over whom an ancient Athenian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.208#of the circle of AEschylus would have half-killed himself with laughter
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.209#or irritation: but we--accept precisely this wild motleyness, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.210#medley of the most delicate, the most coarse, and the most artificial,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.211#with a secret confidence and cordiality; we enjoy it as a refinement
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.212#of art reserved expressly for us, and allow ourselves to be as little
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.213#disturbed by the repulsive fumes and the proximity of the English
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.214#populace in which Shakespeare's art and taste lives, as perhaps on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.215#the Chiaja of Naples, where, with all our senses awake, we go our way,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.216#enchanted and voluntarily, in spite of the drain-odour of the lower
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.217#quarters of the town. That as men of the "historical sense" we have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.218#our virtues, is not to be disputed:--we are unpretentious, unselfish,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.219#modest, brave, habituated to self-control and self-renunciation, very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.220#grateful, very patient, very complaisant--but with all this we are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.221#perhaps not very "tasteful." Let us finally confess it, that what is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.222#most difficult for us men of the "historical sense" to grasp, feel,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.223#taste, and love, what finds us fundamentally prejudiced and almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.224#hostile, is precisely the perfection and ultimate maturity in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.225#culture and art, the essentially noble in works and men, their moment
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.226#of smooth sea and halcyon self-sufficiency, the goldenness and coldness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.227#which all things show that have perfected themselves. Perhaps our great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.228#virtue of the historical sense is in necessary contrast to GOOD taste,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.229#at least to the very bad taste; and we can only evoke in ourselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.230#imperfectly, hesitatingly, and with compulsion the small, short, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.231#happy godsends and glorifications of human life as they shine here and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.232#there: those moments and marvelous experiences when a great power has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.233#voluntarily come to a halt before the boundless and infinite,--when a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.234#super-abundance of refined delight has been enjoyed by a sudden checking
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.235#and petrifying, by standing firmly and planting oneself fixedly on still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.236#trembling ground. PROPORTIONATENESS is strange to us, let us confess it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.237#to ourselves; our itching is really the itching for the infinite, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.238#immeasurable. Like the rider on his forward panting horse, we let the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.239#reins fall before the infinite, we modern men, we semi-barbarians--and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.240#are only in OUR highest bliss when we--ARE IN MOST DANGER.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.241#225. Whether it be hedonism, pessimism, utilitarianism, or eudaemonism,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.242#all those modes of thinking which measure the worth of things according
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.243#to PLEASURE and PAIN, that is, according to accompanying circumstances
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.244#and secondary considerations, are plausible modes of thought and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.245#naivetes, which every one conscious of CREATIVE powers and an artist's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.246#conscience will look down upon with scorn, though not without sympathy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.247#Sympathy for you!--to be sure, that is not sympathy as you understand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.248#it: it is not sympathy for social "distress," for "society" with its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.249#sick and misfortuned, for the hereditarily vicious and defective who lie
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.250#on the ground around us; still less is it sympathy for the grumbling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.251#vexed, revolutionary slave-classes who strive after power--they call it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.252#"freedom." OUR sympathy is a loftier and further-sighted sympathy:--we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.253#see how MAN dwarfs himself, how YOU dwarf him! and there are moments
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.254#when we view YOUR sympathy with an indescribable anguish, when we resist
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.255#it,--when we regard your seriousness as more dangerous than any kind
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.256#of levity. You want, if possible--and there is not a more foolish "if
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.257#possible"--TO DO AWAY WITH SUFFERING; and we?--it really seems that WE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.258#would rather have it increased and made worse than it has ever been!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.259#Well-being, as you understand it--is certainly not a goal; it seems
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.260#to us an END; a condition which at once renders man ludicrous and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.261#contemptible--and makes his destruction DESIRABLE! The discipline
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.262#of suffering, of GREAT suffering--know ye not that it is only THIS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.263#discipline that has produced all the elevations of humanity hitherto?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.264#The tension of soul in misfortune which communicates to it its energy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.265#its shuddering in view of rack and ruin, its inventiveness and bravery
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.266#in undergoing, enduring, interpreting, and exploiting misfortune, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.267#whatever depth, mystery, disguise, spirit, artifice, or greatness has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.268#been bestowed upon the soul--has it not been bestowed through suffering,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.269#through the discipline of great suffering? In man CREATURE and CREATOR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.270#are united: in man there is not only matter, shred, excess, clay, mire,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.271#folly, chaos; but there is also the creator, the sculptor, the hardness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.272#of the hammer, the divinity of the spectator, and the seventh day--do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.273#ye understand this contrast? And that YOUR sympathy for the "creature
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.274#in man" applies to that which has to be fashioned, bruised, forged,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.275#stretched, roasted, annealed, refined--to that which must necessarily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.276#SUFFER, and IS MEANT to suffer? And our sympathy--do ye not understand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.277#what our REVERSE sympathy applies to, when it resists your sympathy as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.278#the worst of all pampering and enervation?--So it is sympathy AGAINST
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.279#sympathy!--But to repeat it once more, there are higher problems than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.280#the problems of pleasure and pain and sympathy; and all systems of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.281#philosophy which deal only with these are naivetes.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.282#226. WE IMMORALISTS.--This world with which WE are concerned, in which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.283#we have to fear and love, this almost invisible, inaudible world of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.284#delicate command and delicate obedience, a world of "almost" in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.285#respect, captious, insidious, sharp, and tender--yes, it is well
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.286#protected from clumsy spectators and familiar curiosity! We are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.287#woven into a strong net and garment of duties, and CANNOT disengage
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.288#ourselves--precisely here, we are "men of duty," even we! Occasionally,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.289#it is true, we dance in our "chains" and betwixt our "swords"; it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.290#is none the less true that more often we gnash our teeth under the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.291#circumstances, and are impatient at the secret hardship of our lot. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.292#do what we will, fools and appearances say of us: "These are men WITHOUT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.293#duty,"--we have always fools and appearances against us!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.294#227. Honesty, granting that it is the virtue of which we cannot rid
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.295#ourselves, we free spirits--well, we will labour at it with all our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.296#perversity and love, and not tire of "perfecting" ourselves in OUR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.297#virtue, which alone remains: may its glance some day overspread like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.298#a gilded, blue, mocking twilight this aging civilization with its dull
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.299#gloomy seriousness! And if, nevertheless, our honesty should one day
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.300#grow weary, and sigh, and stretch its limbs, and find us too hard, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.301#would fain have it pleasanter, easier, and gentler, like an agreeable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.302#vice, let us remain HARD, we latest Stoics, and let us send to its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.303#help whatever devilry we have in us:--our disgust at the clumsy
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.304#and undefined, our "NITIMUR IN VETITUM," our love of adventure,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.305#our sharpened and fastidious curiosity, our most subtle, disguised,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.306#intellectual Will to Power and universal conquest, which rambles and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.307#roves avidiously around all the realms of the future--let us go with all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.308#our "devils" to the help of our "God"! It is probable that people will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.309#misunderstand and mistake us on that account: what does it matter! They
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.310#will say: "Their 'honesty'--that is their devilry, and nothing else!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.311#What does it matter! And even if they were right--have not all Gods
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.312#hitherto been such sanctified, re-baptized devils? And after all, what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.313#do we know of ourselves? And what the spirit that leads us wants TO BE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.314#CALLED? (It is a question of names.) And how many spirits we harbour?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.315#Our honesty, we free spirits--let us be careful lest it become our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.316#vanity, our ornament and ostentation, our limitation, our stupidity!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.317#Every virtue inclines to stupidity, every stupidity to virtue; "stupid
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.318#to the point of sanctity," they say in Russia,--let us be careful lest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.319#out of pure honesty we eventually become saints and bores! Is not life
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.320#a hundred times too short for us--to bore ourselves? One would have to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.321#believe in eternal life in order to...
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.322#228. I hope to be forgiven for discovering that all moral philosophy
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.323#hitherto has been tedious and has belonged to the soporific
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.324#appliances--and that "virtue," in my opinion, has been MORE injured
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.325#by the TEDIOUSNESS of its advocates than by anything else; at the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.326#time, however, I would not wish to overlook their general usefulness. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.327#is desirable that as few people as possible should reflect upon morals,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.328#and consequently it is very desirable that morals should not some day
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.329#become interesting! But let us not be afraid! Things still remain today
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.330#as they have always been: I see no one in Europe who has (or DISCLOSES)
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.331#an idea of the fact that philosophizing concerning morals might be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.332#conducted in a dangerous, captious, and ensnaring manner--that CALAMITY
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.333#might be involved therein. Observe, for example, the indefatigable,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.334#inevitable English utilitarians: how ponderously and respectably they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.335#stalk on, stalk along (a Homeric metaphor expresses it better) in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.336#footsteps of Bentham, just as he had already stalked in the footsteps of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.337#the respectable Helvetius! (no, he was not a dangerous man, Helvetius,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.338#CE SENATEUR POCOCURANTE, to use an expression of Galiani). No new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.339#thought, nothing of the nature of a finer turning or better expression
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.340#of an old thought, not even a proper history of what has been previously
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.341#thought on the subject: an IMPOSSIBLE literature, taking it all in all,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.342#unless one knows how to leaven it with some mischief. In effect, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.343#old English vice called CANT, which is MORAL TARTUFFISM, has insinuated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.344#itself also into these moralists (whom one must certainly read with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.345#eye to their motives if one MUST read them), concealed this time under
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.346#the new form of the scientific spirit; moreover, there is not absent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.347#from them a secret struggle with the pangs of conscience, from which a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.348#race of former Puritans must naturally suffer, in all their scientific
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.349#tinkering with morals. (Is not a moralist the opposite of a Puritan?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.350#That is to say, as a thinker who regards morality as questionable,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.351#as worthy of interrogation, in short, as a problem? Is moralizing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.352#not-immoral?) In the end, they all want English morality to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.353#recognized as authoritative, inasmuch as mankind, or the "general
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.354#utility," or "the happiness of the greatest number,"--no! the happiness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.355#of ENGLAND, will be best served thereby. They would like, by all means,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.356#to convince themselves that the striving after English happiness, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.357#mean after COMFORT and FASHION (and in the highest instance, a seat in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.358#Parliament), is at the same time the true path of virtue; in fact, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.359#in so far as there has been virtue in the world hitherto, it has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.360#just consisted in such striving. Not one of those ponderous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.361#conscience-stricken herding-animals (who undertake to advocate the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.362#cause of egoism as conducive to the general welfare) wants to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.363#any knowledge or inkling of the facts that the "general welfare" is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.364#no ideal, no goal, no notion that can be at all grasped, but is only a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.365#nostrum,--that what is fair to one MAY NOT at all be fair to another,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.366#that the requirement of one morality for all is really a detriment to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.367#higher men, in short, that there is a DISTINCTION OF RANK between man
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.368#and man, and consequently between morality and morality. They are an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.369#unassuming and fundamentally mediocre species of men, these utilitarian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.370#Englishmen, and, as already remarked, in so far as they are tedious, one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.371#cannot think highly enough of their utility. One ought even to ENCOURAGE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.372#them, as has been partially attempted in the following rhymes:--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.373#    Hail, ye worthies, barrow-wheeling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.374#    "Longer--better," aye revealing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.375#    Stiffer aye in head and knee;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.376#    Unenraptured, never jesting,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.377#    Mediocre everlasting,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.378#    SANS GENIE ET SANS ESPRIT!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.379#229. In these later ages, which may be proud of their humanity, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.380#still remains so much fear, so much SUPERSTITION of the fear, of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.381#"cruel wild beast," the mastering of which constitutes the very pride of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.382#these humaner ages--that even obvious truths, as if by the agreement
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.383#of centuries, have long remained unuttered, because they have the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.384#appearance of helping the finally slain wild beast back to life again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.385#I perhaps risk something when I allow such a truth to escape; let
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.386#others capture it again and give it so much "milk of pious sentiment"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.387#[FOOTNOTE: An expression from Schiller's William Tell, Act IV, Scene
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.388#3.] to drink, that it will lie down quiet and forgotten, in its old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.389#corner.--One ought to learn anew about cruelty, and open one's eyes;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.390#one ought at last to learn impatience, in order that such immodest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.391#gross errors--as, for instance, have been fostered by ancient and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.392#modern philosophers with regard to tragedy--may no longer wander about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.393#virtuously and boldly. Almost everything that we call "higher culture"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.394#is based upon the spiritualising and intensifying of CRUELTY--this is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.395#my thesis; the "wild beast" has not been slain at all, it lives, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.396#flourishes, it has only been--transfigured. That which constitutes the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.397#painful delight of tragedy is cruelty; that which operates agreeably in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.398#so-called tragic sympathy, and at the basis even of everything sublime,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.399#up to the highest and most delicate thrills of metaphysics, obtains its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.400#sweetness solely from the intermingled ingredient of cruelty. What the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.401#Roman enjoys in the arena, the Christian in the ecstasies of the cross,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.402#the Spaniard at the sight of the faggot and stake, or of the bull-fight,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.403#the present-day Japanese who presses his way to the tragedy, the workman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.404#of the Parisian suburbs who has a homesickness for bloody revolutions,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.405#the Wagnerienne who, with unhinged will, "undergoes" the performance of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.406#"Tristan and Isolde"--what all these enjoy, and strive with mysterious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.407#ardour to drink in, is the philtre of the great Circe "cruelty." Here,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.408#to be sure, we must put aside entirely the blundering psychology of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.409#former times, which could only teach with regard to cruelty that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.410#it originated at the sight of the suffering of OTHERS: there is an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.411#abundant, super-abundant enjoyment even in one's own suffering, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.412#causing one's own suffering--and wherever man has allowed himself to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.413#persuaded to self-denial in the RELIGIOUS sense, or to self-mutilation,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.414#as among the Phoenicians and ascetics, or in general, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.415#desensualisation, decarnalisation, and contrition, to Puritanical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.416#repentance-spasms, to vivisection of conscience and to Pascal-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.417#SACRIFIZIA DELL' INTELLETO, he is secretly allured and impelled
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.418#forwards by his cruelty, by the dangerous thrill of cruelty TOWARDS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.419#HIMSELF.--Finally, let us consider that even the seeker of knowledge
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.420#operates as an artist and glorifier of cruelty, in that he compels his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.421#spirit to perceive AGAINST its own inclination, and often enough against
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.422#the wishes of his heart:--he forces it to say Nay, where he would like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.423#to affirm, love, and adore; indeed, every instance of taking a thing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.424#profoundly and fundamentally, is a violation, an intentional injuring
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.425#of the fundamental will of the spirit, which instinctively aims at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.426#appearance and superficiality,--even in every desire for knowledge there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.427#is a drop of cruelty.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.428#230. Perhaps what I have said here about a "fundamental will of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.429#spirit" may not be understood without further details; I may be allowed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.430#a word of explanation.--That imperious something which is popularly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.431#called "the spirit," wishes to be master internally and externally,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.432#and to feel itself master; it has the will of a multiplicity for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.433#simplicity, a binding, taming, imperious, and essentially ruling will.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.434#Its requirements and capacities here, are the same as those assigned by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.435#physiologists to everything that lives, grows, and multiplies. The power
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.436#of the spirit to appropriate foreign elements reveals itself in a strong
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.437#tendency to assimilate the new to the old, to simplify the manifold,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.438#to overlook or repudiate the absolutely contradictory; just as it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.439#arbitrarily re-underlines, makes prominent, and falsifies for itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.440#certain traits and lines in the foreign elements, in every portion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.441#the "outside world." Its object thereby is the incorporation of new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.442#"experiences," the assortment of new things in the old arrangements--in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.443#short, growth; or more properly, the FEELING of growth, the feeling of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.444#increased power--is its object. This same will has at its service an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.445#apparently opposed impulse of the spirit, a suddenly adopted preference
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.446#of ignorance, of arbitrary shutting out, a closing of windows, an inner
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.447#denial of this or that, a prohibition to approach, a sort of defensive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.448#attitude against much that is knowable, a contentment with obscurity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.449#with the shutting-in horizon, an acceptance and approval of ignorance:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.450#as that which is all necessary according to the degree of its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.451#appropriating power, its "digestive power," to speak figuratively (and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.452#in fact "the spirit" resembles a stomach more than anything else). Here
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.453#also belong an occasional propensity of the spirit to let itself be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.454#deceived (perhaps with a waggish suspicion that it is NOT so and so,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.455#but is only allowed to pass as such), a delight in uncertainty and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.456#ambiguity, an exulting enjoyment of arbitrary, out-of-the-way narrowness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.457#and mystery, of the too-near, of the foreground, of the magnified,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.458#the diminished, the misshapen, the beautified--an enjoyment of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.459#arbitrariness of all these manifestations of power. Finally, in this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.460#connection, there is the not unscrupulous readiness of the spirit to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.461#deceive other spirits and dissemble before them--the constant pressing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.462#and straining of a creating, shaping, changeable power: the spirit
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.463#enjoys therein its craftiness and its variety of disguises, it enjoys
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.464#also its feeling of security therein--it is precisely by its Protean
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.465#arts that it is best protected and concealed!--COUNTER TO this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.466#propensity for appearance, for simplification, for a disguise, for a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.467#cloak, in short, for an outside--for every outside is a cloak--there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.468#operates the sublime tendency of the man of knowledge, which takes, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.469#INSISTS on taking things profoundly, variously, and thoroughly; as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.470#kind of cruelty of the intellectual conscience and taste, which every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.471#courageous thinker will acknowledge in himself, provided, as it ought
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.472#to be, that he has sharpened and hardened his eye sufficiently long for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.473#introspection, and is accustomed to severe discipline and even severe
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.474#words. He will say: "There is something cruel in the tendency of my
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.475#spirit": let the virtuous and amiable try to convince him that it is not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.476#so! In fact, it would sound nicer, if, instead of our cruelty, perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.477#our "extravagant honesty" were talked about, whispered about, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.478#glorified--we free, VERY free spirits--and some day perhaps SUCH will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.479#actually be our--posthumous glory! Meanwhile--for there is plenty of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.480#time until then--we should be least inclined to deck ourselves out in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.481#such florid and fringed moral verbiage; our whole former work has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.482#just made us sick of this taste and its sprightly exuberance. They are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.483#beautiful, glistening, jingling, festive words: honesty, love of truth,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.484#love of wisdom, sacrifice for knowledge, heroism of the truthful--there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.485#is something in them that makes one's heart swell with pride. But we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.486#anchorites and marmots have long ago persuaded ourselves in all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.487#secrecy of an anchorite's conscience, that this worthy parade of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.488#verbiage also belongs to the old false adornment, frippery, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.489#gold-dust of unconscious human vanity, and that even under such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.490#flattering colour and repainting, the terrible original text HOMO NATURA
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.491#must again be recognized. In effect, to translate man back again into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.492#nature; to master the many vain and visionary interpretations and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.493#subordinate meanings which have hitherto been scratched and daubed over
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.494#the eternal original text, HOMO NATURA; to bring it about that man shall
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.495#henceforth stand before man as he now, hardened by the discipline
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.496#of science, stands before the OTHER forms of nature, with fearless
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.497#Oedipus-eyes, and stopped Ulysses-ears, deaf to the enticements of old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.498#metaphysical bird-catchers, who have piped to him far too long: "Thou
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.499#art more! thou art higher! thou hast a different origin!"--this may be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.500#a strange and foolish task, but that it is a TASK, who can deny! Why did
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.501#we choose it, this foolish task? Or, to put the question differently:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.502#"Why knowledge at all?" Every one will ask us about this. And thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.503#pressed, we, who have asked ourselves the question a hundred times, have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.504#not found and cannot find any better answer....
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.505#231. Learning alters us, it does what all nourishment does that does not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.506#merely "conserve"--as the physiologist knows. But at the bottom of our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.507#souls, quite "down below," there is certainly something unteachable,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.508#a granite of spiritual fate, of predetermined decision and answer to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.509#predetermined, chosen questions. In each cardinal problem there speaks
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.510#an unchangeable "I am this"; a thinker cannot learn anew about man and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.511#woman, for instance, but can only learn fully--he can only follow to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.512#end what is "fixed" about them in himself. Occasionally we find certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.513#solutions of problems which make strong beliefs for us; perhaps they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.514#are henceforth called "convictions." Later on--one sees in them only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.515#footsteps to self-knowledge, guide-posts to the problem which we
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.516#ourselves ARE--or more correctly to the great stupidity which we embody,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.517#our spiritual fate, the UNTEACHABLE in us, quite "down below."--In view
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.518#of this liberal compliment which I have just paid myself, permission
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.519#will perhaps be more readily allowed me to utter some truths about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.520#"woman as she is," provided that it is known at the outset how literally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.521#they are merely--MY truths.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.522#232. Woman wishes to be independent, and therefore she begins to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.523#enlighten men about "woman as she is"--THIS is one of the worst
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.524#developments of the general UGLIFYING of Europe. For what must these
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.525#clumsy attempts of feminine scientificality and self-exposure bring
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.526#to light! Woman has so much cause for shame; in woman there is so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.527#much pedantry, superficiality, schoolmasterliness, petty presumption,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.528#unbridledness, and indiscretion concealed--study only woman's behaviour
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.529#towards children!--which has really been best restrained and dominated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.530#hitherto by the FEAR of man. Alas, if ever the "eternally tedious in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.531#woman"--she has plenty of it!--is allowed to venture forth! if she
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.532#begins radically and on principle to unlearn her wisdom and art-of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.533#charming, of playing, of frightening away sorrow, of alleviating and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.534#taking easily; if she forgets her delicate aptitude for agreeable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.535#desires! Female voices are already raised, which, by Saint Aristophanes!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.536#make one afraid:--with medical explicitness it is stated in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.537#threatening manner what woman first and last REQUIRES from man. Is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.538#it not in the very worst taste that woman thus sets herself up to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.539#scientific? Enlightenment hitherto has fortunately been men's affair,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.540#men's gift--we remained therewith "among ourselves"; and in the end,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.541#in view of all that women write about "woman," we may well have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.542#considerable doubt as to whether woman really DESIRES enlightenment
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.543#about herself--and CAN desire it. If woman does not thereby seek a new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.544#ORNAMENT for herself--I believe ornamentation belongs to the eternally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.545#feminine?--why, then, she wishes to make herself feared: perhaps she
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.546#thereby wishes to get the mastery. But she does not want truth--what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.547#does woman care for truth? From the very first, nothing is more foreign,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.548#more repugnant, or more hostile to woman than truth--her great art is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.549#falsehood, her chief concern is appearance and beauty. Let us confess
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.550#it, we men: we honour and love this very art and this very instinct in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.551#woman: we who have the hard task, and for our recreation gladly seek the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.552#company of beings under whose hands, glances, and delicate follies, our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.553#seriousness, our gravity, and profundity appear almost like follies to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.554#us. Finally, I ask the question: Did a woman herself ever acknowledge
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.555#profundity in a woman's mind, or justice in a woman's heart? And is it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.556#not true that on the whole "woman" has hitherto been most despised by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.557#woman herself, and not at all by us?--We men desire that woman should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.558#not continue to compromise herself by enlightening us; just as it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.559#man's care and the consideration for woman, when the church decreed:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.560#mulier taceat in ecclesia. It was to the benefit of woman when Napoleon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.561#gave the too eloquent Madame de Stael to understand: mulier taceat in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.562#politicis!--and in my opinion, he is a true friend of woman who calls
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.563#out to women today: mulier taceat de mulierel.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.564#233. It betrays corruption of the instincts--apart from the fact that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.565#it betrays bad taste--when a woman refers to Madame Roland, or Madame de
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.566#Stael, or Monsieur George Sand, as though something were proved thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.567#in favour of "woman as she is." Among men, these are the three comical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.568#women as they are--nothing more!--and just the best involuntary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.569#counter-arguments against feminine emancipation and autonomy.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.570#234. Stupidity in the kitchen; woman as cook; the terrible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.571#thoughtlessness with which the feeding of the family and the master of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.572#the house is managed! Woman does not understand what food means, and she
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.573#insists on being cook! If woman had been a thinking creature, she should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.574#certainly, as cook for thousands of years, have discovered the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.575#important physiological facts, and should likewise have got possession
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.576#of the healing art! Through bad female cooks--through the entire lack
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.577#of reason in the kitchen--the development of mankind has been longest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.578#retarded and most interfered with: even today matters are very little
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.579#better. A word to High School girls.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.580#235. There are turns and casts of fancy, there are sentences, little
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.581#handfuls of words, in which a whole culture, a whole society suddenly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.582#crystallises itself. Among these is the incidental remark of Madame de
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.583#Lambert to her son: "MON AMI, NE VOUS PERMETTEZ JAMAIS QUE DES FOLIES,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.584#QUI VOUS FERONT GRAND PLAISIR"--the motherliest and wisest remark, by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.585#the way, that was ever addressed to a son.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.586#236. I have no doubt that every noble woman will oppose what Dante and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.587#Goethe believed about woman--the former when he sang, "ELLA GUARDAVA
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.588#SUSO, ED IO IN LEI," and the latter when he interpreted it, "the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.589#eternally feminine draws us ALOFT"; for THIS is just what she believes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.590#of the eternally masculine.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.591#237.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.592#SEVEN APOPHTHEGMS FOR WOMEN
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.593#How the longest ennui flees, When a man comes to our knees!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.594#Age, alas! and science staid, Furnish even weak virtue aid.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.595#Sombre garb and silence meet: Dress for every dame--discreet.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.596#Whom I thank when in my bliss? God!--and my good tailoress!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.597#Young, a flower-decked cavern home; Old, a dragon thence doth roam.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.598#Noble title, leg that's fine, Man as well: Oh, were HE mine!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.599#Speech in brief and sense in mass--Slippery for the jenny-ass!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.600#237A. Woman has hitherto been treated by men like birds, which, losing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.601#their way, have come down among them from an elevation: as something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.602#delicate, fragile, wild, strange, sweet, and animating--but as something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.603#also which must be cooped up to prevent it flying away.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.604#238. To be mistaken in the fundamental problem of "man and woman," to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.605#deny here the profoundest antagonism and the necessity for an eternally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.606#hostile tension, to dream here perhaps of equal rights, equal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.607#training, equal claims and obligations: that is a TYPICAL sign of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.608#shallow-mindedness; and a thinker who has proved himself shallow at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.609#this dangerous spot--shallow in instinct!--may generally be regarded as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.610#suspicious, nay more, as betrayed, as discovered; he will probably prove
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.611#too "short" for all fundamental questions of life, future as well as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.612#present, and will be unable to descend into ANY of the depths. On the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.613#other hand, a man who has depth of spirit as well as of desires, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.614#has also the depth of benevolence which is capable of severity and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.615#harshness, and easily confounded with them, can only think of woman as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.616#ORIENTALS do: he must conceive of her as a possession, as confinable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.617#property, as a being predestined for service and accomplishing her
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.618#mission therein--he must take his stand in this matter upon the immense
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.619#rationality of Asia, upon the superiority of the instinct of Asia, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.620#the Greeks did formerly; those best heirs and scholars of Asia--who,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.621#as is well known, with their INCREASING culture and amplitude of power,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.622#from Homer to the time of Pericles, became gradually STRICTER towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.623#woman, in short, more Oriental. HOW necessary, HOW logical, even HOW
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.624#humanely desirable this was, let us consider for ourselves!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.625#239. The weaker sex has in no previous age been treated with so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.626#much respect by men as at present--this belongs to the tendency and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.627#fundamental taste of democracy, in the same way as disrespectfulness to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.628#old age--what wonder is it that abuse should be immediately made of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.629#this respect? They want more, they learn to make claims, the tribute
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.630#of respect is at last felt to be well-nigh galling; rivalry for rights,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.631#indeed actual strife itself, would be preferred: in a word, woman is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.632#losing modesty. And let us immediately add that she is also losing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.633#taste. She is unlearning to FEAR man: but the woman who "unlearns to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.634#fear" sacrifices her most womanly instincts. That woman should venture
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.635#forward when the fear-inspiring quality in man--or more definitely,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.636#the MAN in man--is no longer either desired or fully developed, is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.637#reasonable enough and also intelligible enough; what is more difficult
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.638#to understand is that precisely thereby--woman deteriorates. This is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.639#what is happening nowadays: let us not deceive ourselves about it!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.640#Wherever the industrial spirit has triumphed over the military
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.641#and aristocratic spirit, woman strives for the economic and legal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.642#independence of a clerk: "woman as clerkess" is inscribed on the portal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.643#of the modern society which is in course of formation. While she
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.644#thus appropriates new rights, aspires to be "master," and inscribes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.645#"progress" of woman on her flags and banners, the very opposite realises
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.646#itself with terrible obviousness: WOMAN RETROGRADES. Since the French
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.647#Revolution the influence of woman in Europe has DECLINED in proportion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.648#as she has increased her rights and claims; and the "emancipation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.649#woman," insofar as it is desired and demanded by women themselves (and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.650#not only by masculine shallow-pates), thus proves to be a remarkable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.651#symptom of the increased weakening and deadening of the most womanly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.652#instincts. There is STUPIDITY in this movement, an almost masculine
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.653#stupidity, of which a well-reared woman--who is always a sensible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.654#woman--might be heartily ashamed. To lose the intuition as to the ground
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.655#upon which she can most surely achieve victory; to neglect exercise in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.656#the use of her proper weapons; to let-herself-go before man, perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.657#even "to the book," where formerly she kept herself in control and in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.658#refined, artful humility; to neutralize with her virtuous audacity man's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.659#faith in a VEILED, fundamentally different ideal in woman, something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.660#eternally, necessarily feminine; to emphatically and loquaciously
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.661#dissuade man from the idea that woman must be preserved, cared for,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.662#protected, and indulged, like some delicate, strangely wild, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.663#often pleasant domestic animal; the clumsy and indignant collection of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.664#everything of the nature of servitude and bondage which the position of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.665#woman in the hitherto existing order of society has entailed and still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.666#entails (as though slavery were a counter-argument, and not rather a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.667#condition of every higher culture, of every elevation of culture):--what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.668#does all this betoken, if not a disintegration of womanly instincts,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.669#a defeminising? Certainly, there are enough of idiotic friends and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.670#corrupters of woman among the learned asses of the masculine sex, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.671#advise woman to defeminize herself in this manner, and to imitate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.672#all the stupidities from which "man" in Europe, European "manliness,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.673#suffers,--who would like to lower woman to "general culture," indeed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.674#even to newspaper reading and meddling with politics. Here and there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.675#they wish even to make women into free spirits and literary workers: as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.676#though a woman without piety would not be something perfectly obnoxious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.677#or ludicrous to a profound and godless man;--almost everywhere her
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.678#nerves are being ruined by the most morbid and dangerous kind of music
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.679#(our latest German music), and she is daily being made more hysterical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.680#and more incapable of fulfilling her first and last function, that of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.681#bearing robust children. They wish to "cultivate" her in general still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.682#more, and intend, as they say, to make the "weaker sex" STRONG by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.683#culture: as if history did not teach in the most emphatic manner that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.684#the "cultivating" of mankind and his weakening--that is to say, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.685#weakening, dissipating, and languishing of his FORCE OF WILL--have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.686#always kept pace with one another, and that the most powerful and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.687#influential women in the world (and lastly, the mother of Napoleon)
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.688#had just to thank their force of will--and not their schoolmasters--for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.689#their power and ascendancy over men. That which inspires respect
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.690#in woman, and often enough fear also, is her NATURE, which is more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.691#"natural" than that of man, her genuine, carnivora-like, cunning
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.692#flexibility, her tiger-claws beneath the glove, her NAIVETE in egoism,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.693#her untrainableness and innate wildness, the incomprehensibleness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.694#extent, and deviation of her desires and virtues. That which, in spite
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.695#of fear, excites one's sympathy for the dangerous and beautiful cat,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.696#"woman," is that she seems more afflicted, more vulnerable, more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.697#necessitous of love, and more condemned to disillusionment than any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.698#other creature. Fear and sympathy it is with these feelings that man has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.699#hitherto stood in the presence of woman, always with one foot already in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.700#tragedy, which rends while it delights--What? And all that is now to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.701#be at an end? And the DISENCHANTMENT of woman is in progress? The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.702#tediousness of woman is slowly evolving? Oh Europe! Europe! We know
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.703#the horned animal which was always most attractive to thee, from which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.704#danger is ever again threatening thee! Thy old fable might once more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.705#become "history"--an immense stupidity might once again overmaster
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:7.706#thee and carry thee away! And no God concealed beneath it--no! only an
