urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.1#CHAPTER VIII. PEOPLES AND COUNTRIES
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.2#240. I HEARD, once again for the first time, Richard Wagner's overture
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.3#to the Mastersinger: it is a piece of magnificent, gorgeous, heavy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.4#latter-day art, which has the pride to presuppose two centuries of music
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.5#as still living, in order that it may be understood:--it is an honour
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.6#to Germans that such a pride did not miscalculate! What flavours
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.7#and forces, what seasons and climes do we not find mingled in it! It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.8#impresses us at one time as ancient, at another time as foreign, bitter,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.9#and too modern, it is as arbitrary as it is pompously traditional, it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.10#is not infrequently roguish, still oftener rough and coarse--it has fire
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.11#and courage, and at the same time the loose, dun-coloured skin of fruits
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.12#which ripen too late. It flows broad and full: and suddenly there is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.13#moment of inexplicable hesitation, like a gap that opens between cause
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.14#and effect, an oppression that makes us dream, almost a nightmare; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.15#already it broadens and widens anew, the old stream of delight--the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.16#manifold delight,--of old and new happiness; including ESPECIALLY
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.17#the joy of the artist in himself, which he refuses to conceal, his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.18#astonished, happy cognizance of his mastery of the expedients here
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.19#employed, the new, newly acquired, imperfectly tested expedients of art
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.20#which he apparently betrays to us. All in all, however, no beauty, no
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.21#South, nothing of the delicate southern clearness of the sky, nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.22#of grace, no dance, hardly a will to logic; a certain clumsiness even,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.23#which is also emphasized, as though the artist wished to say to us: "It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.24#is part of my intention"; a cumbersome drapery, something arbitrarily
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.25#barbaric and ceremonious, a flirring of learned and venerable conceits
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.26#and witticisms; something German in the best and worst sense of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.27#the word, something in the German style, manifold, formless, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.28#inexhaustible; a certain German potency and super-plenitude of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.29#soul, which is not afraid to hide itself under the RAFFINEMENTS of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.30#decadence--which, perhaps, feels itself most at ease there; a real,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.31#genuine token of the German soul, which is at the same time young and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.32#aged, too ripe and yet still too rich in futurity. This kind of music
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.33#expresses best what I think of the Germans: they belong to the day
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.34#before yesterday and the day after tomorrow--THEY HAVE AS YET NO TODAY.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.35#241. We "good Europeans," we also have hours when we allow ourselves a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.36#warm-hearted patriotism, a plunge and relapse into old loves and narrow
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.37#views--I have just given an example of it--hours of national excitement,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.38#of patriotic anguish, and all other sorts of old-fashioned floods of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.39#sentiment. Duller spirits may perhaps only get done with what confines
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.40#its operations in us to hours and plays itself out in hours--in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.41#considerable time: some in half a year, others in half a lifetime,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.42#according to the speed and strength with which they digest and "change
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.43#their material." Indeed, I could think of sluggish, hesitating races,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.44#which even in our rapidly moving Europe, would require half a century
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.45#ere they could surmount such atavistic attacks of patriotism and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.46#soil-attachment, and return once more to reason, that is to say, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.47#"good Europeanism." And while digressing on this possibility, I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.48#happen to become an ear-witness of a conversation between two old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.49#patriots--they were evidently both hard of hearing and consequently
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.50#spoke all the louder. "HE has as much, and knows as much, philosophy as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.51#a peasant or a corps-student," said the one--"he is still innocent. But
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.52#what does that matter nowadays! It is the age of the masses: they lie on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.53#their belly before everything that is massive. And so also in politicis.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.54#A statesman who rears up for them a new Tower of Babel, some monstrosity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.55#of empire and power, they call 'great'--what does it matter that we more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.56#prudent and conservative ones do not meanwhile give up the old belief
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.57#that it is only the great thought that gives greatness to an action or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.58#affair. Supposing a statesman were to bring his people into the position
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.59#of being obliged henceforth to practise 'high politics,' for which they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.60#were by nature badly endowed and prepared, so that they would have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.61#to sacrifice their old and reliable virtues, out of love to a new and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.62#doubtful mediocrity;--supposing a statesman were to condemn his people
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.63#generally to 'practise politics,' when they have hitherto had something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.64#better to do and think about, and when in the depths of their souls
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.65#they have been unable to free themselves from a prudent loathing of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.66#the restlessness, emptiness, and noisy wranglings of the essentially
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.67#politics-practising nations;--supposing such a statesman were to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.68#stimulate the slumbering passions and avidities of his people, were to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.69#make a stigma out of their former diffidence and delight in aloofness,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.70#an offence out of their exoticism and hidden permanency, were to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.71#depreciate their most radical proclivities, subvert their consciences,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.72#make their minds narrow, and their tastes 'national'--what! a statesman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.73#who should do all this, which his people would have to do penance for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.74#throughout their whole future, if they had a future, such a statesman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.75#would be GREAT, would he?"--"Undoubtedly!" replied the other old patriot
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.76#vehemently, "otherwise he COULD NOT have done it! It was mad perhaps to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.77#wish such a thing! But perhaps everything great has been just as mad
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.78#at its commencement!"--"Misuse of words!" cried his interlocutor,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.79#contradictorily--"strong! strong! Strong and mad! NOT great!"--The old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.80#men had obviously become heated as they thus shouted their "truths" in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.81#each other's faces, but I, in my happiness and apartness, considered how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.82#soon a stronger one may become master of the strong, and also that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.83#there is a compensation for the intellectual superficialising of a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.84#nation--namely, in the deepening of another.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.85#242. Whether we call it "civilization," or "humanising," or "progress,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.86#which now distinguishes the European, whether we call it simply, without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.87#praise or blame, by the political formula the DEMOCRATIC movement in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.88#Europe--behind all the moral and political foregrounds pointed to by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.89#such formulas, an immense PHYSIOLOGICAL PROCESS goes on, which is ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.90#extending the process of the assimilation of Europeans, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.91#increasing detachment from the conditions under which, climatically and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.92#hereditarily, united races originate, their increasing independence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.93#every definite milieu, that for centuries would fain inscribe itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.94#with equal demands on soul and body,--that is to say, the slow emergence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.95#of an essentially SUPER-NATIONAL and nomadic species of man, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.96#possesses, physiologically speaking, a maximum of the art and power
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.97#of adaptation as his typical distinction. This process of the EVOLVING
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.98#EUROPEAN, which can be retarded in its TEMPO by great relapses, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.99#will perhaps just gain and grow thereby in vehemence and depth--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.100#still-raging storm and stress of "national sentiment" pertains to it,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.101#and also the anarchism which is appearing at present--this process
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.102#will probably arrive at results on which its naive propagators and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.103#panegyrists, the apostles of "modern ideas," would least care to reckon.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.104#The same new conditions under which on an average a levelling and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.105#mediocrising of man will take place--a useful, industrious, variously
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.106#serviceable, and clever gregarious man--are in the highest degree
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.107#suitable to give rise to exceptional men of the most dangerous and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.108#attractive qualities. For, while the capacity for adaptation, which is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.109#every day trying changing conditions, and begins a new work with every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.110#generation, almost with every decade, makes the POWERFULNESS of the type
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.111#impossible; while the collective impression of such future Europeans
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.112#will probably be that of numerous, talkative, weak-willed, and very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.113#handy workmen who REQUIRE a master, a commander, as they require their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.114#daily bread; while, therefore, the democratising of Europe will tend to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.115#the production of a type prepared for SLAVERY in the most subtle
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.116#sense of the term: the STRONG man will necessarily in individual and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.117#exceptional cases, become stronger and richer than he has perhaps ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.118#been before--owing to the unprejudicedness of his schooling, owing to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.119#the immense variety of practice, art, and disguise. I meant to say
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.120#that the democratising of Europe is at the same time an involuntary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.121#arrangement for the rearing of TYRANTS--taking the word in all its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.122#meanings, even in its most spiritual sense.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.123#243. I hear with pleasure that our sun is moving rapidly towards the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.124#constellation Hercules: and I hope that the men on this earth will do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.125#like the sun. And we foremost, we good Europeans!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.126#244. There was a time when it was customary to call Germans "deep"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.127#by way of distinction; but now that the most successful type of new
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.128#Germanism is covetous of quite other honours, and perhaps misses
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.129#"smartness" in all that has depth, it is almost opportune and patriotic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.130#to doubt whether we did not formerly deceive ourselves with that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.131#commendation: in short, whether German depth is not at bottom something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.132#different and worse--and something from which, thank God, we are on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.133#point of successfully ridding ourselves. Let us try, then, to relearn
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.134#with regard to German depth; the only thing necessary for the purpose is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.135#a little vivisection of the German soul.--The German soul is above all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.136#manifold, varied in its source, aggregated and super-imposed, rather
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.137#than actually built: this is owing to its origin. A German who would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.138#embolden himself to assert: "Two souls, alas, dwell in my breast," would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.139#make a bad guess at the truth, or, more correctly, he would come far
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.140#short of the truth about the number of souls. As a people made up of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.141#the most extraordinary mixing and mingling of races, perhaps even with a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.142#preponderance of the pre-Aryan element as the "people of the centre" in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.143#every sense of the term, the Germans are more intangible, more ample,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.144#more contradictory, more unknown, more incalculable, more surprising,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.145#and even more terrifying than other peoples are to themselves:--they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.146#escape DEFINITION, and are thereby alone the despair of the French. It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.147#IS characteristic of the Germans that the question: "What is German?"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.148#never dies out among them. Kotzebue certainly knew his Germans well
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.149#enough: "We are known," they cried jubilantly to him--but Sand also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.150#thought he knew them. Jean Paul knew what he was doing when he declared
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.151#himself incensed at Fichte's lying but patriotic flatteries and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.152#exaggerations,--but it is probable that Goethe thought differently about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.153#Germans from Jean Paul, even though he acknowledged him to be right with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.154#regard to Fichte. It is a question what Goethe really thought about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.155#Germans?--But about many things around him he never spoke explicitly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.156#and all his life he knew how to keep an astute silence--probably he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.157#had good reason for it. It is certain that it was not the "Wars of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.158#Independence" that made him look up more joyfully, any more than it was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.159#the French Revolution,--the event on account of which he RECONSTRUCTED
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.160#his "Faust," and indeed the whole problem of "man," was the appearance
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.161#of Napoleon. There are words of Goethe in which he condemns with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.162#impatient severity, as from a foreign land, that which Germans take a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.163#pride in, he once defined the famous German turn of mind as "Indulgence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.164#towards its own and others' weaknesses." Was he wrong? it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.165#characteristic of Germans that one is seldom entirely wrong about them.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.166#The German soul has passages and galleries in it, there are caves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.167#hiding-places, and dungeons therein, its disorder has much of the charm
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.168#of the mysterious, the German is well acquainted with the bypaths to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.169#chaos. And as everything loves its symbol, so the German loves the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.170#clouds and all that is obscure, evolving, crepuscular, damp, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.171#shrouded, it seems to him that everything uncertain, undeveloped,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.172#self-displacing, and growing is "deep". The German himself does not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.173#EXIST, he is BECOMING, he is "developing himself". "Development" is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.174#therefore the essentially German discovery and hit in the great domain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.175#of philosophical formulas,--a ruling idea, which, together with German
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.176#beer and German music, is labouring to Germanise all Europe. Foreigners
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.177#are astonished and attracted by the riddles which the conflicting nature
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.178#at the basis of the German soul propounds to them (riddles which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.179#Hegel systematised and Richard Wagner has in the end set to music).
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.180#"Good-natured and spiteful"--such a juxtaposition, preposterous in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.181#case of every other people, is unfortunately only too often justified
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.182#in Germany one has only to live for a while among Swabians to know this!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.183#The clumsiness of the German scholar and his social distastefulness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.184#agree alarmingly well with his physical rope-dancing and nimble
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.185#boldness, of which all the Gods have learnt to be afraid. If any one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.186#wishes to see the "German soul" demonstrated ad oculos, let him
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.187#only look at German taste, at German arts and manners what boorish
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.188#indifference to "taste"! How the noblest and the commonest stand there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.189#in juxtaposition! How disorderly and how rich is the whole constitution
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.190#of this soul! The German DRAGS at his soul, he drags at everything he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.191#experiences. He digests his events badly; he never gets "done"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.192#with them; and German depth is often only a difficult, hesitating
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.193#"digestion." And just as all chronic invalids, all dyspeptics like what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.194#is convenient, so the German loves "frankness" and "honesty"; it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.195#so CONVENIENT to be frank and honest!--This confidingness, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.196#complaisance, this showing-the-cards of German HONESTY, is probably the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.197#most dangerous and most successful disguise which the German is up to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.198#nowadays: it is his proper Mephistophelean art; with this he can "still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.199#achieve much"! The German lets himself go, and thereby gazes with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.200#faithful, blue, empty German eyes--and other countries immediately
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.201#confound him with his dressing-gown!--I meant to say that, let "German
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.202#depth" be what it will--among ourselves alone we perhaps take the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.203#liberty to laugh at it--we shall do well to continue henceforth to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.204#honour its appearance and good name, and not barter away too cheaply our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.205#old reputation as a people of depth for Prussian "smartness," and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.206#Berlin wit and sand. It is wise for a people to pose, and LET itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.207#be regarded, as profound, clumsy, good-natured, honest, and foolish: it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.208#might even be--profound to do so! Finally, we should do honour to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.209#our name--we are not called the "TIUSCHE VOLK" (deceptive people) for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.210#nothing....
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.211#245. The "good old" time is past, it sang itself out in Mozart--how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.212#happy are WE that his ROCOCO still speaks to us, that his "good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.213#company," his tender enthusiasm, his childish delight in the Chinese and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.214#its flourishes, his courtesy of heart, his longing for the elegant, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.215#amorous, the tripping, the tearful, and his belief in the South, can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.216#still appeal to SOMETHING LEFT in us! Ah, some time or other it will be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.217#over with it!--but who can doubt that it will be over still sooner with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.218#the intelligence and taste for Beethoven! For he was only the last echo
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.219#of a break and transition in style, and NOT, like Mozart, the last echo
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.220#of a great European taste which had existed for centuries. Beethoven
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.221#is the intermediate event between an old mellow soul that is constantly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.222#breaking down, and a future over-young soul that is always COMING;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.223#there is spread over his music the twilight of eternal loss and eternal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.224#extravagant hope,--the same light in which Europe was bathed when it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.225#dreamed with Rousseau, when it danced round the Tree of Liberty of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.226#Revolution, and finally almost fell down in adoration before Napoleon.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.227#But how rapidly does THIS very sentiment now pale, how difficult
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.228#nowadays is even the APPREHENSION of this sentiment, how strangely does
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.229#the language of Rousseau, Schiller, Shelley, and Byron sound to our ear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.230#in whom COLLECTIVELY the same fate of Europe was able to SPEAK, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.231#knew how to SING in Beethoven!--Whatever German music came afterwards,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.232#belongs to Romanticism, that is to say, to a movement which,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.233#historically considered, was still shorter, more fleeting, and more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.234#superficial than that great interlude, the transition of Europe from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.235#Rousseau to Napoleon, and to the rise of democracy. Weber--but what do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.236#WE care nowadays for "Freischutz" and "Oberon"! Or Marschner's "Hans
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.237#Heiling" and "Vampyre"! Or even Wagner's "Tannhauser"! That is extinct,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.238#although not yet forgotten music. This whole music of Romanticism,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.239#besides, was not noble enough, was not musical enough, to maintain its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.240#position anywhere but in the theatre and before the masses; from the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.241#beginning it was second-rate music, which was little thought of by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.242#genuine musicians. It was different with Felix Mendelssohn, that halcyon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.243#master, who, on account of his lighter, purer, happier soul, quickly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.244#acquired admiration, and was equally quickly forgotten: as the beautiful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.245#EPISODE of German music. But with regard to Robert Schumann, who took
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.246#things seriously, and has been taken seriously from the first--he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.247#was the last that founded a school,--do we not now regard it as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.248#satisfaction, a relief, a deliverance, that this very Romanticism
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.249#of Schumann's has been surmounted? Schumann, fleeing into the "Saxon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.250#Switzerland" of his soul, with a half Werther-like, half Jean-Paul-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.251#nature (assuredly not like Beethoven! assuredly not like Byron!)--his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.252#MANFRED music is a mistake and a misunderstanding to the extent of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.253#injustice; Schumann, with his taste, which was fundamentally a PETTY
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.254#taste (that is to say, a dangerous propensity--doubly dangerous among
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.255#Germans--for quiet lyricism and intoxication of the feelings), going
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.256#constantly apart, timidly withdrawing and retiring, a noble weakling who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.257#revelled in nothing but anonymous joy and sorrow, from the beginning
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.258#a sort of girl and NOLI ME TANGERE--this Schumann was already merely a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.259#GERMAN event in music, and no longer a European event, as Beethoven had
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.260#been, as in a still greater degree Mozart had been; with Schumann German
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.261#music was threatened with its greatest danger, that of LOSING THE VOICE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.262#FOR THE SOUL OF EUROPE and sinking into a merely national affair.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.263#246. What a torture are books written in German to a reader who has a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.264#THIRD ear! How indignantly he stands beside the slowly turning swamp
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.265#of sounds without tune and rhythms without dance, which Germans call
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.266#a "book"! And even the German who READS books! How lazily, how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.267#reluctantly, how badly he reads! How many Germans know, and consider it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.268#obligatory to know, that there is ART in every good sentence--art which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.269#must be divined, if the sentence is to be understood! If there is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.270#misunderstanding about its TEMPO, for instance, the sentence itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.271#is misunderstood! That one must not be doubtful about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.272#rhythm-determining syllables, that one should feel the breaking of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.273#too-rigid symmetry as intentional and as a charm, that one should lend a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.274#fine and patient ear to every STACCATO and every RUBATO, that one should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.275#divine the sense in the sequence of the vowels and diphthongs, and how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.276#delicately and richly they can be tinted and retinted in the order of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.277#their arrangement--who among book-reading Germans is complaisant enough
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.278#to recognize such duties and requirements, and to listen to so much art
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.279#and intention in language? After all, one just "has no ear for it";
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.280#and so the most marked contrasts of style are not heard, and the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.281#delicate artistry is as it were SQUANDERED on the deaf.--These were my
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.282#thoughts when I noticed how clumsily and unintuitively two masters in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.283#the art of prose-writing have been confounded: one, whose words drop
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.284#down hesitatingly and coldly, as from the roof of a damp cave--he counts
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.285#on their dull sound and echo; and another who manipulates his language
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.286#like a flexible sword, and from his arm down into his toes feels the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.287#dangerous bliss of the quivering, over-sharp blade, which wishes to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.288#bite, hiss, and cut.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.289#247. How little the German style has to do with harmony and with the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.290#ear, is shown by the fact that precisely our good musicians themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.291#write badly. The German does not read aloud, he does not read for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.292#ear, but only with his eyes; he has put his ears away in the drawer for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.293#the time. In antiquity when a man read--which was seldom enough--he read
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.294#something to himself, and in a loud voice; they were surprised when
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.295#any one read silently, and sought secretly the reason of it. In a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.296#loud voice: that is to say, with all the swellings, inflections, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.297#variations of key and changes of TEMPO, in which the ancient PUBLIC
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.298#world took delight. The laws of the written style were then the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.299#as those of the spoken style; and these laws depended partly on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.300#surprising development and refined requirements of the ear and larynx;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.301#partly on the strength, endurance, and power of the ancient lungs. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.302#the ancient sense, a period is above all a physiological whole, inasmuch
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.303#as it is comprised in one breath. Such periods as occur in Demosthenes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.304#and Cicero, swelling twice and sinking twice, and all in one breath,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.305#were pleasures to the men of ANTIQUITY, who knew by their own schooling
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.306#how to appreciate the virtue therein, the rareness and the difficulty
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.307#in the deliverance of such a period;--WE have really no right to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.308#BIG period, we modern men, who are short of breath in every sense! Those
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.309#ancients, indeed, were all of them dilettanti in speaking, consequently
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.310#connoisseurs, consequently critics--they thus brought their orators to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.311#the highest pitch; in the same manner as in the last century, when all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.312#Italian ladies and gentlemen knew how to sing, the virtuosoship of song
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.313#(and with it also the art of melody) reached its elevation. In Germany,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.314#however (until quite recently when a kind of platform eloquence began
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.315#shyly and awkwardly enough to flutter its young wings), there was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.316#properly speaking only one kind of public and APPROXIMATELY artistical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.317#discourse--that delivered from the pulpit. The preacher was the only one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.318#in Germany who knew the weight of a syllable or a word, in what manner a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.319#sentence strikes, springs, rushes, flows, and comes to a close; he alone
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.320#had a conscience in his ears, often enough a bad conscience: for reasons
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.321#are not lacking why proficiency in oratory should be especially seldom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.322#attained by a German, or almost always too late. The masterpiece of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.323#German prose is therefore with good reason the masterpiece of its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.324#greatest preacher: the BIBLE has hitherto been the best German
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.325#book. Compared with Luther's Bible, almost everything else is merely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.326#"literature"--something which has not grown in Germany, and therefore
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.327#has not taken and does not take root in German hearts, as the Bible has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.328#done.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.329#248. There are two kinds of geniuses: one which above all engenders and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.330#seeks to engender, and another which willingly lets itself be fructified
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.331#and brings forth. And similarly, among the gifted nations, there are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.332#those on whom the woman's problem of pregnancy has devolved, and the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.333#secret task of forming, maturing, and perfecting--the Greeks, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.334#instance, were a nation of this kind, and so are the French; and others
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.335#which have to fructify and become the cause of new modes of life--like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.336#the Jews, the Romans, and, in all modesty be it asked: like the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.337#Germans?--nations tortured and enraptured by unknown fevers and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.338#irresistibly forced out of themselves, amorous and longing for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.339#foreign races (for such as "let themselves be fructified"), and withal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.340#imperious, like everything conscious of being full of generative force,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.341#and consequently empowered "by the grace of God." These two kinds of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.342#geniuses seek each other like man and woman; but they also misunderstand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.343#each other--like man and woman.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.344#249. Every nation has its own "Tartuffery," and calls that its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.345#virtue.--One does not know--cannot know, the best that is in one.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.346#250. What Europe owes to the Jews?--Many things, good and bad, and above
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.347#all one thing of the nature both of the best and the worst: the grand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.348#style in morality, the fearfulness and majesty of infinite demands, of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.349#infinite significations, the whole Romanticism and sublimity of moral
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.350#questionableness--and consequently just the most attractive, ensnaring,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.351#and exquisite element in those iridescences and allurements to life,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.352#in the aftersheen of which the sky of our European culture, its evening
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.353#sky, now glows--perhaps glows out. For this, we artists among the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.354#spectators and philosophers, are--grateful to the Jews.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.355#251. It must be taken into the bargain, if various clouds and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.356#disturbances--in short, slight attacks of stupidity--pass over the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.357#spirit of a people that suffers and WANTS to suffer from national
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.358#nervous fever and political ambition: for instance, among present-day
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.359#Germans there is alternately the anti-French folly, the anti-Semitic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.360#folly, the anti-Polish folly, the Christian-romantic folly, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.361#Wagnerian folly, the Teutonic folly, the Prussian folly (just look at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.362#those poor historians, the Sybels and Treitschkes, and their closely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.363#bandaged heads), and whatever else these little obscurations of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.364#German spirit and conscience may be called. May it be forgiven me that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.365#I, too, when on a short daring sojourn on very infected ground, did not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.366#remain wholly exempt from the disease, but like every one else, began
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.367#to entertain thoughts about matters which did not concern me--the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.368#symptom of political infection. About the Jews, for instance, listen
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.369#to the following:--I have never yet met a German who was favourably
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.370#inclined to the Jews; and however decided the repudiation of actual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.371#anti-Semitism may be on the part of all prudent and political men, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.372#prudence and policy is not perhaps directed against the nature of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.373#sentiment itself, but only against its dangerous excess, and especially
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.374#against the distasteful and infamous expression of this excess of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.375#sentiment;--on this point we must not deceive ourselves. That Germany
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.376#has amply SUFFICIENT Jews, that the German stomach, the German blood,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.377#has difficulty (and will long have difficulty) in disposing only of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.378#quantity of "Jew"--as the Italian, the Frenchman, and the Englishman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.379#have done by means of a stronger digestion:--that is the unmistakable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.380#declaration and language of a general instinct, to which one must listen
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.381#and according to which one must act. "Let no more Jews come in! And shut
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.382#the doors, especially towards the East (also towards Austria)!"--thus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.383#commands the instinct of a people whose nature is still feeble and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.384#uncertain, so that it could be easily wiped out, easily extinguished, by
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.385#a stronger race. The Jews, however, are beyond all doubt the strongest,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.386#toughest, and purest race at present living in Europe, they know how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.387#to succeed even under the worst conditions (in fact better than under
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.388#favourable ones), by means of virtues of some sort, which one would like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.389#nowadays to label as vices--owing above all to a resolute faith which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.390#does not need to be ashamed before "modern ideas", they alter only,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.391#WHEN they do alter, in the same way that the Russian Empire makes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.392#its conquest--as an empire that has plenty of time and is not of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.393#yesterday--namely, according to the principle, "as slowly as possible"!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.394#A thinker who has the future of Europe at heart, will, in all his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.395#perspectives concerning the future, calculate upon the Jews, as he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.396#will calculate upon the Russians, as above all the surest and likeliest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.397#factors in the great play and battle of forces. That which is at present
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.398#called a "nation" in Europe, and is really rather a RES FACTA than NATA
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.399#(indeed, sometimes confusingly similar to a RES FICTA ET PICTA), is in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.400#every case something evolving, young, easily displaced, and not yet
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.401#a race, much less such a race AERE PERENNUS, as the Jews are such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.402#"nations" should most carefully avoid all hot-headed rivalry and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.403#hostility! It is certain that the Jews, if they desired--or if they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.404#were driven to it, as the anti-Semites seem to wish--COULD now have the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.405#ascendancy, nay, literally the supremacy, over Europe, that they are NOT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.406#working and planning for that end is equally certain. Meanwhile, they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.407#rather wish and desire, even somewhat importunely, to be insorbed and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.408#absorbed by Europe, they long to be finally settled, authorized, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.409#respected somewhere, and wish to put an end to the nomadic life, to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.410#"wandering Jew",--and one should certainly take account of this impulse
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.411#and tendency, and MAKE ADVANCES to it (it possibly betokens a mitigation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.412#of the Jewish instincts) for which purpose it would perhaps be useful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.413#and fair to banish the anti-Semitic bawlers out of the country. One
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.414#should make advances with all prudence, and with selection, pretty much
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.415#as the English nobility do It stands to reason that the more powerful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.416#and strongly marked types of new Germanism could enter into relation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.417#with the Jews with the least hesitation, for instance, the nobleman
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.418#officer from the Prussian border it would be interesting in many ways
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.419#to see whether the genius for money and patience (and especially some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.420#intellect and intellectuality--sadly lacking in the place referred to)
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.421#could not in addition be annexed and trained to the hereditary art of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.422#commanding and obeying--for both of which the country in question has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.423#now a classic reputation But here it is expedient to break off my festal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.424#discourse and my sprightly Teutonomania for I have already reached my
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.425#SERIOUS TOPIC, the "European problem," as I understand it, the rearing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.426#of a new ruling caste for Europe.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.427#252. They are not a philosophical race--the English: Bacon represents an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.428#ATTACK on the philosophical spirit generally, Hobbes, Hume, and Locke,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.429#an abasement, and a depreciation of the idea of a "philosopher" for more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.430#than a century. It was AGAINST Hume that Kant uprose and raised himself;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.431#it was Locke of whom Schelling RIGHTLY said, "JE MEPRISE LOCKE"; in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.432#struggle against the English mechanical stultification of the world,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.433#Hegel and Schopenhauer (along with Goethe) were of one accord; the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.434#two hostile brother-geniuses in philosophy, who pushed in different
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.435#directions towards the opposite poles of German thought, and thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.436#wronged each other as only brothers will do.--What is lacking in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.437#England, and has always been lacking, that half-actor and rhetorician
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.438#knew well enough, the absurd muddle-head, Carlyle, who sought to conceal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.439#under passionate grimaces what he knew about himself: namely, what was
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.440#LACKING in Carlyle--real POWER of intellect, real DEPTH of intellectual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.441#perception, in short, philosophy. It is characteristic of such an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.442#unphilosophical race to hold on firmly to Christianity--they NEED its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.443#discipline for "moralizing" and humanizing. The Englishman, more gloomy,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.444#sensual, headstrong, and brutal than the German--is for that very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.445#reason, as the baser of the two, also the most pious: he has all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.446#MORE NEED of Christianity. To finer nostrils, this English Christianity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.447#itself has still a characteristic English taint of spleen and alcoholic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.448#excess, for which, owing to good reasons, it is used as an antidote--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.449#finer poison to neutralize the coarser: a finer form of poisoning is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.450#in fact a step in advance with coarse-mannered people, a step towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.451#spiritualization. The English coarseness and rustic demureness is still
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.452#most satisfactorily disguised by Christian pantomime, and by praying
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.453#and psalm-singing (or, more correctly, it is thereby explained and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.454#differently expressed); and for the herd of drunkards and rakes who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.455#formerly learned moral grunting under the influence of Methodism (and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.456#more recently as the "Salvation Army"), a penitential fit may really be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.457#the relatively highest manifestation of "humanity" to which they can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.458#be elevated: so much may reasonably be admitted. That, however, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.459#offends even in the humanest Englishman is his lack of music, to speak
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.460#figuratively (and also literally): he has neither rhythm nor dance in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.461#the movements of his soul and body; indeed, not even the desire for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.462#rhythm and dance, for "music." Listen to him speaking; look at the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.463#beautiful Englishwoman WALKING--in no country on earth are there more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.464#beautiful doves and swans; finally, listen to them singing! But I ask
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.465#too much...
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.466#253. There are truths which are best recognized by mediocre minds,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.467#because they are best adapted for them, there are truths which only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.468#possess charms and seductive power for mediocre spirits:--one is pushed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.469#to this probably unpleasant conclusion, now that the influence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.470#respectable but mediocre Englishmen--I may mention Darwin, John
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.471#Stuart Mill, and Herbert Spencer--begins to gain the ascendancy in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.472#middle-class region of European taste. Indeed, who could doubt that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.473#is a useful thing for SUCH minds to have the ascendancy for a time? It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.474#would be an error to consider the highly developed and independently
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.475#soaring minds as specially qualified for determining and collecting many
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.476#little common facts, and deducing conclusions from them; as exceptions,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.477#they are rather from the first in no very favourable position towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.478#those who are "the rules." After all, they have more to do than merely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.479#to perceive:--in effect, they have to BE something new, they have to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.480#SIGNIFY something new, they have to REPRESENT new values! The gulf
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.481#between knowledge and capacity is perhaps greater, and also more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.482#mysterious, than one thinks: the capable man in the grand style, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.483#creator, will possibly have to be an ignorant person;--while on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.484#other hand, for scientific discoveries like those of Darwin, a certain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.485#narrowness, aridity, and industrious carefulness (in short, something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.486#English) may not be unfavourable for arriving at them.--Finally, let
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.487#it not be forgotten that the English, with their profound mediocrity,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.488#brought about once before a general depression of European intelligence.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.489#What is called "modern ideas," or "the ideas of the eighteenth century,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.490#or "French ideas"--that, consequently, against which the GERMAN mind
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.491#rose up with profound disgust--is of English origin, there is no doubt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.492#about it. The French were only the apes and actors of these ideas, their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.493#best soldiers, and likewise, alas! their first and profoundest VICTIMS;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.494#for owing to the diabolical Anglomania of "modern ideas," the AME
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.495#FRANCAIS has in the end become so thin and emaciated, that at present
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.496#one recalls its sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, its profound,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.497#passionate strength, its inventive excellency, almost with disbelief.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.498#One must, however, maintain this verdict of historical justice in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.499#a determined manner, and defend it against present prejudices and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.500#appearances: the European NOBLESSE--of sentiment, taste, and manners,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.501#taking the word in every high sense--is the work and invention of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.502#FRANCE; the European ignobleness, the plebeianism of modern ideas--is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.503#ENGLAND'S work and invention.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.504#254. Even at present France is still the seat of the most intellectual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.505#and refined culture of Europe, it is still the high school of taste; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.506#one must know how to find this "France of taste." He who belongs to it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.507#keeps himself well concealed:--they may be a small number in whom it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.508#lives and is embodied, besides perhaps being men who do not stand upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.509#the strongest legs, in part fatalists, hypochondriacs, invalids, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.510#part persons over-indulged, over-refined, such as have the AMBITION to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.511#conceal themselves.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.512#They have all something in common: they keep their ears closed in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.513#presence of the delirious folly and noisy spouting of the democratic
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.514#BOURGEOIS. In fact, a besotted and brutalized France at present sprawls
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.515#in the foreground--it recently celebrated a veritable orgy of bad taste,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.516#and at the same time of self-admiration, at the funeral of Victor Hugo.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.517#There is also something else common to them: a predilection to resist
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.518#intellectual Germanizing--and a still greater inability to do so!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.519#In this France of intellect, which is also a France of pessimism,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.520#Schopenhauer has perhaps become more at home, and more indigenous than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.521#he has ever been in Germany; not to speak of Heinrich Heine, who has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.522#long ago been re-incarnated in the more refined and fastidious lyrists
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.523#of Paris; or of Hegel, who at present, in the form of Taine--the FIRST
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.524#of living historians--exercises an almost tyrannical influence. As
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.525#regards Richard Wagner, however, the more French music learns to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.526#adapt itself to the actual needs of the AME MODERNE, the more will it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.527#"Wagnerite"; one can safely predict that beforehand,--it is already
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.528#taking place sufficiently! There are, however, three things which the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.529#French can still boast of with pride as their heritage and possession,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.530#and as indelible tokens of their ancient intellectual superiority
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.531#in Europe, in spite of all voluntary or involuntary Germanizing and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.532#vulgarizing of taste. FIRSTLY, the capacity for artistic emotion, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.533#devotion to "form," for which the expression, L'ART POUR L'ART, along
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.534#with numerous others, has been invented:--such capacity has not been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.535#lacking in France for three centuries; and owing to its reverence for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.536#the "small number," it has again and again made a sort of chamber
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.537#music of literature possible, which is sought for in vain elsewhere
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.538#in Europe.--The SECOND thing whereby the French can lay claim to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.539#a superiority over Europe is their ancient, many-sided, MORALISTIC
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.540#culture, owing to which one finds on an average, even in the petty
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.541#ROMANCIERS of the newspapers and chance BOULEVARDIERS DE PARIS, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.542#psychological sensitiveness and curiosity, of which, for example, one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.543#has no conception (to say nothing of the thing itself!) in Germany.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.544#The Germans lack a couple of centuries of the moralistic work requisite
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.545#thereto, which, as we have said, France has not grudged: those who call
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.546#the Germans "naive" on that account give them commendation for a defect.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.547#(As the opposite of the German inexperience and innocence IN VOLUPTATE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.548#PSYCHOLOGICA, which is not too remotely associated with the tediousness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.549#of German intercourse,--and as the most successful expression of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.550#genuine French curiosity and inventive talent in this domain of delicate
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.551#thrills, Henri Beyle may be noted; that remarkable anticipatory and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.552#forerunning man, who, with a Napoleonic TEMPO, traversed HIS Europe,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.553#in fact, several centuries of the European soul, as a surveyor and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.554#discoverer thereof:--it has required two generations to OVERTAKE him
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.555#one way or other, to divine long afterwards some of the riddles
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.556#that perplexed and enraptured him--this strange Epicurean and man of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.557#interrogation, the last great psychologist of France).--There is yet
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.558#a THIRD claim to superiority: in the French character there is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.559#successful half-way synthesis of the North and South, which makes them
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.560#comprehend many things, and enjoins upon them other things, which an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.561#Englishman can never comprehend. Their temperament, turned alternately
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.562#to and from the South, in which from time to time the Provencal and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.563#Ligurian blood froths over, preserves them from the dreadful, northern
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.564#grey-in-grey, from sunless conceptual-spectrism and from poverty of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.565#blood--our GERMAN infirmity of taste, for the excessive prevalence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.566#of which at the present moment, blood and iron, that is to say "high
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.567#politics," has with great resolution been prescribed (according to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.568#a dangerous healing art, which bids me wait and wait, but not yet
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.569#hope).--There is also still in France a pre-understanding and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.570#ready welcome for those rarer and rarely gratified men, who are too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.571#comprehensive to find satisfaction in any kind of fatherlandism, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.572#know how to love the South when in the North and the North when in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.573#South--the born Midlanders, the "good Europeans." For them BIZET
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.574#has made music, this latest genius, who has seen a new beauty and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.575#seduction,--who has discovered a piece of the SOUTH IN MUSIC.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.576#255. I hold that many precautions should be taken against German music.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.577#Suppose a person loves the South as I love it--as a great school
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.578#of recovery for the most spiritual and the most sensuous ills, as a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.579#boundless solar profusion and effulgence which o'erspreads a sovereign
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.580#existence believing in itself--well, such a person will learn to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.581#somewhat on his guard against German music, because, in injuring his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.582#taste anew, it will also injure his health anew. Such a Southerner, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.583#Southerner not by origin but by BELIEF, if he should dream of the future
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.584#of music, must also dream of it being freed from the influence of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.585#North; and must have in his ears the prelude to a deeper, mightier, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.586#perhaps more perverse and mysterious music, a super-German music, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.587#does not fade, pale, and die away, as all German music does, at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.588#sight of the blue, wanton sea and the Mediterranean clearness of sky--a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.589#super-European music, which holds its own even in presence of the brown
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.590#sunsets of the desert, whose soul is akin to the palm-tree, and can be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.591#at home and can roam with big, beautiful, lonely beasts of prey... I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.592#could imagine a music of which the rarest charm would be that it knew
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.593#nothing more of good and evil; only that here and there perhaps some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.594#sailor's home-sickness, some golden shadows and tender weaknesses might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.595#sweep lightly over it; an art which, from the far distance, would see
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.596#the colours of a sinking and almost incomprehensible MORAL world fleeing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.597#towards it, and would be hospitable enough and profound enough to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.598#receive such belated fugitives.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.599#256. Owing to the morbid estrangement which the nationality-craze has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.600#induced and still induces among the nations of Europe, owing also to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.601#short-sighted and hasty-handed politicians, who with the help of this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.602#craze, are at present in power, and do not suspect to what extent the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.603#disintegrating policy they pursue must necessarily be only an interlude
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.604#policy--owing to all this and much else that is altogether unmentionable
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.605#at present, the most unmistakable signs that EUROPE WISHES TO BE ONE,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.606#are now overlooked, or arbitrarily and falsely misinterpreted. With all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.607#the more profound and large-minded men of this century, the real general
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.608#tendency of the mysterious labour of their souls was to prepare the way
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.609#for that new SYNTHESIS, and tentatively to anticipate the European of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.610#the future; only in their simulations, or in their weaker moments, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.611#old age perhaps, did they belong to the "fatherlands"--they only rested
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.612#from themselves when they became "patriots." I think of such men as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.613#Napoleon, Goethe, Beethoven, Stendhal, Heinrich Heine, Schopenhauer: it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.614#must not be taken amiss if I also count Richard Wagner among them, about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.615#whom one must not let oneself be deceived by his own misunderstandings
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.616#(geniuses like him have seldom the right to understand themselves),
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.617#still less, of course, by the unseemly noise with which he is now
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.618#resisted and opposed in France: the fact remains, nevertheless, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.619#Richard Wagner and the LATER FRENCH ROMANTICISM of the forties, are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.620#most closely and intimately related to one another. They are akin,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.621#fundamentally akin, in all the heights and depths of their requirements;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.622#it is Europe, the ONE Europe, whose soul presses urgently and longingly,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.623#outwards and upwards, in their multifarious and boisterous art--whither?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.624#into a new light? towards a new sun? But who would attempt to express
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.625#accurately what all these masters of new modes of speech could not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.626#express distinctly? It is certain that the same storm and stress
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.627#tormented them, that they SOUGHT in the same manner, these last great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.628#seekers! All of them steeped in literature to their eyes and ears--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.629#first artists of universal literary culture--for the most part even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.630#themselves writers, poets, intermediaries and blenders of the arts and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.631#the senses (Wagner, as musician is reckoned among painters, as poet
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.632#among musicians, as artist generally among actors); all of them fanatics
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.633#for EXPRESSION "at any cost"--I specially mention Delacroix, the nearest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.634#related to Wagner; all of them great discoverers in the realm of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.635#sublime, also of the loathsome and dreadful, still greater discoverers
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.636#in effect, in display, in the art of the show-shop; all of them talented
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.637#far beyond their genius, out and out VIRTUOSI, with mysterious accesses
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.638#to all that seduces, allures, constrains, and upsets; born enemies of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.639#logic and of the straight line, hankering after the strange, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.640#exotic, the monstrous, the crooked, and the self-contradictory; as men,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.641#Tantaluses of the will, plebeian parvenus, who knew themselves to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.642#incapable of a noble TEMPO or of a LENTO in life and action--think
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.643#of Balzac, for instance,--unrestrained workers, almost destroying
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.644#themselves by work; antinomians and rebels in manners, ambitious and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.645#insatiable, without equilibrium and enjoyment; all of them finally
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.646#shattering and sinking down at the Christian cross (and with right
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.647#and reason, for who of them would have been sufficiently profound and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.648#sufficiently original for an ANTI-CHRISTIAN philosophy?);--on the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.649#whole, a boldly daring, splendidly overbearing, high-flying, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.650#aloft-up-dragging class of higher men, who had first to teach their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.651#century--and it is the century of the MASSES--the conception "higher
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.652#man."... Let the German friends of Richard Wagner advise together as to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.653#whether there is anything purely German in the Wagnerian art, or whether
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.654#its distinction does not consist precisely in coming from SUPER-GERMAN
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.655#sources and impulses: in which connection it may not be underrated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.656#how indispensable Paris was to the development of his type, which the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.657#strength of his instincts made him long to visit at the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.658#decisive time--and how the whole style of his proceedings, of his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.659#self-apostolate, could only perfect itself in sight of the French
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.660#socialistic original. On a more subtle comparison it will perhaps be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.661#found, to the honour of Richard Wagner's German nature, that he has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.662#acted in everything with more strength, daring, severity, and elevation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.663#than a nineteenth-century Frenchman could have done--owing to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.664#circumstance that we Germans are as yet nearer to barbarism than the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.665#French;--perhaps even the most remarkable creation of Richard Wagner is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.666#not only at present, but for ever inaccessible, incomprehensible, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.667#inimitable to the whole latter-day Latin race: the figure of Siegfried,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.668#that VERY FREE man, who is probably far too free, too hard, too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.669#cheerful, too healthy, too ANTI-CATHOLIC for the taste of old and mellow
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.670#civilized nations. He may even have been a sin against Romanticism, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.671#anti-Latin Siegfried: well, Wagner atoned amply for this sin in his old
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.672#sad days, when--anticipating a taste which has meanwhile passed into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.673#politics--he began, with the religious vehemence peculiar to him, to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.674#preach, at least, THE WAY TO ROME, if not to walk therein.--That
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.675#these last words may not be misunderstood, I will call to my aid a few
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.676#powerful rhymes, which will even betray to less delicate ears what I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.677#mean--what I mean COUNTER TO the "last Wagner" and his Parsifal music:--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.678#--Is this our mode?--From German heart came this vexed ululating? From
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.679#German body, this self-lacerating? Is ours this priestly hand-dilation,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.680#This incense-fuming exaltation? Is ours this faltering, falling,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.681#shambling, This quite uncertain ding-dong-dangling? This sly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.682#nun-ogling, Ave-hour-bell ringing, This wholly false enraptured
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.683#heaven-o'erspringing?--Is this our mode?--Think well!--ye still wait for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:8.684#admission--For what ye hear is ROME--ROME'S FAITH BY INTUITION!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1#CHAPTER IX. WHAT IS NOBLE?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.2#257. EVERY elevation of the type "man," has hitherto been the work of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.3#aristocratic society and so it will always be--a society believing in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.4#a long scale of gradations of rank and differences of worth among human
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.5#beings, and requiring slavery in some form or other. Without the PATHOS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.6#OF DISTANCE, such as grows out of the incarnated difference of classes,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.7#out of the constant out-looking and down-looking of the ruling caste on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.8#subordinates and instruments, and out of their equally constant
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.9#practice of obeying and commanding, of keeping down and keeping at a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.10#distance--that other more mysterious pathos could never have arisen, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.11#longing for an ever new widening of distance within the soul itself,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.12#the formation of ever higher, rarer, further, more extended, more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.13#comprehensive states, in short, just the elevation of the type "man,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.14#the continued "self-surmounting of man," to use a moral formula in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.15#a supermoral sense. To be sure, one must not resign oneself to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.16#any humanitarian illusions about the history of the origin of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.17#aristocratic society (that is to say, of the preliminary condition for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.18#the elevation of the type "man"): the truth is hard. Let us acknowledge
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.19#unprejudicedly how every higher civilization hitherto has ORIGINATED!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.20#Men with a still natural nature, barbarians in every terrible sense of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.21#the word, men of prey, still in possession of unbroken strength of will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.22#and desire for power, threw themselves upon weaker, more moral, more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.23#peaceful races (perhaps trading or cattle-rearing communities), or upon
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.24#old mellow civilizations in which the final vital force was flickering
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.25#out in brilliant fireworks of wit and depravity. At the commencement,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.26#the noble caste was always the barbarian caste: their superiority did
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.27#not consist first of all in their physical, but in their psychical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.28#power--they were more COMPLETE men (which at every point also implies
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.29#the same as "more complete beasts").
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.30#258. Corruption--as the indication that anarchy threatens to break out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.31#among the instincts, and that the foundation of the emotions, called
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.32#"life," is convulsed--is something radically different according to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.33#the organization in which it manifests itself. When, for instance, an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.34#aristocracy like that of France at the beginning of the Revolution,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.35#flung away its privileges with sublime disgust and sacrificed itself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.36#to an excess of its moral sentiments, it was corruption:--it was really
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.37#only the closing act of the corruption which had existed for centuries,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.38#by virtue of which that aristocracy had abdicated step by step its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.39#lordly prerogatives and lowered itself to a FUNCTION of royalty (in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.40#the end even to its decoration and parade-dress). The essential thing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.41#however, in a good and healthy aristocracy is that it should not regard
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.42#itself as a function either of the kingship or the commonwealth, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.43#as the SIGNIFICANCE and highest justification thereof--that it should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.44#therefore accept with a good conscience the sacrifice of a legion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.45#of individuals, who, FOR ITS SAKE, must be suppressed and reduced to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.46#imperfect men, to slaves and instruments. Its fundamental belief must
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.47#be precisely that society is NOT allowed to exist for its own sake, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.48#only as a foundation and scaffolding, by means of which a select class
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.49#of beings may be able to elevate themselves to their higher duties, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.50#in general to a higher EXISTENCE: like those sun-seeking climbing plants
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.51#in Java--they are called Sipo Matador,--which encircle an oak so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.52#long and so often with their arms, until at last, high above it, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.53#supported by it, they can unfold their tops in the open light, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.54#exhibit their happiness.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.55#259. To refrain mutually from injury, from violence, from exploitation,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.56#and put one's will on a par with that of others: this may result in a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.57#certain rough sense in good conduct among individuals when the necessary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.58#conditions are given (namely, the actual similarity of the individuals
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.59#in amount of force and degree of worth, and their co-relation within one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.60#organization). As soon, however, as one wished to take this principle
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.61#more generally, and if possible even as the FUNDAMENTAL PRINCIPLE OF
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.62#SOCIETY, it would immediately disclose what it really is--namely, a Will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.63#to the DENIAL of life, a principle of dissolution and decay. Here one
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.64#must think profoundly to the very basis and resist all sentimental
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.65#weakness: life itself is ESSENTIALLY appropriation, injury, conquest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.66#of the strange and weak, suppression, severity, obtrusion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.67#peculiar forms, incorporation, and at the least, putting it mildest,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.68#exploitation;--but why should one for ever use precisely these words
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.69#on which for ages a disparaging purpose has been stamped? Even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.70#organization within which, as was previously supposed, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.71#individuals treat each other as equal--it takes place in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.72#healthy aristocracy--must itself, if it be a living and not a dying
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.73#organization, do all that towards other bodies, which the individuals
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.74#within it refrain from doing to each other it will have to be the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.75#incarnated Will to Power, it will endeavour to grow, to gain ground,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.76#attract to itself and acquire ascendancy--not owing to any morality or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.77#immorality, but because it LIVES, and because life IS precisely Will to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.78#Power. On no point, however, is the ordinary consciousness of Europeans
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.79#more unwilling to be corrected than on this matter, people now rave
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.80#everywhere, even under the guise of science, about coming conditions of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.81#society in which "the exploiting character" is to be absent--that sounds
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.82#to my ears as if they promised to invent a mode of life which should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.83#refrain from all organic functions. "Exploitation" does not belong to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.84#depraved, or imperfect and primitive society it belongs to the nature of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.85#the living being as a primary organic function, it is a consequence
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.86#of the intrinsic Will to Power, which is precisely the Will to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.87#Life--Granting that as a theory this is a novelty--as a reality it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.88#the FUNDAMENTAL FACT of all history let us be so far honest towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.89#ourselves!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.90#260. In a tour through the many finer and coarser moralities which have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.91#hitherto prevailed or still prevail on the earth, I found certain traits
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.92#recurring regularly together, and connected with one another, until
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.93#finally two primary types revealed themselves to me, and a radical
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.94#distinction was brought to light. There is MASTER-MORALITY and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.95#SLAVE-MORALITY,--I would at once add, however, that in all higher and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.96#mixed civilizations, there are also attempts at the reconciliation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.97#the two moralities, but one finds still oftener the confusion and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.98#mutual misunderstanding of them, indeed sometimes their close
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.99#juxtaposition--even in the same man, within one soul. The distinctions
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.100#of moral values have either originated in a ruling caste, pleasantly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.101#conscious of being different from the ruled--or among the ruled class,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.102#the slaves and dependents of all sorts. In the first case, when it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.103#the rulers who determine the conception "good," it is the exalted, proud
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.104#disposition which is regarded as the distinguishing feature, and that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.105#which determines the order of rank. The noble type of man separates
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.106#from himself the beings in whom the opposite of this exalted, proud
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.107#disposition displays itself he despises them. Let it at once be noted
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.108#that in this first kind of morality the antithesis "good" and "bad"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.109#means practically the same as "noble" and "despicable",--the antithesis
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.110#"good" and "EVIL" is of a different origin. The cowardly, the timid, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.111#insignificant, and those thinking merely of narrow utility are despised;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.112#moreover, also, the distrustful, with their constrained glances, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.113#self-abasing, the dog-like kind of men who let themselves be abused,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.114#the mendicant flatterers, and above all the liars:--it is a fundamental
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.115#belief of all aristocrats that the common people are untruthful. "We
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.116#truthful ones"--the nobility in ancient Greece called themselves. It is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.117#obvious that everywhere the designations of moral value were at first
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.118#applied to MEN; and were only derivatively and at a later period applied
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.119#to ACTIONS; it is a gross mistake, therefore, when historians of morals
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.120#start with questions like, "Why have sympathetic actions been praised?"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.121#The noble type of man regards HIMSELF as a determiner of values; he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.122#does not require to be approved of; he passes the judgment: "What is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.123#injurious to me is injurious in itself;" he knows that it is he himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.124#only who confers honour on things; he is a CREATOR OF VALUES. He
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.125#honours whatever he recognizes in himself: such morality equals
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.126#self-glorification. In the foreground there is the feeling of plenitude,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.127#of power, which seeks to overflow, the happiness of high tension, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.128#consciousness of a wealth which would fain give and bestow:--the noble
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.129#man also helps the unfortunate, but not--or scarcely--out of pity, but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.130#rather from an impulse generated by the super-abundance of power. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.131#noble man honours in himself the powerful one, him also who has power
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.132#over himself, who knows how to speak and how to keep silence, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.133#takes pleasure in subjecting himself to severity and hardness, and has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.134#reverence for all that is severe and hard. "Wotan placed a hard heart in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.135#my breast," says an old Scandinavian Saga: it is thus rightly expressed
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.136#from the soul of a proud Viking. Such a type of man is even proud of not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.137#being made for sympathy; the hero of the Saga therefore adds warningly:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.138#"He who has not a hard heart when young, will never have one." The noble
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.139#and brave who think thus are the furthest removed from the morality
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.140#which sees precisely in sympathy, or in acting for the good of others,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.141#or in DESINTERESSEMENT, the characteristic of the moral; faith
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.142#in oneself, pride in oneself, a radical enmity and irony towards
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.143#"selflessness," belong as definitely to noble morality, as do a careless
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.144#scorn and precaution in presence of sympathy and the "warm heart."--It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.145#is the powerful who KNOW how to honour, it is their art, their domain
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.146#for invention. The profound reverence for age and for tradition--all law
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.147#rests on this double reverence,--the belief and prejudice in favour of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.148#ancestors and unfavourable to newcomers, is typical in the morality of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.149#the powerful; and if, reversely, men of "modern ideas" believe almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.150#instinctively in "progress" and the "future," and are more and more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.151#lacking in respect for old age, the ignoble origin of these "ideas" has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.152#complacently betrayed itself thereby. A morality of the ruling class,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.153#however, is more especially foreign and irritating to present-day taste
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.154#in the sternness of its principle that one has duties only to one's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.155#equals; that one may act towards beings of a lower rank, towards all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.156#that is foreign, just as seems good to one, or "as the heart desires,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.157#and in any case "beyond good and evil": it is here that sympathy and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.158#similar sentiments can have a place. The ability and obligation to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.159#exercise prolonged gratitude and prolonged revenge--both only within the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.160#circle of equals,--artfulness in retaliation, RAFFINEMENT of the idea
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.161#in friendship, a certain necessity to have enemies (as outlets for the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.162#emotions of envy, quarrelsomeness, arrogance--in fact, in order to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.163#a good FRIEND): all these are typical characteristics of the noble
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.164#morality, which, as has been pointed out, is not the morality of "modern
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.165#ideas," and is therefore at present difficult to realize, and also to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.166#unearth and disclose.--It is otherwise with the second type of morality,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.167#SLAVE-MORALITY. Supposing that the abused, the oppressed, the suffering,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.168#the unemancipated, the weary, and those uncertain of themselves should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.169#moralize, what will be the common element in their moral estimates?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.170#Probably a pessimistic suspicion with regard to the entire situation of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.171#man will find expression, perhaps a condemnation of man, together with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.172#his situation. The slave has an unfavourable eye for the virtues of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.173#powerful; he has a skepticism and distrust, a REFINEMENT of distrust of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.174#everything "good" that is there honoured--he would fain persuade himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.175#that the very happiness there is not genuine. On the other hand, THOSE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.176#qualities which serve to alleviate the existence of sufferers are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.177#brought into prominence and flooded with light; it is here that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.178#sympathy, the kind, helping hand, the warm heart, patience, diligence,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.179#humility, and friendliness attain to honour; for here these are the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.180#useful qualities, and almost the only means of supporting the burden of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.181#existence. Slave-morality is essentially the morality of utility.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.182#Here is the seat of the origin of the famous antithesis "good" and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.183#"evil":--power and dangerousness are assumed to reside in the evil,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.184#a certain dreadfulness, subtlety, and strength, which do not admit of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.185#being despised. According to slave-morality, therefore, the "evil" man
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.186#arouses fear; according to master-morality, it is precisely the "good"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.187#man who arouses fear and seeks to arouse it, while the bad man is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.188#regarded as the despicable being. The contrast attains its maximum when,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.189#in accordance with the logical consequences of slave-morality, a shade
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.190#of depreciation--it may be slight and well-intentioned--at last attaches
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.191#itself to the "good" man of this morality; because, according to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.192#servile mode of thought, the good man must in any case be the SAFE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.193#man: he is good-natured, easily deceived, perhaps a little stupid, un
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.194#bonhomme. Everywhere that slave-morality gains the ascendancy, language
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.195#shows a tendency to approximate the significations of the words "good"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.196#and "stupid."--A last fundamental difference: the desire for FREEDOM,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.197#the instinct for happiness and the refinements of the feeling of liberty
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.198#belong as necessarily to slave-morals and morality, as artifice and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.199#enthusiasm in reverence and devotion are the regular symptoms of an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.200#aristocratic mode of thinking and estimating.--Hence we can understand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.201#without further detail why love AS A PASSION--it is our European
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.202#specialty--must absolutely be of noble origin; as is well known, its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.203#invention is due to the Provencal poet-cavaliers, those brilliant,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.204#ingenious men of the "gai saber," to whom Europe owes so much, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.205#almost owes itself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.206#261. Vanity is one of the things which are perhaps most difficult for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.207#a noble man to understand: he will be tempted to deny it, where another
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.208#kind of man thinks he sees it self-evidently. The problem for him is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.209#to represent to his mind beings who seek to arouse a good opinion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.210#themselves which they themselves do not possess--and consequently also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.211#do not "deserve,"--and who yet BELIEVE in this good opinion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.212#afterwards. This seems to him on the one hand such bad taste and so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.213#self-disrespectful, and on the other hand so grotesquely unreasonable,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.214#that he would like to consider vanity an exception, and is doubtful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.215#about it in most cases when it is spoken of. He will say, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.216#instance: "I may be mistaken about my value, and on the other hand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.217#may nevertheless demand that my value should be acknowledged by others
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.218#precisely as I rate it:--that, however, is not vanity (but self-conceit,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.219#or, in most cases, that which is called 'humility,' and also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.220#'modesty')." Or he will even say: "For many reasons I can delight in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.221#the good opinion of others, perhaps because I love and honour them,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.222#and rejoice in all their joys, perhaps also because their good opinion
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.223#endorses and strengthens my belief in my own good opinion, perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.224#because the good opinion of others, even in cases where I do not share
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.225#it, is useful to me, or gives promise of usefulness:--all this, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.226#is not vanity." The man of noble character must first bring it home
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.227#forcibly to his mind, especially with the aid of history, that, from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.228#time immemorial, in all social strata in any way dependent, the ordinary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.229#man WAS only that which he PASSED FOR:--not being at all accustomed to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.230#fix values, he did not assign even to himself any other value than that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.231#which his master assigned to him (it is the peculiar RIGHT OF MASTERS to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.232#create values). It may be looked upon as the result of an extraordinary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.233#atavism, that the ordinary man, even at present, is still always WAITING
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.234#for an opinion about himself, and then instinctively submitting himself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.235#to it; yet by no means only to a "good" opinion, but also to a bad
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.236#and unjust one (think, for instance, of the greater part of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.237#self-appreciations and self-depreciations which believing women learn
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.238#from their confessors, and which in general the believing Christian
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.239#learns from his Church). In fact, conformably to the slow rise of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.240#democratic social order (and its cause, the blending of the blood
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.241#of masters and slaves), the originally noble and rare impulse of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.242#the masters to assign a value to themselves and to "think well" of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.243#themselves, will now be more and more encouraged and extended; but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.244#it has at all times an older, ampler, and more radically ingrained
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.245#propensity opposed to it--and in the phenomenon of "vanity" this older
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.246#propensity overmasters the younger. The vain person rejoices over EVERY
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.247#good opinion which he hears about himself (quite apart from the point
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.248#of view of its usefulness, and equally regardless of its truth or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.249#falsehood), just as he suffers from every bad opinion: for he subjects
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.250#himself to both, he feels himself subjected to both, by that oldest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.251#instinct of subjection which breaks forth in him.--It is "the slave"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.252#in the vain man's blood, the remains of the slave's craftiness--and how
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.253#much of the "slave" is still left in woman, for instance!--which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.254#seeks to SEDUCE to good opinions of itself; it is the slave, too, who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.255#immediately afterwards falls prostrate himself before these opinions, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.256#though he had not called them forth.--And to repeat it again: vanity is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.257#an atavism.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.258#262. A SPECIES originates, and a type becomes established and strong in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.259#the long struggle with essentially constant UNFAVOURABLE conditions. On
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.260#the other hand, it is known by the experience of breeders that species
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.261#which receive super-abundant nourishment, and in general a surplus of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.262#protection and care, immediately tend in the most marked way to develop
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.263#variations, and are fertile in prodigies and monstrosities (also in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.264#monstrous vices). Now look at an aristocratic commonwealth, say
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.265#an ancient Greek polis, or Venice, as a voluntary or involuntary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.266#contrivance for the purpose of REARING human beings; there are there men
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.267#beside one another, thrown upon their own resources, who want to make
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.268#their species prevail, chiefly because they MUST prevail, or else
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.269#run the terrible danger of being exterminated. The favour, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.270#super-abundance, the protection are there lacking under which variations
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.271#are fostered; the species needs itself as species, as something which,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.272#precisely by virtue of its hardness, its uniformity, and simplicity of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.273#structure, can in general prevail and make itself permanent in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.274#constant struggle with its neighbours, or with rebellious or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.275#rebellion-threatening vassals. The most varied experience teaches it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.276#what are the qualities to which it principally owes the fact that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.277#it still exists, in spite of all Gods and men, and has hitherto been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.278#victorious: these qualities it calls virtues, and these virtues alone
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.279#it develops to maturity. It does so with severity, indeed it desires
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.280#severity; every aristocratic morality is intolerant in the education
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.281#of youth, in the control of women, in the marriage customs, in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.282#relations of old and young, in the penal laws (which have an eye only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.283#for the degenerating): it counts intolerance itself among the virtues,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.284#under the name of "justice." A type with few, but very marked features,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.285#a species of severe, warlike, wisely silent, reserved, and reticent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.286#men (and as such, with the most delicate sensibility for the charm and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.287#nuances of society) is thus established, unaffected by the vicissitudes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.288#of generations; the constant struggle with uniform UNFAVOURABLE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.289#conditions is, as already remarked, the cause of a type becoming
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.290#stable and hard. Finally, however, a happy state of things results, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.291#enormous tension is relaxed; there are perhaps no more enemies among the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.292#neighbouring peoples, and the means of life, even of the enjoyment
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.293#of life, are present in superabundance. With one stroke the bond and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.294#constraint of the old discipline severs: it is no longer regarded as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.295#necessary, as a condition of existence--if it would continue, it can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.296#only do so as a form of LUXURY, as an archaizing TASTE. Variations,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.297#whether they be deviations (into the higher, finer, and rarer), or
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.298#deteriorations and monstrosities, appear suddenly on the scene in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.299#greatest exuberance and splendour; the individual dares to be individual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.300#and detach himself. At this turning-point of history there manifest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.301#themselves, side by side, and often mixed and entangled together, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.302#magnificent, manifold, virgin-forest-like up-growth and up-striving, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.303#kind of TROPICAL TEMPO in the rivalry of growth, and an extraordinary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.304#decay and self-destruction, owing to the savagely opposing and seemingly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.305#exploding egoisms, which strive with one another "for sun and light,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.306#and can no longer assign any limit, restraint, or forbearance for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.307#themselves by means of the hitherto existing morality. It was this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.308#morality itself which piled up the strength so enormously, which bent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.309#the bow in so threatening a manner:--it is now "out of date," it is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.310#getting "out of date." The dangerous and disquieting point has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.311#reached when the greater, more manifold, more comprehensive life IS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.312#LIVED BEYOND the old morality; the "individual" stands out, and is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.313#obliged to have recourse to his own law-giving, his own arts and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.314#artifices for self-preservation, self-elevation, and self-deliverance.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.315#Nothing but new "Whys," nothing but new "Hows," no common formulas any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.316#longer, misunderstanding and disregard in league with each other, decay,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.317#deterioration, and the loftiest desires frightfully entangled, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.318#genius of the race overflowing from all the cornucopias of good and bad,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.319#a portentous simultaneousness of Spring and Autumn, full of new charms
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.320#and mysteries peculiar to the fresh, still inexhausted, still unwearied
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.321#corruption. Danger is again present, the mother of morality, great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.322#danger; this time shifted into the individual, into the neighbour and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.323#friend, into the street, into their own child, into their own heart,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.324#into all the most personal and secret recesses of their desires and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.325#volitions. What will the moral philosophers who appear at this time have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.326#to preach? They discover, these sharp onlookers and loafers, that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.327#end is quickly approaching, that everything around them decays and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.328#produces decay, that nothing will endure until the day after tomorrow,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.329#except one species of man, the incurably MEDIOCRE. The mediocre alone
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.330#have a prospect of continuing and propagating themselves--they will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.331#be the men of the future, the sole survivors; "be like them! become
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.332#mediocre!" is now the only morality which has still a significance,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.333#which still obtains a hearing.--But it is difficult to preach this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.334#morality of mediocrity! it can never avow what it is and what it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.335#desires! it has to talk of moderation and dignity and duty and brotherly
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.336#love--it will have difficulty IN CONCEALING ITS IRONY!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.337#263. There is an INSTINCT FOR RANK, which more than anything else is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.338#already the sign of a HIGH rank; there is a DELIGHT in the NUANCES
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.339#of reverence which leads one to infer noble origin and habits. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.340#refinement, goodness, and loftiness of a soul are put to a perilous test
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.341#when something passes by that is of the highest rank, but is not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.342#yet protected by the awe of authority from obtrusive touches and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.343#incivilities: something that goes its way like a living touchstone,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.344#undistinguished, undiscovered, and tentative, perhaps voluntarily veiled
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.345#and disguised. He whose task and practice it is to investigate souls,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.346#will avail himself of many varieties of this very art to determine the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.347#ultimate value of a soul, the unalterable, innate order of rank to which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.348#it belongs: he will test it by its INSTINCT FOR REVERENCE. DIFFERENCE
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.349#ENGENDRE HAINE: the vulgarity of many a nature spurts up suddenly like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.350#dirty water, when any holy vessel, any jewel from closed shrines, any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.351#book bearing the marks of great destiny, is brought before it; while
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.352#on the other hand, there is an involuntary silence, a hesitation of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.353#eye, a cessation of all gestures, by which it is indicated that a soul
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.354#FEELS the nearness of what is worthiest of respect. The way in which, on
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.355#the whole, the reverence for the BIBLE has hitherto been maintained
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.356#in Europe, is perhaps the best example of discipline and refinement of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.357#manners which Europe owes to Christianity: books of such profoundness
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.358#and supreme significance require for their protection an external
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.359#tyranny of authority, in order to acquire the PERIOD of thousands of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.360#years which is necessary to exhaust and unriddle them. Much has been
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.361#achieved when the sentiment has been at last instilled into the masses
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.362#(the shallow-pates and the boobies of every kind) that they are not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.363#allowed to touch everything, that there are holy experiences before
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.364#which they must take off their shoes and keep away the unclean hand--it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.365#is almost their highest advance towards humanity. On the contrary, in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.366#the so-called cultured classes, the believers in "modern ideas," nothing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.367#is perhaps so repulsive as their lack of shame, the easy insolence of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.368#eye and hand with which they touch, taste, and finger everything; and it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.369#is possible that even yet there is more RELATIVE nobility of taste, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.370#more tact for reverence among the people, among the lower classes of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.371#the people, especially among peasants, than among the newspaper-reading
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.372#DEMIMONDE of intellect, the cultured class.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.373#264. It cannot be effaced from a man's soul what his ancestors have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.374#preferably and most constantly done: whether they were perhaps diligent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.375#economizers attached to a desk and a cash-box, modest and citizen-like
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.376#in their desires, modest also in their virtues; or whether they were
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.377#accustomed to commanding from morning till night, fond of rude pleasures
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.378#and probably of still ruder duties and responsibilities; or whether,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.379#finally, at one time or another, they have sacrificed old privileges of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.380#birth and possession, in order to live wholly for their faith--for their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.381#"God,"--as men of an inexorable and sensitive conscience, which blushes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.382#at every compromise. It is quite impossible for a man NOT to have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.383#the qualities and predilections of his parents and ancestors in his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.384#constitution, whatever appearances may suggest to the contrary. This is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.385#the problem of race. Granted that one knows something of the parents,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.386#it is admissible to draw a conclusion about the child: any kind
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.387#of offensive incontinence, any kind of sordid envy, or of clumsy
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.388#self-vaunting--the three things which together have constituted the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.389#genuine plebeian type in all times--such must pass over to the child, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.390#surely as bad blood; and with the help of the best education and culture
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.391#one will only succeed in DECEIVING with regard to such heredity.--And
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.392#what else does education and culture try to do nowadays! In our very
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.393#democratic, or rather, very plebeian age, "education" and "culture" MUST
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.394#be essentially the art of deceiving--deceiving with regard to origin,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.395#with regard to the inherited plebeianism in body and soul. An educator
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.396#who nowadays preached truthfulness above everything else, and called out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.397#constantly to his pupils: "Be true! Be natural! Show yourselves as you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.398#are!"--even such a virtuous and sincere ass would learn in a short time
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.399#to have recourse to the FURCA of Horace, NATURAM EXPELLERE: with what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.400#results? "Plebeianism" USQUE RECURRET. [FOOTNOTE: Horace's "Epistles,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.401#I. x. 24.]
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.402#265. At the risk of displeasing innocent ears, I submit that egoism
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.403#belongs to the essence of a noble soul, I mean the unalterable belief
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.404#that to a being such as "we," other beings must naturally be in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.405#subjection, and have to sacrifice themselves. The noble soul accepts the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.406#fact of his egoism without question, and also without consciousness of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.407#harshness, constraint, or arbitrariness therein, but rather as something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.408#that may have its basis in the primary law of things:--if he sought a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.409#designation for it he would say: "It is justice itself." He acknowledges
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.410#under certain circumstances, which made him hesitate at first, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.411#there are other equally privileged ones; as soon as he has settled this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.412#question of rank, he moves among those equals and equally privileged
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.413#ones with the same assurance, as regards modesty and delicate respect,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.414#which he enjoys in intercourse with himself--in accordance with an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.415#innate heavenly mechanism which all the stars understand. It is an
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.416#ADDITIONAL instance of his egoism, this artfulness and self-limitation
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.417#in intercourse with his equals--every star is a similar egoist; he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.418#honours HIMSELF in them, and in the rights which he concedes to them, he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.419#has no doubt that the exchange of honours and rights, as the ESSENCE of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.420#all intercourse, belongs also to the natural condition of things. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.421#noble soul gives as he takes, prompted by the passionate and sensitive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.422#instinct of requital, which is at the root of his nature. The notion of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.423#"favour" has, INTER PARES, neither significance nor good repute; there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.424#may be a sublime way of letting gifts as it were light upon one from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.425#above, and of drinking them thirstily like dew-drops; but for those
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.426#arts and displays the noble soul has no aptitude. His egoism hinders him
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.427#here: in general, he looks "aloft" unwillingly--he looks either FORWARD,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.428#horizontally and deliberately, or downwards--HE KNOWS THAT HE IS ON A
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.429#HEIGHT.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.430#266. "One can only truly esteem him who does not LOOK OUT FOR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.431#himself."--Goethe to Rath Schlosser.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.432#267. The Chinese have a proverb which mothers even teach their children:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.433#"SIAO-SIN" ("MAKE THY HEART SMALL"). This is the essentially fundamental
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.434#tendency in latter-day civilizations. I have no doubt that an ancient
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.435#Greek, also, would first of all remark the self-dwarfing in us Europeans
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.436#of today--in this respect alone we should immediately be "distasteful"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.437#to him.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.438#268. What, after all, is ignobleness?--Words are vocal symbols for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.439#ideas; ideas, however, are more or less definite mental symbols
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.440#for frequently returning and concurring sensations, for groups of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.441#sensations. It is not sufficient to use the same words in order to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.442#understand one another: we must also employ the same words for the same
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.443#kind of internal experiences, we must in the end have experiences IN
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.444#COMMON. On this account the people of one nation understand one another
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.445#better than those belonging to different nations, even when they use
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.446#the same language; or rather, when people have lived long together under
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.447#similar conditions (of climate, soil, danger, requirement, toil) there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.448#ORIGINATES therefrom an entity that "understands itself"--namely, a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.449#nation. In all souls a like number of frequently recurring experiences
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.450#have gained the upper hand over those occurring more rarely: about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.451#these matters people understand one another rapidly and always more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.452#rapidly--the history of language is the history of a process of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.453#abbreviation; on the basis of this quick comprehension people always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.454#unite closer and closer. The greater the danger, the greater is the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.455#need of agreeing quickly and readily about what is necessary; not to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.456#misunderstand one another in danger--that is what cannot at all be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.457#dispensed with in intercourse. Also in all loves and friendships one has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.458#the experience that nothing of the kind continues when the discovery
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.459#has been made that in using the same words, one of the two parties has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.460#feelings, thoughts, intuitions, wishes, or fears different from those of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.461#the other. (The fear of the "eternal misunderstanding": that is the good
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.462#genius which so often keeps persons of different sexes from too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.463#hasty attachments, to which sense and heart prompt them--and NOT some
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.464#Schopenhauerian "genius of the species"!) Whichever groups of sensations
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.465#within a soul awaken most readily, begin to speak, and give the word of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.466#command--these decide as to the general order of rank of its values, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.467#determine ultimately its list of desirable things. A man's estimates of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.468#value betray something of the STRUCTURE of his soul, and wherein it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.469#sees its conditions of life, its intrinsic needs. Supposing now that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.470#necessity has from all time drawn together only such men as could
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.471#express similar requirements and similar experiences by similar symbols,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.472#it results on the whole that the easy COMMUNICABILITY of need,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.473#which implies ultimately the undergoing only of average and COMMON
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.474#experiences, must have been the most potent of all the forces which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.475#have hitherto operated upon mankind. The more similar, the more ordinary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.476#people, have always had and are still having the advantage; the more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.477#select, more refined, more unique, and difficultly comprehensible, are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.478#liable to stand alone; they succumb to accidents in their isolation, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.479#seldom propagate themselves. One must appeal to immense opposing forces,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.480#in order to thwart this natural, all-too-natural PROGRESSUS IN SIMILE,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.481#the evolution of man to the similar, the ordinary, the average, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.482#gregarious--to the IGNOBLE--!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.483#269. The more a psychologist--a born, an unavoidable psychologist
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.484#and soul-diviner--turns his attention to the more select cases and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.485#individuals, the greater is his danger of being suffocated by sympathy:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.486#he NEEDS sternness and cheerfulness more than any other man. For
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.487#the corruption, the ruination of higher men, of the more unusually
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.488#constituted souls, is in fact, the rule: it is dreadful to have such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.489#rule always before one's eyes. The manifold torment of the psychologist
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.490#who has discovered this ruination, who discovers once, and then
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.491#discovers ALMOST repeatedly throughout all history, this universal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.492#inner "desperateness" of higher men, this eternal "too late!" in every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.493#sense--may perhaps one day be the cause of his turning with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.494#bitterness against his own lot, and of his making an attempt at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.495#self-destruction--of his "going to ruin" himself. One may perceive
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.496#in almost every psychologist a tell-tale inclination for delightful
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.497#intercourse with commonplace and well-ordered men; the fact is thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.498#disclosed that he always requires healing, that he needs a sort
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.499#of flight and forgetfulness, away from what his insight and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.500#incisiveness--from what his "business"--has laid upon his conscience.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.501#The fear of his memory is peculiar to him. He is easily silenced by the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.502#judgment of others; he hears with unmoved countenance how people honour,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.503#admire, love, and glorify, where he has PERCEIVED--or he even conceals
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.504#his silence by expressly assenting to some plausible opinion. Perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.505#the paradox of his situation becomes so dreadful that, precisely
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.506#where he has learnt GREAT SYMPATHY, together with great CONTEMPT, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.507#multitude, the educated, and the visionaries, have on their part learnt
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.508#great reverence--reverence for "great men" and marvelous animals, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.509#the sake of whom one blesses and honours the fatherland, the earth, the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.510#dignity of mankind, and one's own self, to whom one points the young,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.511#and in view of whom one educates them. And who knows but in all great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.512#instances hitherto just the same happened: that the multitude worshipped
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.513#a God, and that the "God" was only a poor sacrificial animal! SUCCESS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.514#has always been the greatest liar--and the "work" itself is a success;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.515#the great statesman, the conqueror, the discoverer, are disguised in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.516#their creations until they are unrecognizable; the "work" of the artist,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.517#of the philosopher, only invents him who has created it, is REPUTED
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.518#to have created it; the "great men," as they are reverenced, are poor
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.519#little fictions composed afterwards; in the world of historical values
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.520#spurious coinage PREVAILS. Those great poets, for example, such as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.521#Byron, Musset, Poe, Leopardi, Kleist, Gogol (I do not venture to mention
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.522#much greater names, but I have them in my mind), as they now appear, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.523#were perhaps obliged to be: men of the moment, enthusiastic, sensuous,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.524#and childish, light-minded and impulsive in their trust and distrust;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.525#with souls in which usually some flaw has to be concealed; often taking
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.526#revenge with their works for an internal defilement, often seeking
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.527#forgetfulness in their soaring from a too true memory, often lost in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.528#the mud and almost in love with it, until they become like the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.529#Will-o'-the-Wisps around the swamps, and PRETEND TO BE stars--the people
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.530#then call them idealists,--often struggling with protracted disgust,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.531#with an ever-reappearing phantom of disbelief, which makes them cold,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.532#and obliges them to languish for GLORIA and devour "faith as it is"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.533#out of the hands of intoxicated adulators:--what a TORMENT these great
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.534#artists are and the so-called higher men in general, to him who has once
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.535#found them out! It is thus conceivable that it is just from woman--who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.536#is clairvoyant in the world of suffering, and also unfortunately eager
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.537#to help and save to an extent far beyond her powers--that THEY have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.538#learnt so readily those outbreaks of boundless devoted SYMPATHY, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.539#the multitude, above all the reverent multitude, do not understand,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.540#and overwhelm with prying and self-gratifying interpretations. This
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.541#sympathizing invariably deceives itself as to its power; woman would
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.542#like to believe that love can do EVERYTHING--it is the SUPERSTITION
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.543#peculiar to her. Alas, he who knows the heart finds out how poor,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.544#helpless, pretentious, and blundering even the best and deepest love
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.545#is--he finds that it rather DESTROYS than saves!--It is possible that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.546#under the holy fable and travesty of the life of Jesus there is hidden
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.547#one of the most painful cases of the martyrdom of KNOWLEDGE ABOUT LOVE:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.548#the martyrdom of the most innocent and most craving heart, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.549#never had enough of any human love, that DEMANDED love, that demanded
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.550#inexorably and frantically to be loved and nothing else, with terrible
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.551#outbursts against those who refused him their love; the story of a poor
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.552#soul insatiated and insatiable in love, that had to invent hell to send
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.553#thither those who WOULD NOT love him--and that at last, enlightened
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.554#about human love, had to invent a God who is entire love, entire
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.555#CAPACITY for love--who takes pity on human love, because it is so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.556#paltry, so ignorant! He who has such sentiments, he who has such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.557#KNOWLEDGE about love--SEEKS for death!--But why should one deal with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.558#such painful matters? Provided, of course, that one is not obliged to do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.559#so.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.560#270. The intellectual haughtiness and loathing of every man who has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.561#suffered deeply--it almost determines the order of rank HOW deeply men
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.562#can suffer--the chilling certainty, with which he is thoroughly imbued
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.563#and coloured, that by virtue of his suffering he KNOWS MORE than the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.564#shrewdest and wisest can ever know, that he has been familiar with,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.565#and "at home" in, many distant, dreadful worlds of which "YOU know
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.566#nothing"!--this silent intellectual haughtiness of the sufferer, this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.567#pride of the elect of knowledge, of the "initiated," of the almost
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.568#sacrificed, finds all forms of disguise necessary to protect itself from
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.569#contact with officious and sympathizing hands, and in general from all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.570#that is not its equal in suffering. Profound suffering makes noble:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.571#it separates.--One of the most refined forms of disguise is Epicurism,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.572#along with a certain ostentatious boldness of taste, which takes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.573#suffering lightly, and puts itself on the defensive against all that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.574#is sorrowful and profound. They are "gay men" who make use of gaiety,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.575#because they are misunderstood on account of it--they WISH to be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.576#misunderstood. There are "scientific minds" who make use of science,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.577#because it gives a gay appearance, and because scientificness leads to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.578#the conclusion that a person is superficial--they WISH to mislead to a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.579#false conclusion. There are free insolent minds which would fain conceal
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.580#and deny that they are broken, proud, incurable hearts (the cynicism of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.581#Hamlet--the case of Galiani); and occasionally folly itself is the mask
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.582#of an unfortunate OVER-ASSURED knowledge.--From which it follows that it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.583#is the part of a more refined humanity to have reverence "for the mask,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.584#and not to make use of psychology and curiosity in the wrong place.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.585#271. That which separates two men most profoundly is a different sense
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.586#and grade of purity. What does it matter about all their honesty and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.587#reciprocal usefulness, what does it matter about all their mutual
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.588#good-will: the fact still remains--they "cannot smell each other!" The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.589#highest instinct for purity places him who is affected with it in the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.590#most extraordinary and dangerous isolation, as a saint: for it is just
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.591#holiness--the highest spiritualization of the instinct in question. Any
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.592#kind of cognizance of an indescribable excess in the joy of the bath,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.593#any kind of ardour or thirst which perpetually impels the soul out
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.594#of night into the morning, and out of gloom, out of "affliction" into
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.595#clearness, brightness, depth, and refinement:--just as much as such a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.596#tendency DISTINGUISHES--it is a noble tendency--it also SEPARATES.--The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.597#pity of the saint is pity for the FILTH of the human, all-too-human.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.598#And there are grades and heights where pity itself is regarded by him as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.599#impurity, as filth.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.600#272. Signs of nobility: never to think of lowering our duties to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.601#rank of duties for everybody; to be unwilling to renounce or to share
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.602#our responsibilities; to count our prerogatives, and the exercise of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.603#them, among our DUTIES.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.604#273. A man who strives after great things, looks upon every one whom
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.605#he encounters on his way either as a means of advance, or a delay and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.606#hindrance--or as a temporary resting-place. His peculiar lofty BOUNTY
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.607#to his fellow-men is only possible when he attains his elevation and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.608#dominates. Impatience, and the consciousness of being always condemned
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.609#to comedy up to that time--for even strife is a comedy, and conceals the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.610#end, as every means does--spoil all intercourse for him; this kind of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.611#man is acquainted with solitude, and what is most poisonous in it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.612#274. THE PROBLEM OF THOSE WHO WAIT.--Happy chances are necessary, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.613#many incalculable elements, in order that a higher man in whom the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.614#solution of a problem is dormant, may yet take action, or "break forth,"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.615#as one might say--at the right moment. On an average it DOES NOT happen;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.616#and in all corners of the earth there are waiting ones sitting who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.617#hardly know to what extent they are waiting, and still less that they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.618#wait in vain. Occasionally, too, the waking call comes too late--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.619#chance which gives "permission" to take action--when their best youth,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.620#and strength for action have been used up in sitting still; and how many
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.621#a one, just as he "sprang up," has found with horror that his limbs are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.622#benumbed and his spirits are now too heavy! "It is too late," he has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.623#said to himself--and has become self-distrustful and henceforth for ever
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.624#useless.--In the domain of genius, may not the "Raphael without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.625#hands" (taking the expression in its widest sense) perhaps not be the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.626#exception, but the rule?--Perhaps genius is by no means so rare: but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.627#rather the five hundred HANDS which it requires in order to tyrannize
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.628#over the [GREEK INSERTED HERE], "the right time"--in order to take
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.629#chance by the forelock!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.630#275. He who does not WISH to see the height of a man, looks all the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.631#more sharply at what is low in him, and in the foreground--and thereby
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.632#betrays himself.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.633#276. In all kinds of injury and loss the lower and coarser soul is
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.634#better off than the nobler soul: the dangers of the latter must be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.635#greater, the probability that it will come to grief and perish is in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.636#fact immense, considering the multiplicity of the conditions of its
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.637#existence.--In a lizard a finger grows again which has been lost; not so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.638#in man.--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.639#277. It is too bad! Always the old story! When a man has finished
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.640#building his house, he finds that he has learnt unawares something
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.641#which he OUGHT absolutely to have known before he--began to build. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.642#eternal, fatal "Too late!" The melancholia of everything COMPLETED--!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.643#278.--Wanderer, who art thou? I see thee follow thy path without scorn,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.644#without love, with unfathomable eyes, wet and sad as a plummet which has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.645#returned to the light insatiated out of every depth--what did it seek
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.646#down there?--with a bosom that never sighs, with lips that conceal their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.647#loathing, with a hand which only slowly grasps: who art thou? what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.648#hast thou done? Rest thee here: this place has hospitality for every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.649#one--refresh thyself! And whoever thou art, what is it that now pleases
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.650#thee? What will serve to refresh thee? Only name it, whatever I have
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.651#I offer thee! "To refresh me? To refresh me? Oh, thou prying one,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.652#what sayest thou! But give me, I pray thee---" What? what? Speak out!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.653#"Another mask! A second mask!"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.654#279. Men of profound sadness betray themselves when they are happy: they
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.655#have a mode of seizing upon happiness as though they would choke and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.656#strangle it, out of jealousy--ah, they know only too well that it will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.657#flee from them!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.658#280. "Bad! Bad! What? Does he not--go back?" Yes! But you misunderstand
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.659#him when you complain about it. He goes back like every one who is about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.660#to make a great spring.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.661#281.--"Will people believe it of me? But I insist that they believe it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.662#of me: I have always thought very unsatisfactorily of myself and about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.663#myself, only in very rare cases, only compulsorily, always without
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.664#delight in 'the subject,' ready to digress from 'myself,' and always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.665#without faith in the result, owing to an unconquerable distrust of the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.666#POSSIBILITY of self-knowledge, which has led me so far as to feel a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.667#CONTRADICTIO IN ADJECTO even in the idea of 'direct knowledge' which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.668#theorists allow themselves:--this matter of fact is almost the most
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.669#certain thing I know about myself. There must be a sort of repugnance
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.670#in me to BELIEVE anything definite about myself.--Is there perhaps
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.671#some enigma therein? Probably; but fortunately nothing for my own
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.672#teeth.--Perhaps it betrays the species to which I belong?--but not to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.673#myself, as is sufficiently agreeable to me."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.674#282.--"But what has happened to you?"--"I do not know," he said,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.675#hesitatingly; "perhaps the Harpies have flown over my table."--It
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.676#sometimes happens nowadays that a gentle, sober, retiring man becomes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.677#suddenly mad, breaks the plates, upsets the table, shrieks, raves,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.678#and shocks everybody--and finally withdraws, ashamed, and raging at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.679#himself--whither? for what purpose? To famish apart? To suffocate with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.680#his memories?--To him who has the desires of a lofty and dainty soul,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.681#and only seldom finds his table laid and his food prepared, the danger
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.682#will always be great--nowadays, however, it is extraordinarily so.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.683#Thrown into the midst of a noisy and plebeian age, with which he does
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.684#not like to eat out of the same dish, he may readily perish of hunger
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.685#and thirst--or, should he nevertheless finally "fall to," of sudden
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.686#nausea.--We have probably all sat at tables to which we did not belong;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.687#and precisely the most spiritual of us, who are most difficult to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.688#nourish, know the dangerous DYSPEPSIA which originates from a sudden
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.689#insight and disillusionment about our food and our messmates--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.690#AFTER-DINNER NAUSEA.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.691#283. If one wishes to praise at all, it is a delicate and at the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.692#same time a noble self-control, to praise only where one DOES NOT
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.693#agree--otherwise in fact one would praise oneself, which is contrary
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.694#to good taste:--a self-control, to be sure, which offers excellent
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.695#opportunity and provocation to constant MISUNDERSTANDING. To be able to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.696#allow oneself this veritable luxury of taste and morality, one must
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.697#not live among intellectual imbeciles, but rather among men whose
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.698#misunderstandings and mistakes amuse by their refinement--or one will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.699#have to pay dearly for it!--"He praises me, THEREFORE he acknowledges me
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.700#to be right"--this asinine method of inference spoils half of the life
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.701#of us recluses, for it brings the asses into our neighbourhood and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.702#friendship.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.703#284. To live in a vast and proud tranquility; always beyond... To have,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.704#or not to have, one's emotions, one's For and Against, according to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.705#choice; to lower oneself to them for hours; to SEAT oneself on them as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.706#upon horses, and often as upon asses:--for one must know how to make
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.707#use of their stupidity as well as of their fire. To conserve one's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.708#three hundred foregrounds; also one's black spectacles: for there are
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.709#circumstances when nobody must look into our eyes, still less into our
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.710#"motives." And to choose for company that roguish and cheerful vice,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.711#politeness. And to remain master of one's four virtues, courage,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.712#insight, sympathy, and solitude. For solitude is a virtue with us, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.713#a sublime bent and bias to purity, which divines that in the contact of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.714#man and man--"in society"--it must be unavoidably impure. All society
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.715#makes one somehow, somewhere, or sometime--"commonplace."
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.716#285. The greatest events and thoughts--the greatest thoughts, however,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.717#are the greatest events--are longest in being comprehended: the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.718#generations which are contemporary with them do not EXPERIENCE such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.719#events--they live past them. Something happens there as in the realm of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.720#stars. The light of the furthest stars is longest in reaching man; and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.721#before it has arrived man DENIES--that there are stars there. "How
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.722#many centuries does a mind require to be understood?"--that is also a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.723#standard, one also makes a gradation of rank and an etiquette therewith,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.724#such as is necessary for mind and for star.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.725#286. "Here is the prospect free, the mind exalted." [FOOTNOTE: Goethe's
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.726#"Faust," Part II, Act V. The words of Dr. Marianus.]--But there is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.727#reverse kind of man, who is also upon a height, and has also a free
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.728#prospect--but looks DOWNWARDS.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.729#287. What is noble? What does the word "noble" still mean for us
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.730#nowadays? How does the noble man betray himself, how is he recognized
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.731#under this heavy overcast sky of the commencing plebeianism, by which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.732#everything is rendered opaque and leaden?--It is not his actions which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.733#establish his claim--actions are always ambiguous, always inscrutable;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.734#neither is it his "works." One finds nowadays among artists and scholars
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.735#plenty of those who betray by their works that a profound longing for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.736#nobleness impels them; but this very NEED of nobleness is radically
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.737#different from the needs of the noble soul itself, and is in fact the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.738#eloquent and dangerous sign of the lack thereof. It is not the works,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.739#but the BELIEF which is here decisive and determines the order of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.740#rank--to employ once more an old religious formula with a new and deeper
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.741#meaning--it is some fundamental certainty which a noble soul has about
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.742#itself, something which is not to be sought, is not to be found, and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.743#perhaps, also, is not to be lost.--THE NOBLE SOUL HAS REVERENCE FOR
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.744#ITSELF.--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.745#288. There are men who are unavoidably intellectual, let them turn
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.746#and twist themselves as they will, and hold their hands before their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.747#treacherous eyes--as though the hand were not a betrayer; it always
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.748#comes out at last that they have something which they hide--namely,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.749#intellect. One of the subtlest means of deceiving, at least as long as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.750#possible, and of successfully representing oneself to be stupider
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.751#than one really is--which in everyday life is often as desirable as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.752#an umbrella,--is called ENTHUSIASM, including what belongs to it, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.753#instance, virtue. For as Galiani said, who was obliged to know it: VERTU
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.754#EST ENTHOUSIASME.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.755#289. In the writings of a recluse one always hears something of the echo
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.756#of the wilderness, something of the murmuring tones and timid vigilance
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.757#of solitude; in his strongest words, even in his cry itself, there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.758#sounds a new and more dangerous kind of silence, of concealment. He who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.759#has sat day and night, from year's end to year's end, alone with his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.760#soul in familiar discord and discourse, he who has become a cave-bear,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.761#or a treasure-seeker, or a treasure-guardian and dragon in his cave--it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.762#may be a labyrinth, but can also be a gold-mine--his ideas themselves
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.763#eventually acquire a twilight-colour of their own, and an odour, as much
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.764#of the depth as of the mould, something uncommunicative and repulsive,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.765#which blows chilly upon every passer-by. The recluse does not believe
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.766#that a philosopher--supposing that a philosopher has always in the first
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.767#place been a recluse--ever expressed his actual and ultimate opinions in
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.768#books: are not books written precisely to hide what is in us?--indeed,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.769#he will doubt whether a philosopher CAN have "ultimate and actual"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.770#opinions at all; whether behind every cave in him there is not, and must
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.771#necessarily be, a still deeper cave: an ampler, stranger, richer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.772#world beyond the surface, an abyss behind every bottom, beneath every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.773#"foundation." Every philosophy is a foreground philosophy--this is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.774#recluse's verdict: "There is something arbitrary in the fact that the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.775#PHILOSOPHER came to a stand here, took a retrospect, and looked around;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.776#that he HERE laid his spade aside and did not dig any deeper--there
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.777#is also something suspicious in it." Every philosophy also CONCEALS a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.778#philosophy; every opinion is also a LURKING-PLACE, every word is also a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.779#MASK.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.780#290. Every deep thinker is more afraid of being understood than of being
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.781#misunderstood. The latter perhaps wounds his vanity; but the former
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.782#wounds his heart, his sympathy, which always says: "Ah, why would you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.783#also have as hard a time of it as I have?"
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.784#291. Man, a COMPLEX, mendacious, artful, and inscrutable animal, uncanny
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.785#to the other animals by his artifice and sagacity, rather than by his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.786#strength, has invented the good conscience in order finally to enjoy his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.787#soul as something SIMPLE; and the whole of morality is a long, audacious
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.788#falsification, by virtue of which generally enjoyment at the sight of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.789#the soul becomes possible. From this point of view there is perhaps much
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.790#more in the conception of "art" than is generally believed.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.791#292. A philosopher: that is a man who constantly experiences, sees,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.792#hears, suspects, hopes, and dreams extraordinary things; who is struck
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.793#by his own thoughts as if they came from the outside, from above and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.794#below, as a species of events and lightning-flashes PECULIAR TO HIM; who
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.795#is perhaps himself a storm pregnant with new lightnings; a portentous
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.796#man, around whom there is always rumbling and mumbling and gaping and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.797#something uncanny going on. A philosopher: alas, a being who often
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.798#runs away from himself, is often afraid of himself--but whose curiosity
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.799#always makes him "come to himself" again.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.800#293. A man who says: "I like that, I take it for my own, and mean to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.801#guard and protect it from every one"; a man who can conduct a case,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.802#carry out a resolution, remain true to an opinion, keep hold of a woman,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.803#punish and overthrow insolence; a man who has his indignation and his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.804#sword, and to whom the weak, the suffering, the oppressed, and even the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.805#animals willingly submit and naturally belong; in short, a man who is a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.806#MASTER by nature--when such a man has sympathy, well! THAT sympathy has
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.807#value! But of what account is the sympathy of those who suffer! Or of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.808#those even who preach sympathy! There is nowadays, throughout almost the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.809#whole of Europe, a sickly irritability and sensitiveness towards pain,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.810#and also a repulsive irrestrainableness in complaining, an effeminizing,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.811#which, with the aid of religion and philosophical nonsense, seeks
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.812#to deck itself out as something superior--there is a regular cult of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.813#suffering. The UNMANLINESS of that which is called "sympathy" by such
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.814#groups of visionaries, is always, I believe, the first thing that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.815#strikes the eye.--One must resolutely and radically taboo this latest
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.816#form of bad taste; and finally I wish people to put the good amulet,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.817#"GAI SABER" ("gay science," in ordinary language), on heart and neck, as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.818#a protection against it.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.819#294. THE OLYMPIAN VICE.--Despite the philosopher who, as a genuine
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.820#Englishman, tried to bring laughter into bad repute in all thinking
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.821#minds--"Laughing is a bad infirmity of human nature, which every
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.822#thinking mind will strive to overcome" (Hobbes),--I would even
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.823#allow myself to rank philosophers according to the quality of their
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.824#laughing--up to those who are capable of GOLDEN laughter. And supposing
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.825#that Gods also philosophize, which I am strongly inclined to believe,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.826#owing to many reasons--I have no doubt that they also know how to laugh
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.827#thereby in an overman-like and new fashion--and at the expense of all
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.828#serious things! Gods are fond of ridicule: it seems that they cannot
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.829#refrain from laughter even in holy matters.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.830#295. The genius of the heart, as that great mysterious one possesses
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.831#it, the tempter-god and born rat-catcher of consciences, whose voice can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.832#descend into the nether-world of every soul, who neither speaks a word
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.833#nor casts a glance in which there may not be some motive or touch
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.834#of allurement, to whose perfection it pertains that he knows how to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.835#appear,--not as he is, but in a guise which acts as an ADDITIONAL
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.836#constraint on his followers to press ever closer to him, to follow him
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.837#more cordially and thoroughly;--the genius of the heart, which imposes
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.838#silence and attention on everything loud and self-conceited, which
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.839#smoothes rough souls and makes them taste a new longing--to lie placid
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.840#as a mirror, that the deep heavens may be reflected in them;--the genius
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.841#of the heart, which teaches the clumsy and too hasty hand to hesitate,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.842#and to grasp more delicately; which scents the hidden and forgotten
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.843#treasure, the drop of goodness and sweet spirituality under thick dark
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.844#ice, and is a divining-rod for every grain of gold, long buried and
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.845#imprisoned in mud and sand; the genius of the heart, from contact with
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.846#which every one goes away richer; not favoured or surprised, not as
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.847#though gratified and oppressed by the good things of others; but richer
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.848#in himself, newer than before, broken up, blown upon, and sounded by a
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.849#thawing wind; more uncertain, perhaps, more delicate, more fragile, more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.850#bruised, but full of hopes which as yet lack names, full of a new will
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.851#and current, full of a new ill-will and counter-current... but what am I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.852#doing, my friends? Of whom am I talking to you? Have I forgotten myself
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.853#so far that I have not even told you his name? Unless it be that you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.854#have already divined of your own accord who this questionable God
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.855#and spirit is, that wishes to be PRAISED in such a manner? For, as it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.856#happens to every one who from childhood onward has always been on his
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.857#legs, and in foreign lands, I have also encountered on my path many
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.858#strange and dangerous spirits; above all, however, and again and again,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.859#the one of whom I have just spoken: in fact, no less a personage than
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.860#the God DIONYSUS, the great equivocator and tempter, to whom, as you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.861#know, I once offered in all secrecy and reverence my first-fruits--the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.862#last, as it seems to me, who has offered a SACRIFICE to him, for I
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.863#have found no one who could understand what I was then doing. In
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.864#the meantime, however, I have learned much, far too much, about the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.865#philosophy of this God, and, as I said, from mouth to mouth--I, the last
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.866#disciple and initiate of the God Dionysus: and perhaps I might at last
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.867#begin to give you, my friends, as far as I am allowed, a little taste of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.868#this philosophy? In a hushed voice, as is but seemly: for it has to do
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.869#with much that is secret, new, strange, wonderful, and uncanny. The
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.870#very fact that Dionysus is a philosopher, and that therefore Gods also
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.871#philosophize, seems to me a novelty which is not unensnaring, and might
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.872#perhaps arouse suspicion precisely among philosophers;--among you, my
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.873#friends, there is less to be said against it, except that it comes too
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.874#late and not at the right time; for, as it has been disclosed to me, you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.875#are loth nowadays to believe in God and gods. It may happen, too, that
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.876#in the frankness of my story I must go further than is agreeable to the
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.877#strict usages of your ears? Certainly the God in question went further,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.878#very much further, in such dialogues, and was always many paces ahead of
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.879#me... Indeed, if it were allowed, I should have to give him, according
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.880#to human usage, fine ceremonious tides of lustre and merit, I should
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.881#have to extol his courage as investigator and discoverer, his fearless
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.882#honesty, truthfulness, and love of wisdom. But such a God does not know
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.883#what to do with all that respectable trumpery and pomp. "Keep that," he
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.884#would say, "for thyself and those like thee, and whoever else require
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.885#it! I--have no reason to cover my nakedness!" One suspects that this
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.886#kind of divinity and philosopher perhaps lacks shame?--He once said:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.887#"Under certain circumstances I love mankind"--and referred thereby to
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.888#Ariadne, who was present; "in my opinion man is an agreeable, brave,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.889#inventive animal, that has not his equal upon earth, he makes his way
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.890#even through all labyrinths. I like man, and often think how I can
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.891#still further advance him, and make him stronger, more evil, and more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.892#profound."--"Stronger, more evil, and more profound?" I asked in horror.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.893#"Yes," he said again, "stronger, more evil, and more profound; also more
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.894#beautiful"--and thereby the tempter-god smiled with his halcyon smile,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.895#as though he had just paid some charming compliment. One here sees at
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.896#once that it is not only shame that this divinity lacks;--and in general
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.897#there are good grounds for supposing that in some things the Gods could
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.898#all of them come to us men for instruction. We men are--more human.--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.899#296. Alas! what are you, after all, my written and painted thoughts! Not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.900#long ago you were so variegated, young and malicious, so full of thorns
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.901#and secret spices, that you made me sneeze and laugh--and now? You
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.902#have already doffed your novelty, and some of you, I fear, are ready
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.903#to become truths, so immortal do they look, so pathetically honest, so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.904#tedious! And was it ever otherwise? What then do we write and paint,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.905#we mandarins with Chinese brush, we immortalisers of things which LEND
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.906#themselves to writing, what are we alone capable of painting? Alas, only
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.907#that which is just about to fade and begins to lose its odour! Alas,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.908#only exhausted and departing storms and belated yellow sentiments! Alas,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.909#only birds strayed and fatigued by flight, which now let themselves be
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.910#captured with the hand--with OUR hand! We immortalize what cannot live
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.911#and fly much longer, things only which are exhausted and mellow! And it
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.912#is only for your AFTERNOON, you, my written and painted thoughts, for
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.913#which alone I have colours, many colours, perhaps, many variegated
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.914#softenings, and fifty yellows and browns and greens and reds;--but
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.915#nobody will divine thereby how ye looked in your morning, you sudden
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.916#sparks and marvels of my solitude, you, my old, beloved--EVIL thoughts!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.917#FROM THE HEIGHTS
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.918#By F W Nietzsche
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.919#Translated by L. A. Magnus
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.920#                       1.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.921#     MIDDAY of Life! Oh, season of delight!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.922#                      My summer's park!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.923#     Uneaseful joy to look, to lurk, to hark--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.924#     I peer for friends, am ready day and night,--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.925#     Where linger ye, my friends? The time is right!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.926#                       2.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.927#     Is not the glacier's grey today for you
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.928#                         Rose-garlanded?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.929#     The brooklet seeks you, wind, cloud, with longing thread
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.930#     And thrust themselves yet higher to the blue,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.931#     To spy for you from farthest eagle's view.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.932#                       3.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.933#     My table was spread out for you on high--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.934#                      Who dwelleth so
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.935#     Star-near, so near the grisly pit below?--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.936#     My realm--what realm hath wider boundary?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.937#     My honey--who hath sipped its fragrancy?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.938#                       4.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.939#     Friends, ye are there! Woe me,--yet I am not
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.940#                        He whom ye seek?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.941#     Ye stare and stop--better your wrath could speak!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.942#     I am not I? Hand, gait, face, changed? And what
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.943#     I am, to you my friends, now am I not?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.944#                       5.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.945#     Am I an other? Strange am I to Me?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.946#                      Yet from Me sprung?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.947#     A wrestler, by himself too oft self-wrung?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.948#     Hindering too oft my own self's potency,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.949#     Wounded and hampered by self-victory?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.950#                       6.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.951#     I sought where-so the wind blows keenest. There
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.952#                     I learned to dwell
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.953#     Where no man dwells, on lonesome ice-lorn fell,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.954#     And unlearned Man and God and curse and prayer?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.955#     Became a ghost haunting the glaciers bare?
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.956#                       7.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.957#     Ye, my old friends! Look! Ye turn pale, filled o'er
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.958#                      With love and fear!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.959#     Go! Yet not in wrath. Ye could ne'er live here.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.960#     Here in the farthest realm of ice and scaur,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.961#     A huntsman must one be, like chamois soar.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.962#                       8.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.963#     An evil huntsman was I? See how taut
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.964#                    My bow was bent!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.965#     Strongest was he by whom such bolt were sent--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.966#     Woe now! That arrow is with peril fraught,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.967#     Perilous as none.--Have yon safe home ye sought!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.968#                       9.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.969#     Ye go! Thou didst endure enough, oh, heart;--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.970#                     Strong was thy hope;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.971#     Unto new friends thy portals widely ope,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.972#     Let old ones be. Bid memory depart!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.973#     Wast thou young then, now--better young thou art!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.974#                       10.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.975#     What linked us once together, one hope's tie--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.976#                    (Who now doth con
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.977#     Those lines, now fading, Love once wrote thereon?)--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.978#     Is like a parchment, which the hand is shy
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.979#     To touch--like crackling leaves, all seared, all dry.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.980#                       11.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.981#     Oh! Friends no more! They are--what name for those?--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.982#                           Friends' phantom-flight
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.983#     Knocking at my heart's window-pane at night,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.984#     Gazing on me, that speaks "We were" and goes,--
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.985#     Oh, withered words, once fragrant as the rose!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.986#                       12.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.987#     Pinings of youth that might not understand!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.988#                       For which I pined,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.989#     Which I deemed changed with me, kin of my kind:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.990#     But they grew old, and thus were doomed and banned:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.991#     None but new kith are native of my land!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.992#                       13.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.993#     Midday of life! My second youth's delight!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.994#                       My summer's park!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.995#     Unrestful joy to long, to lurk, to hark!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.996#     I peer for friends!--am ready day and night,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.997#     For my new friends. Come! Come! The time is right!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.998#                       14.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.999#     This song is done,--the sweet sad cry of rue
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1000#                       Sang out its end;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1001#     A wizard wrought it, he the timely friend,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1002#     The midday-friend,--no, do not ask me who;
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1003#     At midday 'twas, when one became as two.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1004#                       15.
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1005#     We keep our Feast of Feasts, sure of our bourne,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1006#                      Our aims self-same:
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1007#     The Guest of Guests, friend Zarathustra, came!
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1008#     The world now laughs, the grisly veil was torn,
urn:cts:fuTexts:douglase.narrative.mcelvern:9.1009#     And Light and Dark were one that wedding-morn.
